('l30301', 'm303', 'Functions & Scope', E'# Functions & Scope\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nFunctions are the primary abstraction in JavaScript. Scope rules determine where variables are visible.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write function declarations, expressions, and arrow functions\n- Understand lexical scope\n- Use default and rest parameters\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Function Types\n```javascript\n// Declaration (hoisted)\nfunction greet(name) { return `Hello, ${name}!`; }\n\n// Expression\nconst greet = function(name) { return `Hello, ${name}!`; };\n\n// Arrow function\nconst greet = (name) => `Hello, ${name}!`;\nconst double = x => x * 2;\nconst getUser = () => ({ id: 1 }); // Returning object -- wrap in ()\n```\n\n### Parameters\n```javascript\n// Default parameters\nfunction createUser(name, role = "employee", active = true) {\n  return { name, role, active };\n}\n\n// Rest parameters\nfunction sum(...numbers) {\n  return numbers.reduce((total, n) => total + n, 0);\n}\nsum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5); // 15\n\n// Destructuring parameters\nfunction displayUser({ name, email, role = "user" }) {\n  console.log(`${name} (${email}) -- ${role}`);\n}\n```\n\n### Scope\n```javascript\nfunction outer() {\n  let outerVar = "outer";\n  function inner() {\n    let innerVar = "inner";\n    console.log(outerVar); // accessible via closure\n  }\n  // innerVar not accessible here\n}\n```\n\n### this in Functions\n```javascript\nconst obj = {\n  name: "Alice",\n  greet: function() { console.log(this.name); },      // "Alice"\n  greetArrow: () => { console.log(this.name); }       // undefined\n};\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use const arrow functions for callbacks\n- Destructure parameters for objects with 3+ properties\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a function declaration and expression?\n2. Why do arrow functions not have their own this?\n\n## Assignment\nWrite a memoize(fn) higher-order function that caches results and returns cached result on subsequent calls with the same arguments.', 30, 1),

('l30401', 'm304', 'Arrays & Array Methods', E'# Arrays & Array Methods\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nES6+ array methods replace verbose loops with concise, readable data transformations used in every modern codebase.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use map, filter, reduce, find, some, every fluently\n- Transform arrays without mutation\n- Use spread and destructuring\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Core Methods\n```javascript\nconst courses = [\n  { id: 1, title: "HTML5",      category: "Frontend", enrolled: 1200 },\n  { id: 2, title: "JavaScript", category: "Frontend", enrolled: 3500 },\n  { id: 3, title: "Node.js",    category: "Backend",  enrolled: 2100 },\n];\n\nconst titles     = courses.map(c => c.title);\nconst frontend   = courses.filter(c => c.category === "Frontend");\nconst js         = courses.find(c => c.title === "JavaScript");\nconst hasPopular = courses.some(c => c.enrolled > 3000);\nconst allActive  = courses.every(c => c.enrolled > 0);\nconst total      = courses.reduce((sum, c) => sum + c.enrolled, 0);\n```\n\n### Transforming\n```javascript\nconst sorted = [...courses].sort((a, b) => b.enrolled - a.enrolled);\nconst top2   = sorted.slice(0, 2);\n\n// flat and flatMap\n[[1, 2], [3, 4]].flat();                            // [1,2,3,4]\n["hello world"].flatMap(s => s.split(" "));         // ["hello","world"]\n```\n\n### Spread & Destructuring\n```javascript\nconst [first, second, ...rest] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];\nconst combined = [...[1,2], ...[3,4]];\nlet x = 1, y = 2;\n[x, y] = [y, x]; // Swap\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Prefer map/filter/reduce over for loops for data transforms\n- Never mutate arrays directly -- use spread before sorting\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between find and filter?\n2. How does reduce work? What is the accumulator?\n\n## Assignment\nGiven a users array: filter active users, group by department, sort each group by XP descending, return top 3 per department.', 30, 1),

('l30501', 'm305', 'Objects & Destructuring', E'# Objects & Destructuring\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nObjects are the core data structure in JavaScript. Destructuring and spread make working with them concise -- patterns you see in every React codebase.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create and manipulate objects\n- Use destructuring with defaults and renaming\n- Apply spread and Object utility methods\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Object Basics\n```javascript\nconst user = { id: 1, name: "Alice", role: "employee" };\n\nconsole.log(user.name);     // Dot notation\nconsole.log(user["role"]);  // Bracket notation\n\nconst field = "email";\nconst update = { [field]: "new@email.com" }; // Computed property\n```\n\n### Destructuring\n```javascript\nconst { name, email, role = "user", id: userId } = user;\n// role defaults to "user", id renamed to userId\n\nfunction renderUser({ name, role, xp = 0 }) {\n  return `${name} (${role}) -- ${xp} XP`;\n}\n```\n\n### Spread & Immutable Updates\n```javascript\nconst defaults = { theme: "light", language: "en" };\nconst prefs    = { theme: "dark" };\nconst settings = { ...defaults, ...prefs }; // Later wins\n\n// React state pattern -- update without mutating\nconst updated = { ...user, email: "new@email.com" };\n```\n\n### Object Utility Methods\n```javascript\nconst obj = { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 };\nObject.keys(obj)    // ["a","b","c"]\nObject.values(obj)  // [1,2,3]\nObject.entries(obj) // [["a",1],["b",2],["c",3]]\n\n// Reconstruct from entries\nconst doubled = Object.fromEntries(\n  Object.entries(obj).map(([k, v]) => [k, v * 2])\n);\n\n// Optional chaining + nullish coalescing\nconst city = user?.address?.city ?? "Unknown";\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use spread for immutable updates (especially in React)\n- Use optional chaining ?. for nested access\n- Use ?? not || for defaults (|| skips 0 and "")\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between || and ?? for defaults?\n2. How do you update a nested object immutably?\n\n## Assignment\nWrite a deepMerge(target, source) that recursively merges objects without mutating either argument.', 25, 1),

('l30601', 'm306', 'Control Flow & Loops', E'# Control Flow & Loops\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nEvery program needs conditionals and loops. Choosing the right construct leads to more readable code.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use if/else, switch, and ternary correctly\n- Write all loop types and know when to use each\n- Apply short-circuit evaluation\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Conditionals\n```javascript\nif (score >= 90) grade = "A";\nelse if (score >= 80) grade = "B";\nelse grade = "F";\n\n// Ternary\nconst label = isLoggedIn ? "Dashboard" : "Sign In";\n\n// Switch\nswitch (role) {\n  case "admin":    return <AdminDashboard />;\n  case "employee": return <EmployeeDashboard />;\n  default:         return <LandingPage />;\n}\n\n// Short-circuit\nconst name    = user && user.name;\nconst display = name || "Anonymous";\nconst count   = data?.items?.length ?? 0;\n```\n\n### Loops\n```javascript\nfor (let i = 0; i < lessons.length; i++) {\n  console.log(i, lessons[i]);\n}\n\nfor (const lesson of lessons) {\n  if (lesson.completed) continue;\n  if (lesson.locked)    break;\n  await playLesson(lesson);\n}\n\nfor (const key in settings) {\n  if (Object.hasOwn(settings, key)) {\n    console.log(key, settings[key]);\n  }\n}\n\nlet retries = 0;\nwhile (retries < 3) {\n  const result = await fetchData();\n  if (result.ok) break;\n  retries++;\n}\n```\n\n### Labeled Break (nested loops)\n```javascript\nouterLoop:\nfor (let i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++) {\n  for (let j = 0; j < matrix[i].length; j++) {\n    if (matrix[i][j] === target) break outerLoop;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Prefer for...of over for when index not needed\n- Prefer array methods over for for data transforms\n- Avoid for...in on arrays\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between for...in and for...of?\n2. What is short-circuit evaluation?\n\n## Assignment\nWrite throttle(fn, limit) ensuring the function is called at most once per limit milliseconds.', 25, 1),

('l30701', 'm307', 'DOM Manipulation', E'# DOM Manipulation\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nThe DOM is how JavaScript controls what users see. Every dynamic UI element relies on DOM manipulation.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Select elements with querySelector\n- Create, insert, and remove DOM nodes\n- Modify content, attributes, and classes\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Selecting Elements\n```javascript\nconst title  = document.querySelector("h1");\nconst links  = document.querySelectorAll("nav a");\nconst btn    = document.querySelector("#submit-btn");\nconst cards  = [...document.querySelectorAll(".card")];\n```\n\n### Modifying Content\n```javascript\ntitle.textContent = "Welcome!";           // Safe -- no XSS\ntitle.innerHTML   = "<strong>Hi</strong>"; // Parses HTML\n\nimg.setAttribute("src", "new.jpg");\nel.dataset.userId = "123";                 // data-user-id="123"\n```\n\n### Classes & Styles\n```javascript\ncard.classList.add("active");\ncard.classList.remove("loading");\ncard.classList.toggle("expanded");\ncard.classList.contains("active");\n\ncard.style.backgroundColor = "#3b82f6";\ncard.style.transform       = "translateY(-4px)";\n```\n\n### Creating & Inserting\n```javascript\nconst el = document.createElement("div");\nel.className = "course-card";\nel.textContent = "HTML5";\ncontainer.appendChild(el);\n\n// Efficient batch insert with template\ncontainer.insertAdjacentHTML("beforeend",\n  `<div class="card"><h3>${title}</h3></div>`);\n\nel.remove(); // Remove element\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use textContent not innerHTML for user data (XSS prevention)\n- Cache element references -- do not query the DOM repeatedly\n- Use DocumentFragment for batch inserts\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between textContent and innerHTML?\n2. How do you efficiently insert many elements?\n\n## Assignment\nFetch courses from a mock API, render them as cards, add real-time search that updates the DOM without re-fetching.', 30, 1),

('l30801', 'm308', 'Events & Event Handling', E'# Events & Event Handling\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nEvents are how users interact with your page. Understanding bubbling and delegation prevents memory leaks and makes interactions reliable.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Attach and remove event listeners\n- Understand event propagation\n- Use event delegation for dynamic content\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### addEventListener\n```javascript\nconst btn = document.querySelector("#submit");\n\nbtn.addEventListener("click", handleClick);\nfunction handleClick(e) {\n  console.log(e.type, e.target, e.currentTarget);\n}\nbtn.removeEventListener("click", handleClick);\n\nbtn.addEventListener("click", init, { once: true });    // Fire once\ndocument.addEventListener("scroll", onScroll, { passive: true }); // Performance\n```\n\n### Common Events\n```javascript\n// Keyboard\nwindow.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {\n  if (e.key === "Escape") closeModal();\n  if (e.ctrlKey && e.key === "s") e.preventDefault();\n});\n\n// Form\nform.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {\n  e.preventDefault();\n  const data = Object.fromEntries(new FormData(e.target));\n  console.log(data);\n});\n\ninput.addEventListener("input", (e) => console.log(e.target.value));\n```\n\n### Event Propagation\n```\nCapture:  Window -> Body -> div -> button\nBubble:   Window <- Body <- div <- button  (default)\n```\n\n```javascript\nbtn.addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  e.stopPropagation(); // Stop bubbling\n  e.preventDefault();  // Prevent default behavior\n});\n```\n\n### Event Delegation\n```javascript\n// One listener handles all cards (including dynamically added ones)\nconst container = document.querySelector(".course-list");\ncontainer.addEventListener("click", (e) => {\n  const card = e.target.closest(".course-card");\n  if (!card) return;\n  navigateToCourse(card.dataset.courseId);\n});\n```\n\n### Custom Events\n```javascript\nconst evt = new CustomEvent("course-completed", {\n  bubbles: true,\n  detail: { courseId: "c1" }\n});\nelement.dispatchEvent(evt);\n\ndocument.addEventListener("course-completed", (e) => {\n  console.log(e.detail.courseId);\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use delegation for lists and dynamic content\n- Always clean up listeners on component unmount\n- Use { passive: true } on scroll/touch listeners\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is event bubbling and how do you stop it?\n2. What is event delegation and why is it useful?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild an interactive quiz: 5 questions, event delegation for answers, instant feedback per question, final score on submit.', 30, 1),

('l31201', 'm312', 'Error Handling', E'# Error Handling\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nUnhandled errors crash applications. Proper error handling is the mark of production-ready code.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use try/catch/finally correctly\n- Create custom error classes\n- Handle async errors properly\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### try / catch / finally\n```javascript\ntry {\n  const data = JSON.parse(invalidJSON);\n} catch (error) {\n  console.error(error.name, error.message, error.stack);\n} finally {\n  cleanup(); // Always runs\n}\n```\n\n### Custom Error Classes\n```javascript\nclass AppError extends Error {\n  constructor(message, statusCode = 500, code = "INTERNAL_ERROR") {\n    super(message);\n    this.name = "AppError";\n    this.statusCode = statusCode;\n    this.code = code;\n  }\n}\n\nclass NotFoundError extends AppError {\n  constructor(resource) {\n    super(`${resource} not found`, 404, "NOT_FOUND");\n    this.name = "NotFoundError";\n  }\n}\n\nclass ValidationError extends AppError {\n  constructor(field, message) {\n    super(message, 400, "VALIDATION_ERROR");\n    this.field = field;\n  }\n}\n\n// Typed error handling\ntry {\n  await getUser(id);\n} catch (error) {\n  if (error instanceof NotFoundError) {\n    res.status(404).json({ error: error.message });\n  } else {\n    res.status(500).json({ error: "Server error" });\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Async Error Handling\n```javascript\nasync function loadUser(id) {\n  try {\n    const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);\n    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);\n    return await res.json();\n  } catch (error) {\n    console.error("Failed:", error);\n    throw error; // Re-throw for caller\n  }\n}\n\n// Global handlers\nwindow.addEventListener("unhandledrejection", (e) => {\n  console.error("Unhandled rejection:", e.reason);\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Never swallow errors (empty catch blocks)\n- Use custom error classes with statusCode\n- Always clean up in finally\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. When does the finally block NOT run?\n2. How do you handle errors in async/await code?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild an API client with typed errors: NetworkError, AuthError, ValidationError. Each fetch method should catch raw errors and rethrow as typed ones.', 25, 1),

('l31301', 'm313', 'ES6+ Modules', E'# ES6+ Modules\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nModules organize JavaScript code. Every React and Node project uses them. Understanding exports and imports prevents build errors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use named and default exports/imports\n- Create barrel files\n- Use dynamic imports for code splitting\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Named Exports\n```javascript\n// utils/math.js\nexport function add(a, b)    { return a + b; }\nexport function subtract(a, b) { return a - b; }\nexport const PI = 3.14159;\n\n// main.js\nimport { add, subtract, PI } from "./utils/math.js";\nimport { add as sum }        from "./utils/math.js";\nimport * as math             from "./utils/math.js";\n```\n\n### Default Exports\n```javascript\n// Button.jsx\nexport default function Button({ children, onClick }) {\n  return <button onClick={onClick}>{children}</button>;\n}\n\n// Importing\nimport Button from "./Button.jsx";  // any name works\nimport React, { useState } from "react"; // mix default + named\n```\n\n### Barrel Files\n```javascript\n// components/index.js\nexport { default as Button } from "./Button.jsx";\nexport { default as Card }   from "./Card.jsx";\nexport { default as Modal }  from "./Modal.jsx";\n\n// Consumer\nimport { Button, Card, Modal } from "./components";\n```\n\n### Dynamic Imports\n```javascript\nbtn.addEventListener("click", async () => {\n  const { Chart } = await import("./Chart.js");\n  new Chart(data);\n});\n\n// React lazy loading\nconst AdminPage = React.lazy(() => import("./AdminPage.jsx"));\n```\n\n### ES Modules vs CommonJS\n```javascript\n// ES Modules\nimport { x } from "./mod.js";\nexport const y = 1;\n\n// CommonJS (Node.js older style)\nconst { x } = require("./mod.js");\nmodule.exports = { y: 1 };\n\n// Enable ESM in Node: { "type": "module" } in package.json\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Named exports for utilities (better IDE support)\n- Default export for main component of a file\n- Dynamic imports for large rarely-used features\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between named and default exports?\n2. What is a barrel file?\n3. When would you use dynamic import()?\n\n## Assignment\nRefactor a 500-line single-file app into modules. Separate utils, components, API calls, and constants. Create barrel files. No circular dependencies.', 25, 1),

('l31401', 'm314', 'OOP & Classes', E'# OOP & Classes\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nES6 classes provide a clean syntax for object-oriented patterns used by React, Node frameworks, and many libraries.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write ES6 classes with constructors and methods\n- Use class inheritance with extends and super\n- Implement encapsulation with private fields\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Class Syntax\n```javascript\nclass User {\n  #password;\n  #loginAttempts = 0;\n  static count = 0;\n\n  constructor(name, email, password) {\n    this.name = name;\n    this.email = email;\n    this.#password = this.#hash(password);\n    this.xp = 0;\n    User.count++;\n  }\n\n  #hash(p) { return btoa(p); }\n\n  addXP(pts) { this.xp += pts; return this; } // chainable\n\n  get displayName() { return `${this.name} (${this.xp} XP)`; }\n\n  set emailAddress(v) {\n    if (!v.includes("@")) throw new Error("Invalid email");\n    this.email = v;\n  }\n\n  static create(data) { return new User(data.name, data.email, data.password); }\n\n  toJSON() { return { name: this.name, xp: this.xp }; }\n}\n```\n\n### Inheritance\n```javascript\nclass Admin extends User {\n  #permissions;\n\n  constructor(name, email, password, permissions = []) {\n    super(name, email, password);\n    this.role = "admin";\n    this.#permissions = new Set(permissions);\n  }\n\n  hasPermission(p) { return this.#permissions.has(p); }\n\n  greet() { return `${super.greet()} You have admin access.`; }\n}\n\nconst admin = new Admin("Bob", "bob@example.com", "secret", ["users:write"]);\nconsole.log(admin instanceof User);  // true\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use private fields # for true encapsulation\n- Prefer composition over deep inheritance\n- Classes best for stateful entities (User, Cart, EventEmitter)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What are private class fields?\n2. What does super() do?\n3. When would you prefer composition over inheritance?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild an EventEmitter class: on(event, listener), off(event, listener), emit(event, ...args), once(event, listener).', 30, 1),

('l31501', 'm315', 'Closures & Prototypes', E'# Closures & Prototypes\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nClosures and prototypes are the underlying mechanisms of JavaScript. Understanding them separates senior from junior developers.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Explain what a closure is\n- Use closures for data privacy\n- Understand the prototype chain\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Closures\n```javascript\nfunction createCounter(start = 0) {\n  let count = start; // Private\n  return {\n    increment() { count++; },\n    decrement() { count--; },\n    value()     { return count; }\n  };\n}\n\nconst c = createCounter(10);\nc.increment(); c.increment();\nc.value(); // 12 -- count not accessible directly\n```\n\n### Classic Closure Bug\n```javascript\n// Bug: var is function-scoped\nfor (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);\n}\n// 3 3 3\n\n// Fix: let is block-scoped\nfor (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {\n  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);\n}\n// 0 1 2\n```\n\n### Prototype Chain\n```javascript\n// Every object links to its prototype\nconst arr = [1, 2, 3];\n// arr -> Array.prototype -> Object.prototype -> null\n// arr.push comes from Array.prototype\n\nconst animal = {\n  breathe() { return `${this.name} breathes`; }\n};\n\nconst dog = Object.create(animal);\ndog.name = "Rex";\ndog.bark = function() { return "Woof!"; };\n\nconsole.log(dog.breathe()); // inherited from prototype\nconsole.log(dog.bark());    // own method\n\n// class syntax is syntactic sugar over prototypes\nclass Dog extends Animal {} // Dog.prototype.__proto__ = Animal.prototype\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use closures for module pattern and private state\n- Never modify built-in prototypes (Array.prototype.myMethod = ...)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a closure? Give a practical use case.\n2. What is the prototype chain?\n3. What is the difference between __proto__ and prototype?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement createStore(reducer, initialState) using closures: getState(), dispatch(action), subscribe(listener). No classes.', 30, 1),

('l31601', 'm316', 'Functional Programming', E'# Functional Programming in JavaScript\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nFunctional programming produces predictable, testable code. React is built on FP principles: pure components, immutable state, composition.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write pure functions\n- Apply function composition and currying\n- Work with immutable data\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Pure Functions\n```javascript\n// Pure: same input -> same output, no side effects\nconst add    = (a, b) => a + b;\nconst double = x => x * 2;\n\n// Impure: modifies external state\nlet total = 0;\nconst addToTotal = (n) => { total += n; }; // side effect\n```\n\n### Immutability\n```javascript\n// Never mutate -- create new values\nconst user    = { name: "Alice", xp: 100 };\nconst updated = { ...user, xp: user.xp + 50 };\n\nconst nums    = [1, 2, 3];\nconst newNums = [...nums, 4];\nconst sorted  = [...nums].sort();\n```\n\n### Composition\n```javascript\nconst pipe = (...fns) => x => fns.reduce((acc, fn) => fn(acc), x);\n\nconst trim    = s => s.trim();\nconst lower   = s => s.toLowerCase();\nconst words   = s => s.split(" ");\n\nconst process = pipe(trim, lower, words);\nprocess("  Hello World  "); // ["hello", "world"]\n```\n\n### Currying\n```javascript\nconst multiply = a => b => a * b;\nconst double   = multiply(2);\nconst triple   = multiply(3);\ndouble(5); // 10\ntriple(5); // 15\n\n// Practical\nconst filter = predicate => arr => arr.filter(predicate);\nconst map    = transform  => arr => arr.map(transform);\nconst getActive = filter(u => u.active);\nconst getNames  = map(u => u.name);\nconst getActiveNames = pipe(getActive, getNames);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Keep side effects at the edges of your application\n- Name functions clearly -- FP code is self-documenting\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a pure function?\n2. What is currying?\n3. What is the difference between compose and pipe?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a data pipeline with pipe(): filter inactive users, transform to display format, sort by name, paginate. Each step is a pure function.', 25, 1),

('l31701', 'm317', 'Design Patterns in JavaScript', E'# Design Patterns in JavaScript\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDesign patterns are proven solutions to recurring problems. Recognizing and applying them shows engineering maturity.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement Singleton, Observer, Factory, Strategy patterns\n- Recognize patterns in popular libraries\n- Know when to apply each pattern\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Singleton\n```javascript\nclass Config {\n  static #instance = null;\n  #settings = {};\n\n  static getInstance() {\n    if (!Config.#instance) Config.#instance = new Config();\n    return Config.#instance;\n  }\n\n  set(key, value) { this.#settings[key] = value; }\n  get(key)        { return this.#settings[key]; }\n}\nconst config = Config.getInstance(); // Always same object\n```\n\n### Observer Pattern (foundation of all UI frameworks)\n```javascript\nclass EventEmitter {\n  #listeners = new Map();\n\n  on(event, fn) {\n    if (!this.#listeners.has(event)) this.#listeners.set(event, []);\n    this.#listeners.get(event).push(fn);\n    return () => this.off(event, fn);\n  }\n\n  off(event, fn) {\n    this.#listeners.set(event,\n      (this.#listeners.get(event) || []).filter(l => l !== fn));\n  }\n\n  emit(event, ...args) {\n    (this.#listeners.get(event) || []).forEach(l => l(...args));\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Strategy Pattern\n```javascript\nconst byName = data => [...data].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));\nconst byXP   = data => [...data].sort((a, b) => b.xp - a.xp);\n\nclass Sorter {\n  constructor(strategy) { this.strategy = strategy; }\n  sort(data) { return this.strategy(data); }\n}\n\nconst sorter = new Sorter(byXP);\nsorter.sort(users);\nsorter.strategy = byName; // Swap at runtime\n```\n\n### Proxy Pattern\n```javascript\nconst user = new Proxy({}, {\n  get(target, key) { console.log(`Getting ${key}`); return Reflect.get(target, key); },\n  set(target, key, value) {\n    if (key === "xp" && value < 0) throw new RangeError("XP cannot be negative");\n    return Reflect.set(target, key, value);\n  }\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Apply patterns only when they solve a real problem -- not prematurely\n- Observer/Pub-Sub is the foundation of React, Vue, RxJS\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the Observer pattern and where is it used in React?\n2. What are the drawbacks of Singleton?\n3. What is the Strategy pattern?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a state manager with Observer: createStore() holding state, subscriptions, and dispatch triggering listeners. Add undo/redo using Command pattern.', 30, 1)

