('l40201', 'm402', 'Basic Types & Type Annotations', E'# Basic Types & Type Annotations\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nType annotations are how you tell TypeScript what kind of data a variable holds.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Annotate variables, parameters, and return types\n- Use all primitive and special types\n- Use union and literal types\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Primitive Types\n```typescript\nlet name:    string  = "Alice";\nlet age:     number  = 25;\nlet active:  boolean = true;\nlet nothing: null    = null;\n\n// Type inference\nlet city  = "Mumbai"; // string\nlet score = 100;      // number\n```\n\n### Arrays & Tuples\n```typescript\nconst names:  string[]       = ["Alice", "Bob"];\nconst scores: Array<number>  = [95, 87];\n\n// Tuple: fixed-length, fixed-type\nconst point: [number, number]          = [10, 20];\nconst entry: [string, number, boolean] = ["Alice", 25, true];\n```\n\n### Special Types\n```typescript\nlet a: any     = "hello"; a = 42; // no error -- dangerous\nlet b: unknown = getData();\nif (typeof b === "string") b.toUpperCase(); // narrow first\n\nfunction log(msg: string): void { console.log(msg); }\nfunction fail(msg: string): never { throw new Error(msg); }\n```\n\n### Union & Literal Types\n```typescript\nlet id: string | number = "abc";\nid = 123; // also valid\n\ntype Direction = "north" | "south" | "east" | "west";\ntype Role      = "admin" | "mentor" | "employee";\n\nfunction move(dir: Direction) { console.log(`Moving ${dir}`); }\nmove("north"); // OK\nmove("up");    // Error\n```\n\n### Type Assertions\n```typescript\nconst input = document.querySelector("#email") as HTMLInputElement;\nconst el    = document.querySelector(".card")!; // non-null assertion\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Rely on inference -- annotate only where needed\n- Avoid any -- use unknown for truly unknown types\n- Use literal unions for string enums\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between any and unknown?\n2. What is a union type?\n3. What is type inference?\n\n## Assignment\nAnnotate a user management module: User type, CRUD functions with proper types, Role union type.', 25, 1),

('l40301', 'm403', 'Interfaces & Type Aliases', E'# Interfaces & Type Aliases\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nInterfaces and type aliases define object shapes and data contracts -- the foundation of TypeScript.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write interfaces and type aliases\n- Know the differences between them\n- Use optional, readonly properties, and extension\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Interface\n```typescript\ninterface User {\n  readonly id:   number;\n  name:          string;\n  email:         string;\n  role:          "admin" | "mentor" | "employee";\n  avatar?:       string;  // Optional\n  xp:            number;\n}\n\ninterface Admin extends User {\n  permissions: string[];\n}\n\n// Declaration merging (unique to interface)\ninterface User { department?: string; } // merges\n```\n\n### Type Alias\n```typescript\ntype ID     = string | number;\ntype Status = "pending" | "approved" | "rejected";\n\n// Intersection (only with type)\ntype AdminUser = User & { permissions: string[] };\n\n// Computed types\ntype Optional<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };\n```\n\n### Interface vs Type\n| Feature | Interface | Type |\n|---|---|---|\n| Extending | extends | & intersection |\n| Declaration merging | Yes | No |\n| Union/computed types | No | Yes |\n\n### Index Signatures & Readonly\n```typescript\ninterface Config {\n  readonly apiUrl:  string;\n  [key: string]: unknown; // any extra key allowed\n}\n\nconst config: Config = { apiUrl: "/api", debug: true };\nconfig.apiUrl = "x"; // Error: readonly\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Interface for extendable object shapes\n- Type alias for unions, intersections, utility types\n- Readonly for truly immutable properties\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is declaration merging?\n2. When would you use type over interface?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign Course, Module, Lesson, UserProgress interfaces using extends for hierarchy. Add readonly IDs.', 25, 1),

('l40401', 'm404', 'Functions in TypeScript', E'# Functions in TypeScript\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nProperly typed function signatures catch bugs at the call site before runtime.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Type parameters and return values\n- Write optional, default, and rest parameters\n- Type callbacks and HOFs\n- Write function overloads\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Basic Typing\n```typescript\nfunction add(a: number, b: number): number { return a + b; }\nconst multiply = (a: number, b: number): number => a * b;\nfunction log(msg: string): void { console.log(msg); }\nfunction fail(msg: string): never { throw new Error(msg); }\n```\n\n### Optional & Default\n```typescript\nfunction createUser(\n  name:    string,\n  role:    "admin" | "employee" = "employee",\n  active?: boolean\n): User {\n  return { name, role, active: active ?? true };\n}\n```\n\n### Rest & Spread\n```typescript\nfunction sum(...nums: number[]): number {\n  return nums.reduce((a, n) => a + n, 0);\n}\nsum(1, 2, 3, 4);\n```\n\n### Function Types & HOFs\n```typescript\ntype Predicate<T>  = (item: T) => boolean;\ntype Transform<T, U> = (item: T) => U;\n\nfunction filter<T>(arr: T[], pred: Predicate<T>): T[] {\n  return arr.filter(pred);\n}\n\nconst activeUsers = filter(users, u => u.active);\n```\n\n### Overloads\n```typescript\nfunction format(value: string): string;\nfunction format(value: number): string;\nfunction format(value: string | number): string {\n  if (typeof value === "string") return value.trim();\n  return value.toFixed(2);\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always type callback parameters\n- Use generics for reusable HOFs\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a type-safe EventEmitter<Events extends Record<string, any>> where each event name maps to its payload type.', 25, 1),

('l40501', 'm405', 'Classes & OOP in TypeScript', E'# Classes & OOP in TypeScript\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nTypeScript adds access modifiers and abstract classes to JS classes for more powerful OOP.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use public, private, protected, readonly\n- Write abstract classes and implement interfaces\n- Use constructor shorthand\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Access Modifiers\n```typescript\nclass BankAccount {\n  public   owner:     string;\n  private  balance:   number;\n  protected accountNo: string;\n  readonly  createdAt: Date;\n\n  constructor(owner: string, balance: number) {\n    this.owner     = owner;\n    this.balance   = balance;\n    this.accountNo = Math.random().toString(36);\n    this.createdAt = new Date();\n  }\n\n  deposit(amount: number): void {\n    if (amount <= 0) throw new RangeError("Must be positive");\n    this.balance += amount;\n  }\n  getBalance(): number { return this.balance; }\n}\n```\n\n### Constructor Shorthand\n```typescript\nclass User {\n  constructor(\n    public  readonly id:   number,\n    public           name: string,\n    private          email: string,\n    public           xp:   number = 0\n  ) {}\n  getEmail(): string { return this.email; }\n}\n```\n\n### Abstract Classes\n```typescript\nabstract class Shape {\n  abstract area():      number;\n  abstract perimeter(): number;\n  describe(): string {\n    return `Area: ${this.area()}, Perimeter: ${this.perimeter()}`;\n  }\n}\n\nclass Circle extends Shape {\n  constructor(private radius: number) { super(); }\n  area()      { return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2; }\n  perimeter() { return 2 * Math.PI * this.radius; }\n}\n```\n\n### Implementing Interfaces\n```typescript\ninterface Serializable {\n  serialize():            string;\n  deserialize(s: string): this;\n}\n\nclass Product implements Serializable {\n  constructor(public name: string, public price: number) {}\n  serialize() { return JSON.stringify(this); }\n  deserialize(s: string): this { return Object.assign(this, JSON.parse(s)); }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Constructor shorthand reduces boilerplate\n- Prefer private over public for internals\n- Abstract classes for shared behaviour\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between private and #private?\n2. What is an abstract class?\n3. What is the difference between implements and extends?\n\n## Assignment\nShape hierarchy: abstract Shape, Circle, Rectangle, Triangle implementing area() and perimeter(). ShapeRenderer accepts any Shape.', 30, 1),

('l40701', 'm407', 'Utility Types', E'# Utility Types\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nBuilt-in utility types transform existing types without rewriting them -- eliminating duplicate definitions.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use Partial, Required, Readonly, Pick, Omit, Record\n- Use Exclude, Extract, NonNullable, ReturnType\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Object Transformation\n```typescript\ninterface User { id: number; name: string; email: string; xp: number; role: string; }\n\ntype UserUpdate    = Partial<User>;           // all optional\ntype StrictUser    = Required<User>;          // all required\ntype ImmutableUser = Readonly<User>;          // all readonly\ntype UserCard      = Pick<User, "id"|"name"|"role">; // select fields\ntype CreateUser    = Omit<User, "id">;        // exclude id\ntype PublicUser    = Omit<User, "id"|"email">;\n```\n\n### Record & Collection Types\n```typescript\ntype RolePermissions = Record<"admin"|"mentor"|"employee", string[]>;\nconst perms: RolePermissions = {\n  admin:    ["users:write", "courses:write"],\n  mentor:   ["courses:write"],\n  employee: ["courses:read"],\n};\n```\n\n### Type Filtering\n```typescript\ntype A = "a" | "b" | "c";\ntype B = "b" | "c" | "d";\n\ntype OnlyInA = Exclude<A, B>;        // "a"\ntype InBoth  = Extract<A, B>;        // "b" | "c"\n\ntype MaybeStr = string | null | undefined;\ntype DefStr   = NonNullable<MaybeStr>; // string\n```\n\n### Function Utilities\n```typescript\nfunction fetchUser(id: number): Promise<User> { ... }\n\ntype FetchReturn = ReturnType<typeof fetchUser>;   // Promise<User>\ntype FetchParams = Parameters<typeof fetchUser>;  // [number]\ntype UserType    = Awaited<ReturnType<typeof fetchUser>>; // User\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Partial<T> for update DTOs\n- Omit<T, "id"> for creation DTOs\n- Record<string, T> for typed dictionaries\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Difference between Partial and Required?\n2. Difference between Pick and Omit?\n3. What does ReturnType do?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild FormValues<T>, FormErrors<T> (all strings), FormTouched<T> (all booleans) using utility types.', 25, 1),

('l40801', 'm408', 'Advanced Types', E'# Advanced Types\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAdvanced types enable type narrowing, conditional types, and mapped types that power sophisticated library APIs.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use type guards and narrowing\n- Write discriminated unions\n- Use mapped and conditional types\n- Apply template literal types\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Type Guards\n```typescript\nfunction process(value: string | number) {\n  if (typeof value === "string") return value.toUpperCase();\n  return value.toFixed(2);\n}\n\nfunction isUser(obj: unknown): obj is User {\n  return typeof obj === "object" && obj !== null && "id" in obj;\n}\n```\n\n### Discriminated Unions\n```typescript\ntype Success<T> = { status: "success"; data: T };\ntype Failure    = { status: "error";   message: string };\ntype Loading    = { status: "loading" };\ntype Result<T>  = Success<T> | Failure | Loading;\n\nfunction handle<T>(r: Result<T>) {\n  switch (r.status) {\n    case "success": return r.data;\n    case "error":   return r.message;\n    case "loading": return null;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Mapped Types\n```typescript\ntype Nullable<T> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null };\ntype Flags<T>    = { [K in keyof T]: boolean };\ntype UserFlags   = Flags<User>; // all booleans\n```\n\n### Conditional Types\n```typescript\ntype IsString<T>  = T extends string ? true : false;\ntype Unwrap<T>    = T extends Array<infer U> ? U : T;\ntype StrArray     = Unwrap<string[]>; // string\n```\n\n### Template Literal Types\n```typescript\ntype EventName = "click" | "focus" | "blur";\ntype Handler   = `on${Capitalize<EventName>}`;  // "onClick" | "onFocus" | "onBlur"\n\ntype CRUD     = "create" | "read" | "update" | "delete";\ntype Resource = "user" | "course";\ntype Action   = `${CRUD}:${Resource}`; // all combinations\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use discriminated unions for variant types\n- Use type guards to narrow before using specific props\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a discriminated union?\n2. What is the infer keyword?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild Result<T, E> using discriminated unions. Write match(result, handlers) that is fully type-safe.', 30, 1),

('l40901', 'm409', 'Modules & Namespaces', E'# Modules & Namespaces\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nModules organize TypeScript code across files. Understanding resolution prevents build errors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use ES module exports in TypeScript\n- Configure path aliases\n- Write declaration files\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### TypeScript Exports\n```typescript\nexport interface User    { id: number; name: string; }\nexport type Role         = "admin" | "employee";\nexport const MAX_XP      = 10000;\nexport function formatXP(xp: number) { return `${xp} XP`; }\n\nexport default class UserService {\n  async getUser(id: number): Promise<User> {\n    return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());\n  }\n}\n\nexport { User as UserType } from "./types";\nexport * from "./helpers";\n```\n\n### Type-Only Imports\n```typescript\nimport type { User }    from "./types";\nimport { formatXP, type Role } from "./utils";\n```\n\n### Path Aliases (tsconfig.json)\n```json\n{\n  "compilerOptions": {\n    "baseUrl": ".",\n    "paths": {\n      "@/*":           ["src/*"],\n      "@components/*": ["src/components/*"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Declaration Files\n```typescript\n// vendor.d.ts\ndeclare module "some-js-lib" {\n  export function doSomething(v: string): number;\n}\n\n// Augment existing module\ndeclare module "express" {\n  interface Request { user?: User; }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use import type for type-only imports (erased at runtime)\n- Set up path aliases to avoid deep relative paths\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is import type?\n2. What is a .d.ts file?\n\n## Assignment\nSet up path aliases, create barrel files, write a .d.ts for a third-party JS library.', 25, 1),

('l41001', 'm410', 'TypeScript Configuration', E'# TypeScript Configuration\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\ntsconfig.json controls how TypeScript compiles. The right config prevents entire classes of bugs.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand key tsconfig options\n- Enable strict mode\n- Configure for React and Node\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Essential tsconfig.json\n```json\n{\n  "compilerOptions": {\n    "target": "ES2022",\n    "module": "ESNext",\n    "moduleResolution": "Bundler",\n    "lib": ["ES2022", "DOM"],\n    "strict": true,\n    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,\n    "noImplicitReturns": true,\n    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,\n    "esModuleInterop": true,\n    "skipLibCheck": true,\n    "declaration": true,\n    "sourceMap": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### What strict Enables\n```\nstrictNullChecks          -- null not assignable to other types\nstrictFunctionTypes       -- stricter function type checking\nstrictPropertyInitialization -- class props must be initialized\nnoImplicitAny             -- no implicit any types\n```\n\n### strictNullChecks in Practice\n```typescript\nfunction greet(name: string | null) {\n  // name.toUpperCase(); // Error\n  if (name) name.toUpperCase();       // OK after narrow\n  name?.toUpperCase();               // Optional chaining\n  (name ?? "Guest").toUpperCase();   // Nullish coalescing\n}\n```\n\n### React + Vite tsconfig\n```json\n{\n  "compilerOptions": {\n    "target": "ES2020",\n    "lib": ["ES2020", "DOM", "DOM.Iterable"],\n    "module": "ESNext",\n    "moduleResolution": "Bundler",\n    "jsx": "react-jsx",\n    "strict": true,\n    "noUnusedLocals": true,\n    "noUnusedParameters": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always strict: true on new projects\n- Add noUncheckedIndexedAccess for safer array access\n- Separate tsconfig for tests\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What does strict: true enable?\n2. What does strictNullChecks do?\n3. Difference between target and lib?\n\n## Assignment\nConfigure a React + Node monorepo: separate tsconfigs per package, shared base, path aliases, strict mode.', 20, 1),

('l41101', 'm411', 'TypeScript with React', E'# TypeScript with React\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nReact + TypeScript is the dominant frontend stack. Proper typing prevents the majority of React runtime errors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Type components, props, and state\n- Type event handlers\n- Write typed custom hooks\n- Build generic components\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Component Props\n```typescript\nimport { type FC, type ReactNode } from "react";\n\ninterface ButtonProps {\n  children:  ReactNode;\n  onClick?:  () => void;\n  variant?:  "primary" | "secondary" | "danger";\n  disabled?: boolean;\n}\n\nconst Button: FC<ButtonProps> = ({ children, onClick, variant = "primary", disabled = false }) => (\n  <button onClick={onClick} disabled={disabled} className={`btn-${variant}`}>\n    {children}\n  </button>\n);\n```\n\n### State & Refs\n```typescript\nconst [user,    setUser]    = useState<User | null>(null);\nconst [loading, setLoading] = useState(false); // inferred boolean\n\nconst inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);\ninputRef.current?.focus();\n```\n\n### Event Handlers\n```typescript\nconst handleChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => setValue(e.target.value);\nconst handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => { e.preventDefault(); };\nconst handleClick  = (e: React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>) => { e.stopPropagation(); };\nconst handleKey    = (e: React.KeyboardEvent) => { if (e.key === "Enter") submit(); };\n```\n\n### Custom Hook\n```typescript\nfunction useFetch<T>(url: string) {\n  const [data,    setData]    = useState<T | null>(null);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  const [error,   setError]   = useState<string | null>(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetch(url)\n      .then(r => r.json() as Promise<T>)\n      .then(d => { setData(d); setLoading(false); })\n      .catch(e => { setError(e.message); setLoading(false); });\n  }, [url]);\n\n  return { data, loading, error };\n}\n\nconst { data: user, loading } = useFetch<User>(`/api/users/${id}`);\n```\n\n### Generic Components\n```typescript\ninterface ListProps<T> {\n  items:       T[];\n  renderItem:  (item: T) => ReactNode;\n  keyExtractor: (item: T) => string | number;\n}\n\nfunction List<T>({ items, renderItem, keyExtractor }: ListProps<T>) {\n  return <ul>{items.map(item => <li key={keyExtractor(item)}>{renderItem(item)}</li>)}</ul>;\n}\n\n<List items={courses} keyExtractor={c => c.id} renderItem={c => <CourseCard course={c} />} />\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use FC<Props> for explicit props typing\n- Type all event handlers -- never any\n- ReactNode for anything renderable; ReactElement for JSX only\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Difference between ReactNode and ReactElement?\n2. How do you type a ref to an HTML element?\n3. How do you type a generic React component?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a typed DataTable<T>: sortable columns, selectable rows, pagination. Zero implicit any.', 35, 1),

('l41201', 'm412', 'Enterprise TypeScript Patterns', E'# Enterprise TypeScript Patterns\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nLarge TypeScript projects need runtime validation, branded types, and type-safe API clients.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use branded types for domain safety\n- Validate at runtime with Zod\n- Build type-safe API clients\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Branded Types\n```typescript\ntype Brand<T, B> = T & { readonly _brand: B };\ntype UserId   = Brand<number, "UserId">;\ntype CourseId = Brand<string, "CourseId">;\n\nfunction getUser(id: UserId): Promise<User> {\n  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`).then(r => r.json());\n}\nconst userId = 42 as UserId;\ngetUser(userId); // explicit cast required\n```\n\n### Runtime Validation with Zod\n```typescript\nimport { z } from "zod";\n\nconst UserSchema = z.object({\n  id:    z.number().positive(),\n  name:  z.string().min(1).max(100),\n  email: z.string().email(),\n  role:  z.enum(["admin", "mentor", "employee"]),\n  xp:    z.number().min(0).default(0),\n});\n\ntype User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;\n\nconst result = UserSchema.safeParse(apiResponse);\nif (result.success) {\n  const user: User = result.data;\n} else {\n  console.error(result.error.flatten());\n}\n```\n\n### Builder Pattern\n```typescript\nclass QueryBuilder<T> {\n  private q = "";\n  select(fields: (keyof T)[]): this { this.q = `SELECT ${fields.join(", ")}`; return this; }\n  from(table: string): this          { this.q += ` FROM ${table}`;             return this; }\n  where(cond: string): this          { this.q += ` WHERE ${cond}`;             return this; }\n  limit(n: number): this             { this.q += ` LIMIT ${n}`;                return this; }\n  build(): string                    { return this.q; }\n}\n\nconst sql = new QueryBuilder<User>()\n  .select(["id", "name"])\n  .from("users")\n  .where("role = ''employee''")\n  .limit(10)\n  .build();\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Validate all external data at runtime with Zod\n- Generate TS types from your API schema (OpenAPI -> types)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a branded type?\n2. Difference between compile-time and runtime checking?\n3. How does Zod help TypeScript?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a type-safe FormBuilder<T> using Builder pattern where T is the form data type -- field names must match T.', 35, 1)

