('l50201', 'm502', 'JSX & Rendering', E'# JSX & Rendering\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nJSX is how React describes UI. Understanding JSX transforms, expressions, and lists prevents the most common React beginner errors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write valid JSX\n- Render dynamic expressions and lists\n- Use conditional rendering patterns\n- Understand React.Fragment\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### JSX Basics\n```jsx\n// JSX compiles to React.createElement calls\nconst element = <h1 className="title">Hello</h1>;\n// Becomes: React.createElement("h1", { className: "title" }, "Hello")\n\n// JSX rules:\n// 1. Single root element (or Fragment)\n// 2. All tags must close: <img /> not <img>\n// 3. Use className not class\n// 4. Use htmlFor not for\n// 5. CamelCase attributes: onClick, onChange, tabIndex\n```\n\n### Expressions in JSX\n```jsx\nconst name = "Alice";\nconst score = 95;\n\nfunction UserCard({ user }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <h2>{user.name.toUpperCase()}</h2>\n      <p>Score: {score >= 90 ? "Excellent" : "Good"}</p>\n      <p>Joined: {new Date(user.createdAt).toLocaleDateString()}</p>\n      {/* This is a JSX comment */}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Conditional Rendering\n```jsx\nfunction Status({ isLoggedIn, user }) {\n  // Pattern 1: if/else\n  if (!isLoggedIn) return <LoginPage />;\n\n  // Pattern 2: Ternary\n  return (\n    <div>\n      {isLoggedIn ? <Dashboard user={user} /> : <LoginPage />}\n\n      {/* Pattern 3: && (short-circuit) */}\n      {user.isAdmin && <AdminPanel />}\n\n      {/* Pattern 4: Nullish */}\n      {user.avatar ?? <DefaultAvatar />}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Lists & Keys\n```jsx\nfunction CourseList({ courses }) {\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {courses.map(course => (\n        // Key must be unique and stable (not array index for dynamic lists)\n        <li key={course.id}>\n          <CourseCard course={course} />\n        </li>\n      ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n}\n\n// What NOT to do:\ncourses.map((c, index) => <li key={index}>{c.title}</li>); // fragile\n```\n\n### Fragments\n```jsx\n// Fragment avoids extra DOM nodes\nfunction UserInfo({ user }) {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <dt>Name</dt>\n      <dd>{user.name}</dd>\n    </>\n  );\n}\n\n// When you need a key on fragment:\n{items.map(item => (\n  <React.Fragment key={item.id}>\n    <dt>{item.term}</dt>\n    <dd>{item.definition}</dd>\n  </React.Fragment>\n))}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use stable IDs as keys, never array index for sortable/removable lists\n- Prefer ternary for binary conditions, && for show/hide\n- Return null to render nothing\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is JSX and what does it compile to?\n2. Why do list items need keys?\n3. What is a React Fragment?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a dynamic notifications feed: render a list of notifications, conditionally show a badge count, render different notification types differently using discriminated unions.', 25, 1),

('l50301', 'm503', 'Components & Props', E'# Components & Props\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nComponents are the building blocks of React. Good prop design leads to reusable, predictable UI components.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write function components\n- Design props interfaces\n- Pass and receive props including children\n- Understand prop drilling and when to avoid it\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Function Components\n```jsx\n// Basic component\nfunction Greeting({ name }) {\n  return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;\n}\n\n// With TypeScript (preferred)\ninterface CourseCardProps {\n  title:       string;\n  description: string;\n  difficulty:  "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n  duration:    number; // hours\n  enrolled?:   number;\n  onEnroll?:   () => void;\n}\n\nfunction CourseCard({ title, description, difficulty, duration, enrolled = 0, onEnroll }: CourseCardProps) {\n  return (\n    <div className="course-card">\n      <h3>{title}</h3>\n      <p>{description}</p>\n      <span className={`badge badge-${difficulty.toLowerCase()}`}>{difficulty}</span>\n      <p>{duration}h · {enrolled} enrolled</p>\n      {onEnroll && <button onClick={onEnroll}>Enroll</button>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### children Prop\n```jsx\nfunction Card({ children, title, className = "" }) {\n  return (\n    <div className={`card ${className}`}>\n      {title && <div className="card-header"><h3>{title}</h3></div>}\n      <div className="card-body">{children}</div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Usage\n<Card title="Profile">\n  <Avatar src={user.avatar} />\n  <p>{user.name}</p>\n</Card>\n```\n\n### Prop Spreading & Forwarding\n```jsx\nfunction Button({ children, className = "", ...rest }) {\n  return (\n    <button className={`btn ${className}`} {...rest}>\n      {children}\n    </button>\n  );\n}\n\n// ...rest captures onClick, disabled, type, data-testid, etc.\n<Button onClick={handler} disabled={loading} type="submit">\n  Submit\n</Button>\n```\n\n### Component Composition\n```jsx\n// Prefer composition over complex props\nfunction PageLayout({ header, sidebar, children }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="layout">\n      <header>{header}</header>\n      <div className="content">\n        <aside>{sidebar}</aside>\n        <main>{children}</main>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n<PageLayout\n  header={<Navbar />}\n  sidebar={<CourseSidebar />}\n>\n  <CourseContent />\n</PageLayout>\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Keep components small and focused on one thing\n- Lift state up when multiple siblings need it\n- Pass event handlers (not state setters) down as props\n- Use prop spreading for pass-through HTML attributes\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What are props and how do they differ from state?\n2. What is prop drilling?\n3. What is the children prop?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a Design System starter: Button (with variants), Card, Badge, Input components. Each should accept className override and appropriate native HTML attributes via spread.', 30, 1),

('l50501', 'm505', 'Events & Forms in React', E'# Events & Forms in React\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nForms are the primary way users interact with your application. React''s controlled component pattern makes form state predictable.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Handle all common events in React\n- Build controlled and uncontrolled forms\n- Validate forms with proper UX\n- Use the FormData API\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Event Handling\n```jsx\nfunction InteractiveCard() {\n  const handleClick = (e) => {\n    e.stopPropagation();\n    console.log("Card clicked");\n  };\n\n  const handleKeyDown = (e) => {\n    if (e.key === "Enter" || e.key === " ") {\n      handleClick(e);\n    }\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <div\n      role="button"\n      tabIndex={0}\n      onClick={handleClick}\n      onKeyDown={handleKeyDown}\n    >\n      Click me\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Controlled Form\n```jsx\nfunction LoginForm({ onSubmit }) {\n  const [formData, setFormData] = useState({ email: "", password: "" });\n  const [errors, setErrors] = useState({});\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);\n\n  function handleChange(e) {\n    const { name, value } = e.target;\n    setFormData(prev => ({ ...prev, [name]: value }));\n    // Clear error when user types\n    if (errors[name]) setErrors(prev => ({ ...prev, [name]: "" }));\n  }\n\n  function validate() {\n    const errs = {};\n    if (!formData.email.includes("@")) errs.email = "Invalid email";\n    if (formData.password.length < 8) errs.password = "Min 8 characters";\n    return errs;\n  }\n\n  async function handleSubmit(e) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    const errs = validate();\n    if (Object.keys(errs).length) { setErrors(errs); return; }\n    setLoading(true);\n    try {\n      await onSubmit(formData);\n    } finally {\n      setLoading(false);\n    }\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <div>\n        <label htmlFor="email">Email</label>\n        <input\n          id="email"\n          name="email"\n          type="email"\n          value={formData.email}\n          onChange={handleChange}\n          aria-invalid={!!errors.email}\n        />\n        {errors.email && <p role="alert">{errors.email}</p>}\n      </div>\n      <div>\n        <label htmlFor="password">Password</label>\n        <input\n          id="password"\n          name="password"\n          type="password"\n          value={formData.password}\n          onChange={handleChange}\n        />\n        {errors.password && <p role="alert">{errors.password}</p>}\n      </div>\n      <button type="submit" disabled={loading}>\n        {loading ? "Signing in..." : "Sign In"}\n      </button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Uncontrolled Form (FormData API)\n```jsx\nfunction UploadForm({ onUpload }) {\n  function handleSubmit(e) {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    const data = new FormData(e.currentTarget);\n    const values = Object.fromEntries(data);\n    onUpload(values);\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <input name="title" type="text" required />\n      <input name="file" type="file" accept="image/*" />\n      <button type="submit">Upload</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use controlled inputs for validation and dynamic behavior\n- Use uncontrolled (FormData) for simple submit-only forms\n- Always associate labels with inputs via htmlFor/id\n- Show validation errors on blur, not on every keystroke\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between controlled and uncontrolled components?\n2. Why use e.preventDefault() in form submit?\n3. How do you handle multiple inputs with one onChange?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a multi-step registration form: Step 1 (name, email), Step 2 (password, confirm), Step 3 (department, role selection). Validate each step before advancing.', 30, 1),

('l50601', 'm506', 'useEffect & Lifecycle', E'# useEffect & Lifecycle\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nuseEffect is how React components interact with the outside world: fetching data, setting up subscriptions, and managing timers.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use useEffect for data fetching and side effects\n- Understand dependency arrays\n- Clean up effects properly\n- Avoid common useEffect mistakes\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### useEffect Basics\n```jsx\nuseEffect(() => {\n  // Side effect here\n  return () => {\n    // Cleanup (optional)\n  };\n}, [dependencies]); // Dependency array\n\n// Run once on mount:\nuseEffect(() => { fetchData(); }, []);\n\n// Run when id changes:\nuseEffect(() => { fetchUser(id); }, [id]);\n\n// Run after every render (rare -- usually a bug):\nuseEffect(() => { doSomething(); });\n```\n\n### Data Fetching Pattern\n```jsx\nfunction UserProfile({ userId }) {\n  const [user, setUser]       = useState(null);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  const [error, setError]     = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let cancelled = false; // Prevent state update after unmount\n\n    async function load() {\n      try {\n        setLoading(true);\n        const data = await fetchUser(userId);\n        if (!cancelled) setUser(data);\n      } catch (err) {\n        if (!cancelled) setError(err.message);\n      } finally {\n        if (!cancelled) setLoading(false);\n      }\n    }\n\n    load();\n    return () => { cancelled = true; }; // Cleanup\n  }, [userId]);\n\n  if (loading) return <Spinner />;\n  if (error)   return <ErrorMessage message={error} />;\n  return <UserCard user={user} />;\n}\n```\n\n### Subscriptions & Timers\n```jsx\n// Event listener cleanup\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const handler = (e) => setKey(e.key);\n  window.addEventListener("keydown", handler);\n  return () => window.removeEventListener("keydown", handler);\n}, []);\n\n// Interval cleanup\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const interval = setInterval(() => setSeconds(s => s + 1), 1000);\n  return () => clearInterval(interval);\n}, []);\n\n// WebSocket cleanup\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const ws = new WebSocket(url);\n  ws.onmessage = (e) => setMessages(m => [...m, e.data]);\n  return () => ws.close();\n}, [url]);\n```\n\n### Common Mistakes\n```jsx\n// WRONG: Missing dependency\nuseEffect(() => {\n  fetchData(userId); // userId used but not in deps\n}, []); // Stale userId!\n\n// WRONG: Object/array in deps (new reference each render)\nuseEffect(() => { ... }, [{ id: 1 }]); // Runs every render!\n\n// RIGHT: Primitive values in deps\nuseEffect(() => { ... }, [userId, role]); // stable primitives\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always clean up subscriptions, intervals, and async operations\n- Use the cancelled flag pattern for async effects\n- Keep effects focused -- split multiple concerns into multiple useEffects\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What does the dependency array do in useEffect?\n2. How do you prevent memory leaks in useEffect?\n3. Why does useEffect run twice in React 18 Strict Mode?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a live search component: debounced input, fetch results on change, cancel previous requests, loading state, empty state, error handling.', 30, 1),

('l50701', 'm507', 'React Router', E'# React Router\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nReact Router is the standard for client-side routing in React apps. Every multi-page React app uses it.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Set up React Router v6\n- Create nested routes and layouts\n- Use navigation hooks\n- Protect routes with auth guards\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Setup\n```bash\nnpm install react-router-dom\n```\n\n```jsx\n// main.jsx\nimport { BrowserRouter } from "react-router-dom";\n\nReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(\n  <BrowserRouter>\n    <App />\n  </BrowserRouter>\n);\n```\n\n### Defining Routes\n```jsx\nimport { Routes, Route, Navigate } from "react-router-dom";\n\nfunction App() {\n  return (\n    <Routes>\n      <Route path="/" element={<Layout />}>\n        <Route index           element={<Home />} />\n        <Route path="courses"  element={<CourseExplorer />} />\n        <Route path="courses/:id" element={<CourseDetail />} />\n        <Route path="profile"  element={<ProtectedRoute><Profile /></ProtectedRoute>} />\n        <Route path="*"        element={<NotFound />} />\n      </Route>\n    </Routes>\n  );\n}\n\n// Layout with Outlet for nested routes\nfunction Layout() {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Navbar />\n      <Outlet />\n      <Footer />\n    </>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Navigation Hooks\n```jsx\nimport { useNavigate, useParams, useSearchParams, useLocation } from "react-router-dom";\n\nfunction CourseDetail() {\n  const { id }         = useParams();         // Route params\n  const [params]       = useSearchParams();   // ?tab=lessons\n  const navigate       = useNavigate();\n  const location       = useLocation();\n\n  const tab = params.get("tab") ?? "overview";\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <h1>Course {id}</h1>\n      <button onClick={() => navigate("/courses")}>Back</button>\n      <button onClick={() => navigate(-1)}>Go Back</button>\n      <button onClick={() => navigate(`?tab=lessons`)}>Lessons</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Protected Routes\n```jsx\nfunction ProtectedRoute({ children }) {\n  const { user } = useAuth();\n  const location = useLocation();\n\n  if (!user) {\n    // Redirect to login, save intended destination\n    return <Navigate to="/login" state={{ from: location }} replace />;\n  }\n\n  return children;\n}\n\n// After login, redirect to original destination\nfunction LoginPage() {\n  const location = useLocation();\n  const navigate = useNavigate();\n  const from     = location.state?.from?.pathname ?? "/dashboard";\n\n  async function handleLogin(credentials) {\n    await login(credentials);\n    navigate(from, { replace: true });\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Links\n```jsx\nimport { Link, NavLink } from "react-router-dom";\n\n<Link to="/courses">Browse Courses</Link>\n\n// NavLink adds "active" class automatically\n<NavLink to="/courses"\n  className={({ isActive }) => isActive ? "nav-link active" : "nav-link"}\n>\n  Courses\n</NavLink>\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use nested routes for layouts shared across pages\n- Use useNavigate not window.location for programmatic navigation\n- Pass location state for redirect-back patterns\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between Link and NavLink?\n2. How do you pass data between routes?\n3. How do you implement protected routes?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a complete routing setup: public (home, courses, login) and private (dashboard, profile, admin) routes. Admin route restricted to admin role. Redirect to login with return URL.', 30, 1),

('l50801', 'm508', 'Context API', E'# Context API\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nContext solves prop drilling -- sharing data deeply through the component tree without passing props at every level.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create and consume context\n- Combine context with state\n- Know when to use context vs prop drilling vs state management\n- Optimize context re-renders\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Creating Context\n```jsx\nimport { createContext, useContext, useState } from "react";\n\ninterface AuthContextType {\n  user:   User | null;\n  login:  (credentials: Credentials) => Promise<void>;\n  logout: () => void;\n}\n\nconst AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextType | null>(null);\n\n// Custom hook for type safety\nexport function useAuth() {\n  const ctx = useContext(AuthContext);\n  if (!ctx) throw new Error("useAuth must be used within AuthProvider");\n  return ctx;\n}\n```\n\n### Provider\n```jsx\nexport function AuthProvider({ children }) {\n  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);\n\n  async function login(credentials) {\n    const user = await apiLogin(credentials);\n    setUser(user);\n    localStorage.setItem("user", JSON.stringify(user));\n  }\n\n  function logout() {\n    setUser(null);\n    localStorage.removeItem("user");\n  }\n\n  // Restore session on mount\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const saved = localStorage.getItem("user");\n    if (saved) setUser(JSON.parse(saved));\n  }, []);\n\n  return (\n    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, login, logout }}>\n      {children}\n    </AuthContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\n// Wrap app\n<AuthProvider>\n  <App />\n</AuthProvider>\n```\n\n### Consuming Context\n```jsx\nfunction Navbar() {\n  const { user, logout } = useAuth();\n\n  return (\n    <nav>\n      {user ? (\n        <>\n          <span>Hello, {user.name}</span>\n          <button onClick={logout}>Sign Out</button>\n        </>\n      ) : (\n        <Link to="/login">Sign In</Link>\n      )}\n    </nav>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Theme Context Pattern\n```jsx\nconst ThemeContext = createContext<{ theme: string; toggle: () => void } | null>(null);\n\nexport function ThemeProvider({ children }) {\n  const [theme, setTheme] = useState(() =>\n    localStorage.getItem("theme") ?? "light"\n  );\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    document.documentElement.setAttribute("data-theme", theme);\n    localStorage.setItem("theme", theme);\n  }, [theme]);\n\n  const toggle = () => setTheme(t => t === "light" ? "dark" : "light");\n\n  return (\n    <ThemeContext.Provider value={{ theme, toggle }}>\n      {children}\n    </ThemeContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\nexport const useTheme = () => {\n  const ctx = useContext(ThemeContext);\n  if (!ctx) throw new Error("useTheme must be inside ThemeProvider");\n  return ctx;\n};\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Split contexts by concern (auth, theme, cart) -- not one mega-context\n- Memoize context value with useMemo to prevent unnecessary re-renders\n- Create a custom hook for each context\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between Context and Redux?\n2. When does a component re-render due to context?\n3. How do you prevent unnecessary re-renders from context?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a shopping cart using Context: CartProvider with add/remove/clear/total. Show cart count in navbar, cart items in drawer, checkout summary on a separate page.', 30, 1),

('l50901', 'm509', 'Custom Hooks', E'# Custom Hooks\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nCustom hooks let you extract and reuse stateful logic across components without copy-pasting. They are the primary code reuse mechanism in React.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Extract logic into custom hooks\n- Build common utility hooks\n- Compose hooks from other hooks\n- Test custom hooks\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Rules of Custom Hooks\n```\n1. Name must start with "use"\n2. Can call other hooks inside\n3. Logic is shared, NOT state (each component gets its own state)\n```\n\n### Common Custom Hooks\n```jsx\n// useLocalStorage\nfunction useLocalStorage<T>(key: string, defaultValue: T) {\n  const [value, setValue] = useState<T>(() => {\n    try {\n      const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);\n      return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : defaultValue;\n    } catch {\n      return defaultValue;\n    }\n  });\n\n  const setStored = (newValue: T | ((prev: T) => T)) => {\n    const resolved = typeof newValue === "function"\n      ? (newValue as (prev: T) => T)(value)\n      : newValue;\n    setValue(resolved);\n    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(resolved));\n  };\n\n  return [value, setStored] as const;\n}\n\n// useDebounce\nfunction useDebounce<T>(value: T, delay: number): T {\n  const [debounced, setDebounced] = useState(value);\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const timer = setTimeout(() => setDebounced(value), delay);\n    return () => clearTimeout(timer);\n  }, [value, delay]);\n  return debounced;\n}\n\n// useMediaQuery\nfunction useMediaQuery(query: string): boolean {\n  const [matches, setMatches] = useState(\n    () => window.matchMedia(query).matches\n  );\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const mq = window.matchMedia(query);\n    setMatches(mq.matches);\n    const handler = (e: MediaQueryListEvent) => setMatches(e.matches);\n    mq.addEventListener("change", handler);\n    return () => mq.removeEventListener("change", handler);\n  }, [query]);\n  return matches;\n}\n\n// useAsync\nfunction useAsync<T>(asyncFn: () => Promise<T>, deps: unknown[]) {\n  const [state, setState] = useState<{\n    data: T | null; loading: boolean; error: string | null;\n  }>({ data: null, loading: true, error: null });\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    let cancelled = false;\n    setState({ data: null, loading: true, error: null });\n    asyncFn()\n      .then(data => !cancelled && setState({ data, loading: false, error: null }))\n      .catch(err => !cancelled && setState({ data: null, loading: false, error: err.message }));\n    return () => { cancelled = true; };\n  }, deps);\n\n  return state;\n}\n```\n\n### Composing Hooks\n```jsx\nfunction useUserProfile(userId: string) {\n  const isMobile = useMediaQuery("(max-width: 768px)");\n  const { data: user, loading, error } = useAsync(\n    () => fetchUser(userId),\n    [userId]\n  );\n  const [starred, setStarred] = useLocalStorage(`starred-${userId}`, false);\n\n  return { user, loading, error, isMobile, starred, setStarred };\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Each hook should do one thing\n- Prefix with "use" -- React enforces hook rules by this naming\n- Return arrays for value/setter pairs ([value, setter]), objects for 3+ values\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a custom hook and a utility function?\n2. Is state shared between components using the same custom hook?\n3. How do you test custom hooks?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild usePagination(items, pageSize): returns currentPage, totalPages, currentItems, nextPage, prevPage, goToPage. Use it in a course list component.', 30, 1),

('l51001', 'm510', 'API Integration in React', E'# API Integration in React\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nEvery real application fetches data. Handling loading, error, and success states correctly is the difference between a good and bad user experience.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Fetch data with useEffect and React Query\n- Handle loading and error states\n- Mutate data and update UI optimistically\n- Cache and invalidate queries\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Basic Fetch Pattern (useEffect)\n```jsx\nfunction CourseList() {\n  const [courses, setCourses] = useState([]);\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  const [error,   setError]   = useState(null);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetch("/api/courses")\n      .then(r => { if (!r.ok) throw new Error(r.status); return r.json(); })\n      .then(data => { setCourses(data); setLoading(false); })\n      .catch(err => { setError(err.message); setLoading(false); });\n  }, []);\n\n  if (loading) return <SkeletonGrid />;\n  if (error)   return <ErrorAlert message={error} onRetry={() => setLoading(true)} />;\n  return <Grid items={courses} renderItem={c => <CourseCard course={c} />} />;\n}\n```\n\n### React Query (TanStack Query) -- Recommended\n```bash\nnpm install @tanstack/react-query\n```\n\n```jsx\nimport { useQuery, useMutation, useQueryClient } from "@tanstack/react-query";\n\n// Fetch\nconst { data: courses, isLoading, error } = useQuery({\n  queryKey: ["courses"],\n  queryFn:  () => fetch("/api/courses").then(r => r.json()),\n  staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes\n});\n\n// With params\nconst { data: course } = useQuery({\n  queryKey: ["courses", id],\n  queryFn:  () => fetchCourse(id),\n  enabled:  !!id, // Only run if id exists\n});\n\n// Mutation (create/update/delete)\nconst queryClient = useQueryClient();\nconst { mutate: enroll, isPending } = useMutation({\n  mutationFn: (courseId) => fetch(`/api/enroll/${courseId}`, { method: "POST" }),\n  onSuccess: () => {\n    queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ["courses"] });\n    toast.success("Enrolled successfully!");\n  },\n  onError: (err) => toast.error(err.message),\n});\n\n<button onClick={() => enroll(course.id)} disabled={isPending}>\n  {isPending ? "Enrolling..." : "Enroll"}\n</button>\n```\n\n### Optimistic Updates\n```jsx\nconst { mutate: toggleLike } = useMutation({\n  mutationFn: (courseId) => likeApi(courseId),\n  onMutate: async (courseId) => {\n    await queryClient.cancelQueries({ queryKey: ["courses"] });\n    const previous = queryClient.getQueryData(["courses"]);\n    // Optimistically update\n    queryClient.setQueryData(["courses"], old =>\n      old.map(c => c.id === courseId ? { ...c, liked: !c.liked } : c)\n    );\n    return { previous }; // Context for rollback\n  },\n  onError: (err, id, context) => {\n    queryClient.setQueryData(["courses"], context.previous); // Rollback\n  },\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use React Query for any real app (eliminates loading/error boilerplate)\n- Use queryKey arrays to scope caches precisely\n- Invalidate queries after mutations to keep UI fresh\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between staleTime and cacheTime in React Query?\n2. What is an optimistic update?\n3. How do you handle loading and error states in React?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a full CRUD course manager using React Query: list courses, create new course, edit course name, delete course with confirmation. Optimistic delete.', 30, 1),

('l51101', 'm511', 'State Management with Zustand', E'# State Management with Zustand\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nWhen context becomes too heavy and Redux too complex, Zustand offers a simple, scalable state management solution.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create Zustand stores\n- Use slices for organized state\n- Persist state to localStorage\n- Connect stores to React components\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Basic Store\n```bash\nnpm install zustand\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport { create } from "zustand";\n\ninterface CourseStore {\n  courses:       Course[];\n  loading:       boolean;\n  setCourses:    (courses: Course[]) => void;\n  addCourse:     (course: Course) => void;\n  removeCourse:  (id: string) => void;\n  setLoading:    (loading: boolean) => void;\n}\n\nexport const useCourseStore = create<CourseStore>((set) => ({\n  courses:  [],\n  loading:  false,\n  setCourses:   (courses) => set({ courses }),\n  addCourse:    (course)  => set(state => ({ courses: [...state.courses, course] })),\n  removeCourse: (id)      => set(state => ({ courses: state.courses.filter(c => c.id !== id) })),\n  setLoading:   (loading) => set({ loading }),\n}));\n```\n\n### Using the Store\n```jsx\nfunction CourseList() {\n  const { courses, loading, removeCourse } = useCourseStore();\n  // Only re-renders when courses or loading changes\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      {loading && <Spinner />}\n      {courses.map(course => (\n        <CourseCard\n          key={course.id}\n          course={course}\n          onDelete={() => removeCourse(course.id)}\n        />\n      ))}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\n// Select specific slices to minimize re-renders\nconst courseCount = useCourseStore(state => state.courses.length);\n```\n\n### Persisted Store\n```typescript\nimport { create } from "zustand";\nimport { persist } from "zustand/middleware";\n\ninterface UserPreferences {\n  theme:       "light" | "dark";\n  language:    string;\n  sidebarOpen: boolean;\n  setTheme:    (theme: "light" | "dark") => void;\n  toggleSidebar: () => void;\n}\n\nexport const usePreferences = create<UserPreferences>()(\n  persist(\n    (set) => ({\n      theme:        "light",\n      language:     "en",\n      sidebarOpen:  true,\n      setTheme:     (theme) => set({ theme }),\n      toggleSidebar: () => set(state => ({ sidebarOpen: !state.sidebarOpen })),\n    }),\n    { name: "user-preferences" } // localStorage key\n  )\n);\n```\n\n### Zustand vs Redux\n| Feature | Zustand | Redux Toolkit |\n|---|---|---|\n| Boilerplate | Minimal | Moderate |\n| DevTools | Yes | Yes (better) |\n| Middleware | Simple | Rich |\n| Learning curve | Low | Moderate |\n| Best for | Simple-medium apps | Large apps with complex flows |\n\n## Best Practices\n- Keep stores small and focused\n- Use selectors to prevent unnecessary re-renders\n- Persist user preferences but not server data (use React Query for that)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between local state and global state?\n2. When would you use Zustand vs React Query?\n3. How does Zustand compare to Redux?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a notifications system with Zustand: add/dismiss/clear notifications, persist notification preferences, show toast UI connected to the store.', 25, 1),

('l51201', 'm512', 'React Performance Optimization', E'# React Performance Optimization\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nReact is fast by default but slow patterns accumulate. Understanding re-renders and how to prevent unnecessary ones is required for production-grade apps.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Identify unnecessary re-renders\n- Use React.memo, useMemo, useCallback correctly\n- Apply virtualization for long lists\n- Use code splitting and lazy loading\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### When React Re-renders\n```\nA component re-renders when:\n1. Its state changes\n2. Its parent re-renders (even if props unchanged!)\n3. Context it consumes changes\n```\n\n### React.memo\n```jsx\n// Prevents re-render if props haven''t changed (shallow comparison)\nconst CourseCard = React.memo(function CourseCard({ course, onEnroll }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <h3>{course.title}</h3>\n      <button onClick={() => onEnroll(course.id)}>Enroll</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n});\n\n// Custom comparison\nconst CourseCard = React.memo(CourseCardComponent,\n  (prev, next) => prev.course.id === next.course.id && prev.course.updatedAt === next.course.updatedAt\n);\n```\n\n### useMemo & useCallback\n```jsx\nfunction CourseExplorer({ courses, searchTerm }) {\n  // Memoize expensive computation\n  const filteredCourses = useMemo(\n    () => courses.filter(c =>\n      c.title.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm.toLowerCase())\n    ),\n    [courses, searchTerm] // Only recompute when these change\n  );\n\n  // Memoize callback to prevent re-rendering memo children\n  const handleEnroll = useCallback(\n    (courseId) => { enroll(courseId); },\n    [] // Stable reference\n  );\n\n  return (\n    <CourseList\n      courses={filteredCourses}\n      onEnroll={handleEnroll} // Stable reference\n    />\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### List Virtualization\n```bash\nnpm install @tanstack/react-virtual\n```\n\n```jsx\nimport { useVirtualizer } from "@tanstack/react-virtual";\n\nfunction VirtualCourseList({ courses }) {\n  const parentRef = useRef(null);\n  const virtualizer = useVirtualizer({\n    count:       courses.length,\n    getScrollElement: () => parentRef.current,\n    estimateSize: () => 120, // Estimated row height\n  });\n\n  return (\n    <div ref={parentRef} style={{ height: "600px", overflow: "auto" }}>\n      <div style={{ height: virtualizer.getTotalSize() }}>\n        {virtualizer.getVirtualItems().map(item => (\n          <div\n            key={item.key}\n            style={{ position: "absolute", top: item.start, height: item.size }}\n          >\n            <CourseCard course={courses[item.index]} />\n          </div>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n// Renders only visible items -- handles 10,000+ items smoothly\n```\n\n### Code Splitting\n```jsx\nconst AdminPage    = React.lazy(() => import("./pages/AdminPage"));\nconst AnalyticsPage = React.lazy(() => import("./pages/Analytics"));\n\n<Suspense fallback={<PageSkeleton />}>\n  <Routes>\n    <Route path="/admin"     element={<AdminPage />} />\n    <Route path="/analytics" element={<AnalyticsPage />} />\n  </Routes>\n</Suspense>\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Profile before optimizing (React DevTools Profiler)\n- React.memo is for child components that re-render frequently with same props\n- useCallback is only useful when passing callbacks to memo-ized components\n- Virtualize lists longer than 100 items\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between useMemo and useCallback?\n2. When should you use React.memo?\n3. What is virtualization and when do you need it?\n\n## Assignment\nProfile a slow course list (1000 items): identify the bottleneck using React DevTools, apply React.memo, useMemo for filtering, and virtualization. Measure before/after render times.', 30, 1),

('l51301', 'm513', 'Testing React Apps', E'# Testing React Apps\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nTested React components prevent regressions. React Testing Library''s user-centric approach makes tests that reflect real user behavior.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write unit tests with Vitest and React Testing Library\n- Test user interactions and async behavior\n- Mock API calls\n- Write integration tests for forms\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Setup\n```bash\nnpm install -D vitest @testing-library/react @testing-library/user-event @testing-library/jest-dom jsdom\n```\n\n```typescript\n// vite.config.ts\nexport default defineConfig({\n  test: {\n    environment: "jsdom",\n    globals:     true,\n    setupFiles:  ["./src/test/setup.ts"],\n  },\n});\n\n// setup.ts\nimport "@testing-library/jest-dom";\n```\n\n### Component Tests\n```typescript\nimport { render, screen } from "@testing-library/react";\nimport { userEvent }      from "@testing-library/user-event";\nimport { CourseCard }     from "./CourseCard";\n\nconst mockCourse = {\n  id: "1", title: "HTML5 Fundamentals",\n  difficulty: "Beginner", duration: 12, enrolled: 1200\n};\n\ntest("renders course title", () => {\n  render(<CourseCard course={mockCourse} />);\n  expect(screen.getByText("HTML5 Fundamentals")).toBeInTheDocument();\n});\n\ntest("calls onEnroll when button clicked", async () => {\n  const onEnroll = vi.fn();\n  render(<CourseCard course={mockCourse} onEnroll={onEnroll} />);\n  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: /enroll/i }));\n  expect(onEnroll).toHaveBeenCalledWith("1");\n});\n\ntest("shows difficulty badge", () => {\n  render(<CourseCard course={mockCourse} />);\n  expect(screen.getByText("Beginner")).toHaveClass("badge-beginner");\n});\n```\n\n### Testing Forms\n```typescript\ntest("submits login form with valid data", async () => {\n  const onSubmit = vi.fn();\n  render(<LoginForm onSubmit={onSubmit} />);\n\n  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText(/email/i), "alice@example.com");\n  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText(/password/i), "password123");\n  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: /sign in/i }));\n\n  expect(onSubmit).toHaveBeenCalledWith({\n    email: "alice@example.com",\n    password: "password123",\n  });\n});\n\ntest("shows error for invalid email", async () => {\n  render(<LoginForm onSubmit={vi.fn()} />);\n  await userEvent.type(screen.getByLabelText(/email/i), "notanemail");\n  await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button", { name: /sign in/i }));\n  expect(screen.getByRole("alert")).toHaveTextContent("Invalid email");\n});\n```\n\n### Mocking API Calls\n```typescript\nimport { vi } from "vitest";\n\nvi.mock("../api/courses", () => ({\n  fetchCourses: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue([\n    { id: "1", title: "HTML5" },\n    { id: "2", title: "CSS3" },\n  ]),\n}));\n\ntest("loads and displays courses", async () => {\n  render(<CourseList />);\n  expect(screen.getByTestId("skeleton")).toBeInTheDocument();\n  await screen.findByText("HTML5"); // waits for async\n  expect(screen.getAllByRole("listitem")).toHaveLength(2);\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Test behavior, not implementation (query by role/label, not className)\n- Use findBy* for async elements (waits automatically)\n- Mock at the module boundary, not deep inside components\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between getBy, queryBy, and findBy?\n2. Why does React Testing Library discourage testing implementation details?\n3. What is userEvent and how does it differ from fireEvent?\n\n## Assignment\nWrite a full test suite for a LoginForm: valid submit, invalid email error, invalid password error, loading state during submission, server error display.', 30, 1),

('l51401', 'm514', 'Authentication in React', E'# Authentication in React\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAuthentication is in every production app. Implementing it correctly -- with token storage, refresh, and route protection -- is a core skill.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement JWT auth with refresh tokens\n- Store tokens securely\n- Protect routes based on role\n- Handle token expiry automatically\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Auth Context Setup\n```typescript\ninterface AuthState {\n  user:         User | null;\n  accessToken:  string | null;\n  isLoading:    boolean;\n}\n\ninterface AuthContext extends AuthState {\n  login:  (creds: Credentials) => Promise<void>;\n  logout: () => Promise<void>;\n  isAuthenticated: boolean;\n}\n\nexport function AuthProvider({ children }) {\n  const [state, setState] = useState<AuthState>({\n    user: null, accessToken: null, isLoading: true\n  });\n\n  // Restore session on mount\n  useEffect(() => {\n    refreshAccessToken()\n      .then(({ user, token }) => setState({ user, accessToken: token, isLoading: false }))\n      .catch(() => setState({ user: null, accessToken: null, isLoading: false }));\n  }, []);\n\n  async function login(credentials: Credentials) {\n    const { user, accessToken } = await apiLogin(credentials);\n    setState({ user, accessToken, isLoading: false });\n  }\n\n  async function logout() {\n    await apiLogout();\n    setState({ user: null, accessToken: null, isLoading: false });\n  }\n\n  return (\n    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ ...state, login, logout, isAuthenticated: !!state.user }}>\n      {!state.isLoading && children}\n    </AuthContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Token Storage Best Practices\n```\nStorage | XSS Risk | CSRF Risk | Notes\nlocalStorage | HIGH    | None     | Easy to implement -- NOT for sensitive apps\nsessionStorage | HIGH  | None     | Lost on tab close\nHTTP-only cookie | None | Medium  | Best for production -- use with CSRF token\nmemory (useState) | None | None   | Lost on refresh -- use with refresh endpoint\n\nRecommended: Access token in memory + Refresh token in HTTP-only cookie\n```\n\n### API Interceptor with Token\n```typescript\nconst api = axios.create({ baseURL: "/api", withCredentials: true });\n\napi.interceptors.request.use((config) => {\n  const token = useAuthStore.getState().accessToken;\n  if (token) config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${token}`;\n  return config;\n});\n\napi.interceptors.response.use(\n  res => res,\n  async (error) => {\n    if (error.response?.status === 401) {\n      try {\n        const { token } = await refreshAccessToken();\n        useAuthStore.setState({ accessToken: token });\n        return api(error.config); // Retry original request\n      } catch {\n        useAuthStore.getState().logout();\n        window.location.href = "/login";\n      }\n    }\n    return Promise.reject(error);\n  }\n);\n```\n\n### Role-Based Route Protection\n```jsx\nfunction RequireRole({ role, children }) {\n  const { user, isAuthenticated } = useAuth();\n  const location = useLocation();\n\n  if (!isAuthenticated) {\n    return <Navigate to="/login" state={{ from: location }} replace />;\n  }\n\n  if (user.role !== role) {\n    return <Navigate to="/unauthorized" replace />;\n  }\n\n  return children;\n}\n\n<Route path="/admin" element={\n  <RequireRole role="admin"><AdminPage /></RequireRole>\n} />\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Never store JWTs in localStorage for security-sensitive apps\n- Use HTTP-only cookies for refresh tokens\n- Implement automatic token refresh before expiry\n- Show loading state while auth is being determined\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Why is localStorage unsafe for JWT storage?\n2. What is a refresh token and why use it?\n3. How do you implement automatic token refresh?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement complete auth: login with JWT, store access token in memory, refresh token via HTTP-only cookie, auto-refresh on 401, role-based route protection (admin/mentor/employee).', 30, 1),

('l51501', 'm515', 'Deployment & Build Optimization', E'# React Deployment & Build Optimization\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nA fast, optimized build is the last step before users can use your app. Getting deployment right means fast loads, proper caching, and zero-downtime releases.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Optimize Vite builds\n- Configure code splitting\n- Deploy to Vercel/Netlify/S3\n- Set up proper caching headers\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Vite Build Configuration\n```typescript\n// vite.config.ts\nimport { defineConfig } from "vite";\nimport react from "@vitejs/plugin-react";\n\nexport default defineConfig({\n  plugins: [react()],\n  build: {\n    target: "es2020",\n    minify: "esbuild",\n    sourcemap: false, // true for staging\n    rollupOptions: {\n      output: {\n        manualChunks: {\n          vendor:   ["react", "react-dom"],\n          router:   ["react-router-dom"],\n          query:    ["@tanstack/react-query"],\n          ui:       ["@radix-ui/react-dialog", "@radix-ui/react-dropdown-menu"],\n        },\n      },\n    },\n  },\n  resolve: {\n    alias: { "@": "/src" },\n  },\n});\n```\n\n### Analyzing Bundle Size\n```bash\nnpm install -D rollup-plugin-visualizer\n\n# Add to vite.config.ts plugins:\nimport { visualizer } from "rollup-plugin-visualizer";\nplugins: [react(), visualizer({ open: true })]\n\nnpm run build  # Opens bundle visualization\n```\n\n### Environment Variables\n```bash\n# .env.production\nVITE_API_URL=https://api.rlearn.com\nVITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://xxx.supabase.co\nVITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=eyJ...\n```\n\n```typescript\nconst apiUrl = import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL;\n```\n\n### Deploying to Vercel\n```bash\nnpm install -g vercel\nvercel --prod\n\n# vercel.json for SPA routing\n{\n  "rewrites": [{ "source": "/(.*)", "destination": "/" }]\n}\n```\n\n### Deploying to Netlify\n```toml\n# netlify.toml\n[build]\n  command = "npm run build"\n  publish = "dist"\n\n[[redirects]]\n  from = "/*"\n  to = "/index.html"\n  status = 200\n```\n\n### Caching Strategy\n```\nFile type     | Cache Header          | Why\n-----------   | --------              | ---\nindex.html    | no-cache              | Always fresh (entry point)\nassets/*.js   | max-age=31536000      | Content-hashed -- safe to cache forever\nassets/*.css  | max-age=31536000      | Content-hashed\nimages        | max-age=86400         | Cache 1 day\nfonts         | max-age=31536000      | Very stable\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Split vendor and app code (vendors change less often)\n- Use environment variables for all config\n- Enable gzip/brotli compression on server\n- Monitor Core Web Vitals in production (Vercel Analytics, Lighthouse CI)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is code splitting and why does it improve performance?\n2. What is a content hash and why does it help caching?\n3. What is the difference between a SPA and SSR?\n\n## Assignment\nDeploy the R-Learn frontend to Vercel: configure environment variables, split vendor chunks, analyze bundle size, achieve Lighthouse Performance score > 80.', 25, 1)

