('l70101', 'm701', 'Node.js Runtime & Architecture', E'# Node.js Runtime & Architecture\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nUnderstanding what Node.js is and how it works under the hood is essential for writing efficient server-side code.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Explain what Node.js is\n- Understand V8, libuv, and the event loop\n- Know when to use Node.js and when not to\n- Set up a Node.js project\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### What is Node.js?\n```\nNode.js = V8 (JS engine) + libuv (async I/O) + Node APIs\n\nV8:    Compiles JS to machine code\nlibuv: Thread pool, event loop, OS async I/O\nAPIs:  fs, http, path, crypto, etc.\n```\n\n### Setup\n```bash\nnode --version           # Check version\nnpm init -y              # Initialize project\nnode app.js              # Run a file\nnode --watch app.js      # Auto-restart on change (Node 18+)\n```\n\n### First Node.js Server\n```javascript\nconst http = require("http");\n\nconst server = http.createServer((req, res) => {\n  res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });\n  res.end(JSON.stringify({ message: "Hello from Node.js!" }));\n});\n\nserver.listen(3000, () => console.log("Server running on http://localhost:3000"));\n```\n\n### Node.js vs Browser JavaScript\n```\nNode.js:     fs, http, path, crypto, process, __dirname, require()\nBrowser:     DOM, window, document, fetch (native), localStorage\nBoth:        setTimeout, setInterval, Promise, async/await, Map, Set\n```\n\n### Process Object\n```javascript\nconsole.log(process.version);       // Node version\nconsole.log(process.platform);      // "win32", "darwin", "linux"\nconsole.log(process.env.PORT);      // Environment variables\nconsole.log(process.argv);          // Command-line arguments\nconsole.log(process.cwd());         // Current working directory\nconsole.log(__dirname);             // Directory of current file\nconsole.log(__filename);            // Path of current file\n\nprocess.exit(0);  // Exit with success code\nprocess.exit(1);  // Exit with error code\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use Node.js for I/O-heavy tasks (APIs, file processing, real-time)\n- Avoid Node.js for CPU-heavy tasks (video encoding, ML inference)\n- Use process.env for configuration, never hardcode secrets\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between Node.js and the browser JS environment?\n2. What is V8?\n3. What is libuv?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a Node.js CLI tool that reads a directory, lists all .js files recursively, and prints total line count per file.', 20, 1),

('l70201', 'm702', 'Modules & NPM', E'# Modules & NPM in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nNPM manages dependencies for every Node project. Understanding package.json, module systems, and package management prevents version conflicts and security issues.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use CommonJS and ES modules in Node\n- Manage packages with npm\n- Write and publish a package\n- Understand package.json deeply\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### CommonJS Modules\n```javascript\n// Exporting\nfunction add(a, b) { return a + b; }\nconst PI = 3.14;\nmodule.exports = { add, PI };\n\n// Or:\nmodule.exports.add = add;\nmodule.exports.PI  = PI;\n\n// Importing\nconst { add, PI } = require("./math");\nconst fs           = require("fs");      // Core module\nconst express      = require("express"); // npm package\n```\n\n### ES Modules in Node (Modern)\n```json\n// package.json\n{ "type": "module" }\n```\n\n```javascript\n// Now use ES module syntax\nexport const add = (a, b) => a + b;\nexport default function main() {}\n\nimport { add } from "./math.js"; // .js extension required\nimport express from "express";\n```\n\n### package.json Deep Dive\n```json\n{\n  "name":    "my-api",\n  "version": "1.0.0",\n  "type":    "module",\n  "main":    "src/index.js",\n  "scripts": {\n    "start":  "node src/index.js",\n    "dev":    "node --watch src/index.js",\n    "build":  "tsc",\n    "test":   "vitest"\n  },\n  "dependencies": {\n    "express":  "^4.18.0",\n    "zod":      "^3.22.0"\n  },\n  "devDependencies": {\n    "typescript": "^5.0.0",\n    "vitest":     "^1.0.0"\n  },\n  "engines": { "node": ">=18" }\n}\n```\n\n### NPM Commands\n```bash\nnpm install                      # Install all dependencies\nnpm install express              # Add dependency\nnpm install -D typescript        # Add dev dependency\nnpm install -g nodemon           # Install globally\nnpm uninstall lodash             # Remove package\nnpm update                       # Update packages\nnpm outdated                     # Show outdated packages\nnpm audit                        # Security check\nnpm audit fix                    # Auto-fix vulnerabilities\nnpm run dev                      # Run script\nnpm list                         # List installed packages\nnpx create-express-app my-api   # Run without installing\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Commit package-lock.json (reproducible builds)\n- Separate dependencies and devDependencies\n- Set engines field for Node version requirements\n- Audit regularly for security vulnerabilities\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between dependencies and devDependencies?\n2. What does package-lock.json do?\n3. What is the difference between npm install and npx?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild and publish a simple NPM package: a collection of validation utilities (isEmail, isURL, isStrongPassword). Include TypeScript types, tests, and a README.', 25, 1),

('l70301', 'm703', 'The Event Loop in Depth', E'# The Event Loop in Depth\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nThe event loop is the heart of Node.js''s concurrency model. Understanding it explains why Node is fast for I/O and how to avoid blocking it.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Trace code execution through the event loop phases\n- Understand the call stack, task queue, and microtask queue\n- Know the difference between setTimeout, setImmediate, and process.nextTick\n- Identify and fix event loop blocking\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Event Loop Phases\n```\n   ┌─────────────────────────────┐\n   │           timers            │  setTimeout, setInterval callbacks\n   ├─────────────────────────────┤\n   │     pending callbacks       │  I/O errors\n   ├─────────────────────────────┤\n   │       idle, prepare         │  Internal use\n   ├─────────────────────────────┤\n   │           poll              │  Retrieve new I/O events\n   ├─────────────────────────────┤\n   │           check             │  setImmediate callbacks\n   ├─────────────────────────────┤\n   │      close callbacks        │  socket.on("close", ...)\n   └─────────────────────────────┘\n   Between each phase: microtask queue (Promise.then, queueMicrotask)\n```\n\n### Execution Order\n```javascript\nconsole.log("1 - sync");          // 1st\n\nsetTimeout(() => console.log("2 - setTimeout"),  0); // 4th\nsetImmediate(() => console.log("3 - setImmediate")); // 5th\nPromise.resolve().then(() => console.log("4 - microtask")); // 3rd\nprocess.nextTick(() => console.log("5 - nextTick"));        // 2nd\n\nconsole.log("6 - sync end");      // 2nd\n\n// Output: 1, 6, 5, 4, 2, 3\n// Microtasks (nextTick, Promise.then) run before next event loop phase\n```\n\n### Blocking the Event Loop\n```javascript\n// BAD: blocks the event loop -- no other requests served during this\napp.get("/slow", (req, res) => {\n  const result = expensiveCPUComputation(); // blocks for 5 seconds!\n  res.json(result);\n});\n\n// GOOD: use worker threads for CPU-heavy work\nimport { Worker } from "worker_threads";\napp.get("/compute", (req, res) => {\n  const worker = new Worker("./compute-worker.js", { workerData: req.body });\n  worker.on("message", (result) => res.json(result));\n  worker.on("error",   (err)    => res.status(500).json({ error: err.message }));\n});\n\n// GOOD: chunked processing with setImmediate\nasync function processLargeArray(items) {\n  const results = [];\n  for (const item of items) {\n    results.push(processItem(item));\n    if (results.length % 100 === 0) {\n      await new Promise(resolve => setImmediate(resolve)); // Yield\n    }\n  }\n  return results;\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Never run synchronous CPU-heavy operations in the main thread\n- Use worker_threads for CPU-bound work\n- Use setImmediate to yield the event loop in long loops\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the event loop?\n2. What is the difference between process.nextTick and Promise.then?\n3. How does Node.js handle many concurrent connections with one thread?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild an endpoint that processes 1 million items. First do it synchronously (notice it blocks). Then fix it with chunked setImmediate. Measure response time difference.', 30, 1),

('l70401', 'm704', 'File System & Buffers', E'# File System & Buffers\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nFile I/O is one of Node''s primary use cases. Understanding the fs module and Buffers is essential for building file processors, upload handlers, and CLI tools.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Read and write files synchronously and asynchronously\n- Work with directories\n- Understand Buffers for binary data\n- Watch files for changes\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Reading Files\n```javascript\nimport { readFile, readFileSync, readdir, stat } from "fs/promises";\n\n// Async (preferred)\nconst content = await readFile("./data.json", "utf8");\nconst data    = JSON.parse(content);\n\n// Sync (ok in CLI tools, startup only -- blocks event loop!)\nconst content = readFileSync("./config.json", "utf8");\n\n// Read binary\nconst image = await readFile("./photo.png"); // Returns Buffer\n```\n\n### Writing Files\n```javascript\nimport { writeFile, appendFile, mkdir } from "fs/promises";\n\nawait writeFile("./output.json", JSON.stringify(data, null, 2), "utf8");\nawait appendFile("./log.txt", `${new Date().toISOString()} Event\\n`);\n\n// Create nested directories\nawait mkdir("./uploads/2024/january", { recursive: true });\n```\n\n### Directory Operations\n```javascript\nimport { readdir, stat, rm } from "fs/promises";\nimport path from "path";\n\n// List files\nconst files = await readdir("./src");\n\n// List with full info\nconst entries = await readdir("./src", { withFileTypes: true });\nfor (const entry of entries) {\n  if (entry.isDirectory()) console.log("DIR:", entry.name);\n  if (entry.isFile())      console.log("FILE:", entry.name);\n}\n\n// Get file stats\nconst info = await stat("./data.json");\nconsole.log(info.size, info.mtime, info.isFile());\n\n// Delete\nawait rm("./temp", { recursive: true, force: true });\n```\n\n### Buffers\n```javascript\n// Buffer: raw binary data in memory\nconst buf = Buffer.from("Hello, World!", "utf8");\nconsole.log(buf.length);        // 13 (bytes)\nconsole.log(buf.toString());    // "Hello, World!"\nconsole.log(buf.toString("base64")); // Base64 encoded\n\n// From hex\nconst hex = Buffer.from("48656c6c6f", "hex");\nconsole.log(hex.toString()); // "Hello"\n\n// Allocate\nconst empty = Buffer.alloc(10);    // Zero-filled\nconst unsafe = Buffer.allocUnsafe(10); // Uninitialized (faster)\n```\n\n### Watching Files\n```javascript\nimport { watch } from "fs";\n\nwatch("./config.json", { encoding: "utf8" }, (eventType, filename) => {\n  console.log(`${filename} changed: ${eventType}`);\n  // Reload config...\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always use async fs operations in servers\n- Use path.join() not string concatenation for paths\n- Handle ENOENT errors (file not found) gracefully\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a Buffer in Node.js?\n2. When would you use readFileSync?\n3. What is the difference between fs and fs/promises?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a log rotation utility: reads a log file, compresses logs older than 7 days to .gz files, deletes logs older than 30 days, writes a summary report.', 25, 1),

('l70501', 'm705', 'Streams & Pipes', E'# Streams & Pipes in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nStreams process data piece-by-piece instead of loading everything into memory. Essential for handling large files, HTTP responses, and real-time data.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand Readable, Writable, and Transform streams\n- Use pipe to connect streams\n- Process large files efficiently\n- Build a custom transform stream\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Why Streams?\n```javascript\n// BAD: Load 4GB file into memory\nconst data = await readFile("huge-file.csv"); // 4GB in RAM!\nprocess(data);\n\n// GOOD: Stream 4GB file chunk by chunk\nconst readable = createReadStream("huge-file.csv");\nreadable.on("data", (chunk) => processChunk(chunk)); // Max 64KB at a time\n```\n\n### Readable Stream\n```javascript\nimport { createReadStream } from "fs";\n\nconst stream = createReadStream("./data.csv", {\n  encoding: "utf8",\n  highWaterMark: 64 * 1024, // 64KB chunks\n});\n\nstream.on("data",  (chunk) => console.log("Chunk:", chunk.length));\nstream.on("end",   ()       => console.log("Done reading"));\nstream.on("error", (err)    => console.error(err));\n```\n\n### Writable Stream\n```javascript\nimport { createWriteStream } from "fs";\n\nconst writer = createWriteStream("./output.txt");\n\nwriter.write("Line 1\\n");\nwriter.write("Line 2\\n");\nwriter.end("Last line\\n");\n\nwriter.on("finish", () => console.log("Write complete"));\n```\n\n### Pipe -- Connect Streams\n```javascript\nimport { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from "fs";\nimport { createGzip } from "zlib";\nimport { pipeline } from "stream/promises";\n\n// Compress a file\nawait pipeline(\n  createReadStream("./large-file.txt"),\n  createGzip(),\n  createWriteStream("./large-file.txt.gz")\n);\nconsole.log("Compressed!");\n```\n\n### Transform Stream\n```javascript\nimport { Transform } from "stream";\n\n// CSV line counter\nconst lineCounter = new Transform({\n  transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {\n    const lines = chunk.toString().split("\\n").length - 1;\n    this.push(`Lines in chunk: ${lines}\\n`);\n    callback();\n  }\n});\n\nawait pipeline(\n  createReadStream("./data.csv"),\n  lineCounter,\n  createWriteStream("./counts.txt")\n);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use pipeline() not .pipe() -- it handles errors and cleanup\n- Set highWaterMark based on your memory budget\n- Implement backpressure handling for writable streams\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is backpressure in streams?\n2. What is the difference between pipe and pipeline?\n3. When would you use a Transform stream?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a CSV processor: stream a 100k-row CSV, transform each row (parse, validate, transform fields), write valid rows to output.csv and invalid rows to errors.csv.', 25, 1),

('l70601', 'm706', 'HTTP Server in Node.js', E'# HTTP Server in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nUnderstanding how the raw http module works demystifies Express and every other Node web framework.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create an HTTP server from scratch\n- Parse request body and query params\n- Set response headers and status codes\n- Handle CORS manually\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Raw HTTP Server\n```javascript\nimport { createServer } from "http";\nimport { parse } from "url";\n\nconst server = createServer(async (req, res) => {\n  const { pathname, query } = parse(req.url, true);\n  const method = req.method;\n\n  // Parse JSON body\n  async function getBody() {\n    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n      let body = "";\n      req.on("data", chunk => body += chunk.toString());\n      req.on("end", () => {\n        try { resolve(JSON.parse(body)); }\n        catch { resolve({}); }\n      });\n      req.on("error", reject);\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Router\n  if (method === "GET" && pathname === "/api/users") {\n    const users = await getUsersFromDB();\n    res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });\n    res.end(JSON.stringify(users));\n\n  } else if (method === "POST" && pathname === "/api/users") {\n    const body = await getBody();\n    const user = await createUser(body);\n    res.writeHead(201, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });\n    res.end(JSON.stringify(user));\n\n  } else {\n    res.writeHead(404, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });\n    res.end(JSON.stringify({ error: "Not found" }));\n  }\n});\n\nserver.listen(3000, () => console.log("Running on :3000"));\n```\n\n### HTTPS Server\n```javascript\nimport { createServer } from "https";\nimport { readFileSync } from "fs";\n\nconst server = createServer({\n  key:  readFileSync("./certs/key.pem"),\n  cert: readFileSync("./certs/cert.pem"),\n}, requestHandler);\n```\n\n### CORS Headers\n```javascript\nfunction setCORSHeaders(res) {\n  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Origin",  "https://rlearn.com");\n  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Methods", "GET,POST,PUT,DELETE,OPTIONS");\n  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Allow-Headers", "Content-Type,Authorization");\n  res.setHeader("Access-Control-Max-Age",       "86400");\n}\n\nif (req.method === "OPTIONS") {\n  setCORSHeaders(res);\n  res.writeHead(204);\n  res.end();\n  return;\n}\n```\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. How do you parse the request body in raw Node.js?\n2. What is a preflight request (OPTIONS)?\n3. Why do we use Express instead of the raw http module?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a REST API from scratch using only the http module: CRUD for users, JSON request/response, proper status codes, CORS handling, and basic input validation.', 25, 1),

('l70701', 'm707', 'Async Patterns in Node.js', E'# Async Patterns in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nNode.js is async by nature. Using the wrong async pattern leads to callback hell, missed errors, or poor performance.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Convert callbacks to Promises\n- Use async/await throughout Node code\n- Run tasks in parallel and sequence\n- Handle concurrency limits\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Promisifying Callbacks\n```javascript\nimport { promisify } from "util";\nimport { readFile }  from "fs";\n\n// Manual promisification\nfunction readFileAsync(path) {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n    readFile(path, "utf8", (err, data) => {\n      if (err) reject(err);\n      else     resolve(data);\n    });\n  });\n}\n\n// Using util.promisify\nconst readFileAsync = promisify(readFile);\nconst data = await readFileAsync("./config.json", "utf8");\n\n// fs/promises (built-in -- prefer this)\nimport { readFile } from "fs/promises";\nconst data = await readFile("./config.json", "utf8");\n```\n\n### Parallel Execution\n```javascript\n// Sequential (slow -- waits for each)\nconst user    = await getUser(id);\nconst courses = await getUserCourses(id);\nconst xp      = await getUserXP(id);\n// Time: user + courses + xp\n\n// Parallel (fast -- all at once)\nconst [user, courses, xp] = await Promise.all([\n  getUser(id),\n  getUserCourses(id),\n  getUserXP(id),\n]);\n// Time: max(user, courses, xp)\n\n// Parallel with individual error handling\nconst results = await Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3]);\nconst successes = results.filter(r => r.status === "fulfilled").map(r => r.value);\nconst failures  = results.filter(r => r.status === "rejected").map(r => r.reason);\n```\n\n### Concurrency Limiting\n```javascript\n// Process 1000 items but max 10 at a time\nasync function withConcurrencyLimit(items, limit, asyncFn) {\n  const results = [];\n  const executing = new Set();\n\n  for (const item of items) {\n    const p = asyncFn(item).then(result => {\n      executing.delete(p);\n      return result;\n    });\n    executing.add(p);\n    results.push(p);\n    if (executing.size >= limit) {\n      await Promise.race(executing);\n    }\n  }\n  return Promise.all(results);\n}\n\nconst results = await withConcurrencyLimit(users, 10, sendEmail);\n// Sends max 10 emails concurrently\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always use async/await over raw Promise chains\n- Use Promise.all for independent parallel work\n- Limit concurrency to avoid overwhelming downstream services\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is util.promisify?\n2. What is the difference between Promise.all and Promise.allSettled?\n3. How do you run N promises with a concurrency limit?\n\n## Assignment\nWrite a bulk email sender: read 5000 users from a file, send each a welcome email via a mock API, limit to 20 concurrent requests, retry failed requests once, log results.', 25, 1),

('l70801', 'm708', 'Error Handling & Logging', E'# Error Handling & Logging in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nProduction Node apps must handle errors gracefully and log them in a way that enables debugging without exposing sensitive information.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement centralized error handling\n- Use a structured logger (pino/winston)\n- Handle uncaught exceptions and rejections\n- Set up error monitoring\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Structured Logging with pino\n```bash\nnpm install pino pino-pretty\n```\n\n```javascript\nimport pino from "pino";\n\nconst logger = pino({\n  level: process.env.LOG_LEVEL ?? "info",\n  transport: process.env.NODE_ENV === "development"\n    ? { target: "pino-pretty", options: { colorize: true } }\n    : undefined, // Production: JSON to stdout\n});\n\n// Structured log entries\nlogger.info({ userId: "123", action: "login" }, "User logged in");\nlogger.warn({ requestId, method: "POST", path: "/api/users" }, "Rate limit approaching");\nlogger.error({ err, requestId }, "Database query failed");\n\n// Child logger with context\nconst requestLogger = logger.child({ requestId: req.id });\nrequestLogger.info("Processing request");\n```\n\n### Error Handling Hierarchy\n```javascript\n// Custom error classes\nclass AppError extends Error {\n  constructor(message, statusCode = 500, code = "INTERNAL_ERROR") {\n    super(message);\n    this.name       = "AppError";\n    this.statusCode = statusCode;\n    this.code       = code;\n    this.isOperational = true; // Expected error (not a bug)\n  }\n}\n\n// Async handler wrapper (avoids try/catch everywhere)\nconst asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) =>\n  Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);\n\n// Express global error handler\napp.use((err, req, res, next) => {\n  const statusCode = err.statusCode ?? 500;\n  const isOperational = err.isOperational ?? false;\n\n  logger.error({\n    err,\n    requestId: req.id,\n    method:    req.method,\n    url:       req.url,\n  }, isOperational ? err.message : "Unexpected error");\n\n  if (!isOperational) {\n    // Bug or unexpected error -- alert team\n    alertMonitoring(err);\n  }\n\n  res.status(statusCode).json({\n    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" && !isOperational\n      ? "Internal server error"\n      : err.message,\n    code: err.code,\n  });\n});\n```\n\n### Global Handlers\n```javascript\nprocess.on("uncaughtException", (err) => {\n  logger.fatal({ err }, "Uncaught exception -- shutting down");\n  process.exit(1);\n});\n\nprocess.on("unhandledRejection", (reason, promise) => {\n  logger.fatal({ reason }, "Unhandled promise rejection");\n  process.exit(1);\n});\n\n// Graceful shutdown\nprocess.on("SIGTERM", async () => {\n  logger.info("Received SIGTERM -- closing server");\n  await server.close();\n  await db.disconnect();\n  process.exit(0);\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Log structured JSON in production (machine-parseable)\n- Use log levels: debug, info, warn, error, fatal\n- Never log passwords, tokens, or PII\n- Set up alerts on error-level logs\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between an operational error and a programmer error?\n2. What is the uncaughtException handler and when should you use it?\n3. What is structured logging?\n\n## Assignment\nAdd pino logging to an Express API: request logging middleware (method, url, status, duration), error logging in global handler, structured context (requestId per request), redact sensitive fields.', 25, 1),

('l70901', 'm709', 'Environment & Configuration', E'# Environment & Configuration in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nHardcoded configuration is the #1 cause of security breaches and deployment failures. Proper env management is non-negotiable.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use environment variables correctly\n- Load .env files with dotenv\n- Validate config with Zod\n- Structure config for multiple environments\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### .env Files\n```bash\n# .env (gitignored!)\nNODE_ENV=development\nPORT=3000\nDATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:pass@localhost:5432/rlearn\nJWT_SECRET=super-secret-development-key\nAWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=AKIA...\nSUPABASE_URL=https://xxx.supabase.co\nSUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY=eyJ...\n```\n\n```bash\nnpm install dotenv\n```\n\n```javascript\nimport "dotenv/config"; // Load .env at startup\n// Or: import dotenv from "dotenv"; dotenv.config();\n\nconsole.log(process.env.PORT);         // "3000"\nconsole.log(process.env.DATABASE_URL);\n```\n\n### Validated Config with Zod\n```javascript\nimport { z }   from "zod";\nimport "dotenv/config";\n\nconst configSchema = z.object({\n  NODE_ENV:     z.enum(["development", "test", "production"]),\n  PORT:         z.string().transform(Number).default("3000"),\n  DATABASE_URL: z.string().url(),\n  JWT_SECRET:   z.string().min(32),\n  LOG_LEVEL:    z.enum(["debug", "info", "warn", "error"]).default("info"),\n});\n\nconst parsed = configSchema.safeParse(process.env);\nif (!parsed.success) {\n  console.error("Invalid environment configuration:");\n  console.error(parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors);\n  process.exit(1); // Fail fast -- do not start with bad config\n}\n\nexport const config = parsed.data;\n// config.PORT is a number (not string!)\n// config.JWT_SECRET is guaranteed to be 32+ chars\n```\n\n### Environment-Specific Files\n```bash\n.env                 # Base defaults\n.env.development     # Development overrides\n.env.test            # Test overrides\n.env.production      # Production (usually set by deployment platform)\n.env.example         # Template -- COMMIT this, not the real .env\n```\n\n### Security\n```bash\n# .gitignore -- ALWAYS ignore .env files with secrets\n.env\n.env.local\n.env.*.local\n\n# .env.example -- safe to commit (no real values)\nNODE_ENV=development\nPORT=3000\nDATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:password@localhost:5432/dbname\nJWT_SECRET=REPLACE_WITH_32_CHAR_SECRET\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Validate all env vars at startup, fail fast\n- Never commit .env files with real secrets\n- Use different secrets per environment\n- Rotate secrets regularly\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Why should you never commit .env files?\n2. How do you handle different config per environment?\n3. What does fail-fast mean in the context of config?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a config module: load .env, validate all variables with Zod, expose typed config object, fail with helpful error message for any missing/invalid variable.', 20, 1),

('l71001', 'm710', 'Security in Node.js', E'# Security in Node.js\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nNode.js applications are frequent targets. Security vulnerabilities in npm packages, APIs, and file operations are common attack vectors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Prevent common Node.js vulnerabilities\n- Secure npm dependencies\n- Rate limit and helmet harden APIs\n- Handle file uploads safely\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Security Headers (helmet)\n```bash\nnpm install helmet\n```\n\n```javascript\nimport helmet from "helmet";\napp.use(helmet()); // Sets 11 security headers automatically\n\n// What helmet sets:\n// Content-Security-Policy\n// X-DNS-Prefetch-Control\n// X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN (clickjacking)\n// Strict-Transport-Security (HTTPS only)\n// X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff\n// X-XSS-Protection: 0 (let CSP handle it)\n```\n\n### Rate Limiting\n```bash\nnpm install express-rate-limit\n```\n\n```javascript\nimport rateLimit from "express-rate-limit";\n\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes\n  max:      100,             // 100 requests per window\n  standardHeaders: true,     // Return rate limit headers\n  message: { error: "Too many requests, please try again later." }\n});\n\nconst loginLimiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,\n  max:      5, // Strict for login\n  skipSuccessfulRequests: true, // Only count failed attempts\n});\n\napp.use("/api/", limiter);\napp.post("/api/auth/login", loginLimiter, loginHandler);\n```\n\n### Dependency Security\n```bash\nnpm audit                    # Check for vulnerabilities\nnpm audit fix                # Auto-fix safe updates\nnpm audit fix --force        # Fix with breaking changes (test after!)\n\n# npm scripts for CI\n"scripts": {\n  "security": "npm audit --audit-level=high"\n}\n```\n\n### Command Injection Prevention\n```javascript\n// DANGEROUS: Never pass user input to exec/spawn\nimport { exec } from "child_process";\nconst filename = req.query.file; // User input\nexec(`cat ${filename}`); // User inputs: "file; rm -rf /"\n\n// SAFE: Use array args\nimport { spawn } from "child_process";\nspawn("cat", [filename]); // Arguments are not shell-interpreted\n\n// SAFER: Validate first\nconst safe = /^[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+\\.txt$/.test(filename);\nif (!safe) throw new AppError("Invalid filename", 400);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always use helmet in production\n- Rate limit auth endpoints aggressively\n- Run npm audit in CI/CD pipeline\n- Never interpolate user input into shell commands\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is helmet and what does it protect against?\n2. What is a command injection attack?\n3. How do you prevent brute force on login endpoints?\n\n## Assignment\nSecurity-harden an Express API: add helmet, rate limiting (global + per-endpoint), input validation, npm audit in CI. Run OWASP ZAP against it and fix all findings.', 25, 1),

('l71101', 'm711', 'Performance & Clustering', E'# Node.js Performance & Clustering\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nA single-threaded Node process uses one CPU core. Clustering and worker threads allow you to use all available CPUs for maximum throughput.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Profile Node.js applications\n- Use cluster module to scale across CPUs\n- Implement worker threads for CPU tasks\n- Apply PM2 for production process management\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Profiling\n```bash\n# Built-in profiler\nnode --prof app.js\nnode --prof-process isolate-*.log > profile.txt\n\n# Clinic.js (better tooling)\nnpm install -g clinic\nclinic doctor -- node app.js\nclinic flame  -- node app.js  # Flame graph\n```\n\n### Cluster Module\n```javascript\nimport cluster from "cluster";\nimport { cpus } from "os";\nimport process  from "process";\n\nif (cluster.isPrimary) {\n  const numCPUs = cpus().length;\n  console.log(`Primary ${process.pid} running, forking ${numCPUs} workers`);\n\n  for (let i = 0; i < numCPUs; i++) {\n    cluster.fork();\n  }\n\n  cluster.on("exit", (worker, code) => {\n    console.log(`Worker ${worker.process.pid} died (${code}), restarting`);\n    cluster.fork(); // Auto-restart\n  });\n\n} else {\n  // Worker: start the HTTP server\n  startServer();\n  console.log(`Worker ${process.pid} started`);\n}\n```\n\n### Worker Threads (CPU-bound)\n```javascript\n// main.js\nimport { Worker } from "worker_threads";\n\nfunction runInWorker(data) {\n  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n    const worker = new Worker("./compute.js", { workerData: data });\n    worker.on("message", resolve);\n    worker.on("error",   reject);\n    worker.on("exit", code => {\n      if (code !== 0) reject(new Error(`Worker exited with code ${code}`));\n    });\n  });\n}\n\napp.post("/api/process", async (req, res) => {\n  const result = await runInWorker(req.body); // Runs off main thread\n  res.json(result);\n});\n\n// compute.js\nimport { parentPort, workerData } from "worker_threads";\nconst result = expensiveComputation(workerData);\nparentPort.postMessage(result);\n```\n\n### PM2 Process Manager\n```bash\nnpm install -g pm2\n\npm2 start app.js --name "rlearn-api" -i max  # Cluster mode\npm2 status\npm2 logs\npm2 restart rlearn-api\npm2 save                # Persist process list\npm2 startup             # Start on system boot\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use clustering for I/O-bound services (most APIs)\n- Use worker_threads for CPU-bound tasks per request\n- Use PM2 in production for monitoring and auto-restart\n- Profile before optimizing -- find the actual bottleneck\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between cluster and worker_threads?\n2. Why does clustering improve performance?\n3. How do you handle state in a clustered Node.js app?\n\n## Assignment\nBenchmark an API endpoint with autocannon: first single-process, then clustered. Compare requests/second and latency. Add a worker thread for a CPU-heavy computation endpoint.', 25, 1)

