('l80101', 'm801', 'Express Setup & Core Concepts', E'# Express Setup & Core Concepts\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nExpress is the most popular Node.js framework. Understanding its core concepts -- middleware, request/response cycle -- is foundational for all backend work.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Set up an Express server\n- Understand the middleware pipeline\n- Handle requests and send responses\n- Structure a basic Express application\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Setup\n```bash\nnpm install express\nnpm install -D @types/express typescript ts-node\n```\n\n### Basic Server\n```typescript\nimport express, { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";\n\nconst app = express();\n\n// Built-in middleware\napp.use(express.json());                          // Parse JSON body\napp.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true })); // Parse form data\napp.use(express.static("public"));               // Serve static files\n\n// Route handler\napp.get("/", (req: Request, res: Response) => {\n  res.status(200).json({ message: "Welcome to R-Learn API" });\n});\n\n// Start server\nconst PORT = process.env.PORT ?? 3000;\napp.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));\n\nexport default app;\n```\n\n### Request Object\n```typescript\napp.post("/api/courses/:id/enroll", (req, res) => {\n  console.log(req.params.id);       // URL params: /courses/123\n  console.log(req.query.tab);       // Query string: ?tab=lessons\n  console.log(req.body.userId);     // JSON body (requires express.json())\n  console.log(req.headers["authorization"]); // Request headers\n  console.log(req.ip);              // Client IP\n  console.log(req.method);          // HTTP method\n  console.log(req.path);            // URL path\n});\n```\n\n### Response Methods\n```typescript\nres.status(200).json({ data: users });\nres.status(201).json({ data: newUser });\nres.status(204).end();                          // No content\nres.status(400).json({ error: "Bad request" });\nres.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" });\nres.redirect(301, "/new-url");\nres.sendFile(path.join(__dirname, "index.html"));\nres.download("./report.pdf", "report.pdf");    // File download\nres.set("X-Custom-Header", "value");\nres.cookie("session", token, { httpOnly: true, secure: true });\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always call next() in middleware or send a response (avoid hangs)\n- Use environment variables for PORT and config\n- Separate app creation from server listen (for testability)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between app.use() and app.get()?\n2. What happens if you do not call next() in middleware?\n3. How do you serve static files in Express?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a full Express server: health check endpoint, JSON body parsing, static file serving, and a basic API with 5 routes. Include graceful shutdown handling.', 25, 1),

('l80201', 'm802', 'Routing in Express', E'# Routing in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nWell-organized routing is the backbone of a maintainable API. Express Router enables modular, scalable route structures.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Define routes with all HTTP methods\n- Use Router for modular routing\n- Handle route parameters and query strings\n- Implement nested routes\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Basic Routing\n```typescript\napp.get   ("/api/courses",     getCourses);\napp.post  ("/api/courses",     createCourse);\napp.get   ("/api/courses/:id", getCourse);\napp.put   ("/api/courses/:id", updateCourse);\napp.patch ("/api/courses/:id", patchCourse);\napp.delete("/api/courses/:id", deleteCourse);\n\n// Catch-all (must be last)\napp.use("*", (req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: "Not found" }));\n```\n\n### Express Router (Modular)\n```typescript\n// routes/courses.ts\nimport { Router } from "express";\nimport { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth";\nimport { CourseController } from "../controllers/CourseController";\n\nconst router = Router();\nconst ctrl = new CourseController();\n\nrouter.get   ("/",    ctrl.list);\nrouter.post  ("/",    authenticate, ctrl.create);\nrouter.get   ("/:id", ctrl.get);\nrouter.put   ("/:id", authenticate, ctrl.update);\nrouter.delete("/:id", authenticate, ctrl.delete);\n\n// Nested: /api/courses/:id/lessons\nrouter.get("/:id/lessons", ctrl.getLessons);\n\nexport { router as coursesRouter };\n\n// app.ts\nimport { coursesRouter } from "./routes/courses";\napp.use("/api/courses", coursesRouter);\n```\n\n### Route Parameters\n```typescript\n// Single param\napp.get("/users/:id", (req, res) => {\n  const { id } = req.params; // "123"\n});\n\n// Multiple params\napp.get("/courses/:courseId/lessons/:lessonId", (req, res) => {\n  const { courseId, lessonId } = req.params;\n});\n\n// Optional param\napp.get("/posts/:year/:month?", (req, res) => {\n  const { year, month = "01" } = req.params;\n});\n\n// Param validation middleware\nrouter.param("id", (req, res, next, id) => {\n  if (!/^[0-9a-fA-F-]{36}$/.test(id)) {\n    return res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid ID format" });\n  }\n  next();\n});\n```\n\n### Query Parameters\n```typescript\n// GET /api/courses?category=Frontend&difficulty=Beginner&page=1&limit=10\napp.get("/api/courses", (req, res) => {\n  const {\n    category,\n    difficulty,\n    page  = "1",\n    limit = "10",\n    search = "",\n    sort = "createdAt"\n  } = req.query as Record<string, string>;\n\n  const courses = db.courses.filter({\n    category, difficulty,\n    title: { contains: search },\n  }).paginate({ page: +page, limit: +limit }).sort(sort);\n\n  res.json({ data: courses, page: +page, limit: +limit });\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Group routes by resource (not by HTTP method)\n- Use Router.param() for reusable param validation\n- Keep route files thin -- move logic to controllers\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between app.use() and app.get() for routes?\n2. What is the purpose of Express Router?\n3. How do you handle 404 in Express?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a fully organized API with 3 resource routers (courses, users, lessons), param validation, query string filtering/pagination, and a catch-all 404 handler.', 25, 1),

('l80301', 'm803', 'Middleware in Express', E'# Middleware in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nMiddleware is the heart of Express. Every cross-cutting concern -- logging, auth, validation, CORS -- is implemented as middleware.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write custom middleware functions\n- Chain middleware correctly\n- Use third-party middleware\n- Implement error-handling middleware\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Middleware Signature\n```typescript\n// Normal middleware\n(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => void\n\n// Error-handling middleware (4 params!)\n(err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => void\n```\n\n### Writing Middleware\n```typescript\n// Logging middleware\nconst requestLogger = (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  const start = Date.now();\n  res.on("finish", () => {\n    const duration = Date.now() - start;\n    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.url} ${res.statusCode} ${duration}ms`);\n  });\n  next(); // Always call next() unless sending response\n};\n\n// Request ID middleware\nimport { v4 as uuid } from "uuid";\nconst requestId = (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  req.id = req.headers["x-request-id"] as string ?? uuid();\n  res.setHeader("X-Request-ID", req.id);\n  next();\n};\n\n// Apply globally\napp.use(requestId);\napp.use(requestLogger);\n```\n\n### Third-Party Middleware\n```bash\nnpm install cors helmet morgan compression express-rate-limit\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport cors        from "cors";\nimport helmet     from "helmet";\nimport morgan     from "morgan";\nimport compression from "compression";\n\napp.use(helmet());\napp.use(cors({ origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(",") }));\napp.use(morgan("combined"));\napp.use(compression());\napp.use(express.json({ limit: "10mb" }));\n```\n\n### Middleware Scope\n```typescript\n// Global middleware\napp.use(helmet());\n\n// Route-level middleware\napp.get("/admin", authenticate, authorize("admin"), adminHandler);\n\n// Router-level middleware\nconst api = Router();\napi.use(authenticate);  // All routes on this router require auth\napi.get("/me", getMe);\n\n// Inline array\napp.post("/upload",\n  [authenticate, validateUpload, handleUpload]\n);\n```\n\n### Error Handling Middleware\n```typescript\n// Must have exactly 4 parameters\nconst errorHandler = (err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  const statusCode = (err as AppError).statusCode ?? 500;\n  const isOperational = (err as AppError).isOperational ?? false;\n\n  logger.error({ err, url: req.url, method: req.method });\n\n  res.status(statusCode).json({\n    error:   isOperational ? err.message : "Internal server error",\n    code:    (err as AppError).code,\n    requestId: req.id,\n  });\n};\n\n// Must be registered LAST\napp.use(errorHandler);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Order matters: security headers before CORS before auth before routes\n- Always call next() or send a response in every code path\n- Pass errors to next(err) -- do not throw in async middleware\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the purpose of calling next() in middleware?\n2. How does error-handling middleware differ from regular middleware?\n3. What is middleware ordering and why does it matter?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a middleware stack: requestId, structured logging, CORS, rate limiting, JSON parsing, authentication, and a global error handler. Test each middleware in isolation.', 25, 1),

('l80401', 'm804', 'Request & Response in Express', E'# Request & Response Objects\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDeep knowledge of the req and res objects lets you handle any HTTP scenario: file uploads, streaming, cookies, custom headers.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Access all parts of the request\n- Use all response methods\n- Handle file uploads with multer\n- Work with cookies and sessions\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Request Deep Dive\n```typescript\napp.post("/api/upload", (req, res) => {\n  // Headers\n  const auth   = req.headers.authorization;    // "Bearer eyJ..."\n  const type   = req.headers["content-type"];\n  const custom = req.headers["x-custom"];\n\n  // Body (requires middleware)\n  const { name, email } = req.body; // JSON\n\n  // URL\n  const { id }     = req.params;    // /users/:id\n  const { page }   = req.query;     // ?page=2\n  const path       = req.path;      // "/api/upload"\n  const fullUrl    = `${req.protocol}://${req.get("host")}${req.originalUrl}`;\n\n  // Client info\n  const ip         = req.ip;\n  const ips        = req.ips; // Proxied IPs\n  const isHTTPS    = req.secure;\n\n  // Custom properties (added by middleware)\n  const user       = req.user;       // Set by auth middleware\n  const requestId  = req.id;         // Set by requestId middleware\n});\n```\n\n### File Uploads with Multer\n```bash\nnpm install multer\nnpm install -D @types/multer\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport multer from "multer";\nimport path   from "path";\n\nconst storage = multer.diskStorage({\n  destination: (req, file, cb) => cb(null, "./uploads"),\n  filename:    (req, file, cb) => {\n    const unique = `${Date.now()}-${Math.round(Math.random() * 1e9)}`;\n    cb(null, `${file.fieldname}-${unique}${path.extname(file.originalname)}`);\n  },\n});\n\nconst upload = multer({\n  storage,\n  limits: { fileSize: 5 * 1024 * 1024 }, // 5MB\n  fileFilter: (req, file, cb) => {\n    if (file.mimetype.startsWith("image/")) cb(null, true);\n    else cb(new Error("Only images allowed"));\n  },\n});\n\napp.post("/api/avatar", upload.single("avatar"), (req, res) => {\n  res.json({ url: `/uploads/${req.file?.filename}` });\n});\n\napp.post("/api/gallery", upload.array("photos", 10), (req, res) => {\n  const urls = req.files.map(f => `/uploads/${f.filename}`);\n  res.json({ urls });\n});\n```\n\n### Cookies\n```typescript\nimport cookieParser from "cookie-parser";\napp.use(cookieParser(process.env.COOKIE_SECRET));\n\n// Set cookie\nres.cookie("refreshToken", token, {\n  httpOnly: true,   // No JS access (XSS protection)\n  secure:   true,   // HTTPS only\n  sameSite: "strict", // CSRF protection\n  maxAge:   7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000, // 7 days\n  path:     "/api/auth/refresh",\n});\n\n// Read cookie\nconst refreshToken = req.cookies.refreshToken;\nconst signed       = req.signedCookies.session;\n\n// Clear cookie\nres.clearCookie("refreshToken");\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use httpOnly cookies for refresh tokens\n- Limit file upload size and validate MIME types\n- Extend Request interface with augmented types in TypeScript\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between req.params and req.query?\n2. How do you secure cookies?\n3. How does multer handle file uploads?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a profile update endpoint: accept name/bio as JSON and avatar as file upload, validate file type and size, store file, return updated profile.', 25, 1),

('l80501', 'm805', 'Controllers & Services', E'# Controllers & Services in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nSeparating concerns into controllers (HTTP) and services (business logic) makes code testable, reusable, and maintainable.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement the Controller-Service pattern\n- Write dependency injection\n- Test services in isolation\n- Structure a layered architecture\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Layered Architecture\n```\nHTTP Layer:     Router -> Controller\n                Routes requests, sends responses\n\nBusiness Layer: Service\n                Business logic, orchestration\n\nData Layer:     Repository\n                Database queries\n```\n\n### Controller\n```typescript\n// controllers/CourseController.ts\nimport { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";\nimport { CourseService }                   from "../services/CourseService";\nimport { CreateCourseDto }                 from "../dtos/CreateCourseDto";\nimport { validate }                        from "../middleware/validate";\n\nexport class CourseController {\n  constructor(private courseService: CourseService) {}\n\n  list = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const { page = "1", limit = "10", category } = req.query as Record<string, string>;\n      const result = await this.courseService.list({ page: +page, limit: +limit, category });\n      res.json({ data: result.courses, meta: result.meta });\n    } catch (err) { next(err); }\n  };\n\n  create = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const dto: CreateCourseDto = req.body;\n      const course = await this.courseService.create(dto, req.user!.id);\n      res.status(201).json({ data: course });\n    } catch (err) { next(err); }\n  };\n\n  get = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const course = await this.courseService.getById(req.params.id);\n      if (!course) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Course not found" });\n      res.json({ data: course });\n    } catch (err) { next(err); }\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### Service\n```typescript\n// services/CourseService.ts\nimport { CourseRepository } from "../repositories/CourseRepository";\nimport { NotFoundError }    from "../errors";\n\nexport class CourseService {\n  constructor(private courseRepo: CourseRepository) {}\n\n  async list({ page, limit, category }: ListParams) {\n    const offset = (page - 1) * limit;\n    const [courses, total] = await Promise.all([\n      this.courseRepo.find({ category }, { offset, limit }),\n      this.courseRepo.count({ category }),\n    ]);\n    return {\n      courses,\n      meta: { page, limit, total, totalPages: Math.ceil(total / limit) }\n    };\n  }\n\n  async create(dto: CreateCourseDto, authorId: string) {\n    return this.courseRepo.create({ ...dto, authorId, createdAt: new Date() });\n  }\n\n  async getById(id: string) {\n    const course = await this.courseRepo.findById(id);\n    if (!course) throw new NotFoundError("Course");\n    return course;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Wiring with DI\n```typescript\n// app.ts\nconst courseRepo       = new CourseRepository(db);\nconst courseService    = new CourseService(courseRepo);\nconst courseController = new CourseController(courseService);\n\napp.use("/api/courses", createCourseRouter(courseController));\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Controllers handle HTTP only (parse req, call service, send res)\n- Services contain all business logic (no req/res objects)\n- Repositories handle all database queries\n- Test services with mock repositories\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a controller and a service?\n2. What is dependency injection?\n3. Why separate services from controllers?\n\n## Assignment\nRefactor a monolithic route handler into Controller + Service + Repository layers. Write unit tests for the service with a mock repository.', 30, 1),

('l80601', 'm806', 'Validation & Sanitization', E'# Validation & Sanitization in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nNever trust user input. Validation and sanitization at the API boundary prevents injection attacks, data corruption, and confusing errors.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Validate request bodies, params, and queries\n- Use Zod for schema validation\n- Sanitize input to prevent XSS and injection\n- Return structured validation errors\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Zod Validation Middleware\n```typescript\nimport { z, ZodSchema } from "zod";\n\nfunction validate(schema: ZodSchema, target: "body" | "query" | "params" = "body") {\n  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    const result = schema.safeParse(req[target]);\n    if (!result.success) {\n      return res.status(400).json({\n        error:   "Validation failed",\n        details: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors,\n      });\n    }\n    req[target] = result.data; // Replace with parsed/coerced data\n    next();\n  };\n}\n```\n\n### Define Schemas\n```typescript\nconst CreateCourseSchema = z.object({\n  title:       z.string().min(3).max(200).trim(),\n  description: z.string().min(10).max(2000).trim(),\n  difficulty:  z.enum(["Beginner", "Intermediate", "Advanced"]),\n  category:    z.enum(["Frontend", "Backend", "DevOps", "System Design"]),\n  duration:    z.number().int().min(1).max(200),\n  price:       z.number().min(0).optional(),\n  tags:        z.array(z.string().max(30)).max(10).optional(),\n});\n\nconst PaginationSchema = z.object({\n  page:  z.coerce.number().int().min(1).default(1),\n  limit: z.coerce.number().int().min(1).max(100).default(10),\n  sort:  z.enum(["createdAt", "title", "enrolled"]).default("createdAt"),\n  order: z.enum(["asc", "desc"]).default("desc"),\n});\n\nconst IdParamSchema = z.object({\n  id: z.string().uuid("Invalid ID format"),\n});\n\n// Apply\nrouter.post(\"/\", validate(CreateCourseSchema), createCourse);\nrouter.get(\"/\",  validate(PaginationSchema, \"query\"), listCourses);\nrouter.get(\"/:id\", validate(IdParamSchema, \"params\"), getCourse);\n```\n\n### Sanitization\n```typescript\nimport DOMPurify from "isomorphic-dompurify";\n\n// Sanitize HTML input (for rich text fields)\nfunction sanitizeHtml(html: string): string {\n  return DOMPurify.sanitize(html, {\n    ALLOWED_TAGS:  ["p", "b", "i", "ul", "li", "ol", "a", "code", "pre"],\n    ALLOWED_ATTR:  ["href"],\n  });\n}\n\n// In schema with transform\nconst ContentSchema = z.object({\n  content: z.string().transform(html => sanitizeHtml(html)),\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Validate at the API boundary -- never trust downstream\n- Use Zod schemas as the single source of truth for TypeScript types\n- Return all validation errors at once (not just the first)\n- Coerce types in query params (they arrive as strings)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between validation and sanitization?\n2. How do you return multiple validation errors?\n3. Why is query param coercion important?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a validation middleware system: CreateUserSchema, UpdateUserSchema (Partial), LoginSchema, PaginationSchema, UUID params. Return structured errors. Sanitize text fields.', 25, 1),

('l80701', 'm807', 'Authentication Middleware', E'# Authentication Middleware in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAuthentication middleware gates access to protected resources. Getting it wrong exposes your entire API.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement JWT authentication middleware\n- Handle token refresh\n- Implement role-based authorization\n- Test authentication middleware\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### JWT Authentication\n```bash\nnpm install jsonwebtoken bcryptjs\nnpm install -D @types/jsonwebtoken @types/bcryptjs\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport jwt from "jsonwebtoken";\n\nconst JWT_SECRET  = process.env.JWT_SECRET!;\nconst JWT_EXPIRES = "15m"; // Short-lived access token\n\n// Generate tokens\nfunction generateAccessToken(payload: JwtPayload): string {\n  return jwt.sign(payload, JWT_SECRET, { expiresIn: JWT_EXPIRES });\n}\n\nfunction generateRefreshToken(payload: JwtPayload): string {\n  return jwt.sign(payload, process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET!, { expiresIn: "7d" });\n}\n\n// Authentication middleware\nconst authenticate = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  try {\n    const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;\n    if (!authHeader?.startsWith("Bearer ")) {\n      return res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });\n    }\n\n    const token = authHeader.split(" ")[1];\n    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as JwtPayload;\n\n    // Attach user to request\n    const user = await userRepo.findById(payload.userId);\n    if (!user || !user.isActive) {\n      return res.status(401).json({ error: "User not found or inactive" });\n    }\n\n    req.user = user;\n    next();\n  } catch (err) {\n    if (err instanceof jwt.TokenExpiredError) {\n      return res.status(401).json({ error: "Token expired", code: "TOKEN_EXPIRED" });\n    }\n    return res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });\n  }\n};\n```\n\n### Authorization Middleware\n```typescript\nconst authorize = (...roles: string[]) => {\n  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    if (!req.user) return res.status(401).json({ error: "Unauthorized" });\n    if (!roles.includes(req.user.role)) {\n      return res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden: insufficient permissions" });\n    }\n    next();\n  };\n};\n\n// Usage\nrouter.delete("/:id", authenticate, authorize("admin"), deleteCourse);\nrouter.put("/:id",    authenticate, authorize("admin", "mentor"), updateCourse);\nrouter.get("/",       authenticate, getCourses); // Any authenticated user\n```\n\n### Refresh Token Endpoint\n```typescript\napp.post("/api/auth/refresh", async (req, res) => {\n  const refreshToken = req.cookies.refreshToken;\n  if (!refreshToken) return res.status(401).json({ error: "No refresh token" });\n\n  try {\n    const payload = jwt.verify(refreshToken, process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET!) as JwtPayload;\n    const user    = await userRepo.findById(payload.userId);\n    if (!user) return res.status(401).json({ error: "User not found" });\n\n    const accessToken = generateAccessToken({ userId: user.id, role: user.role });\n    res.json({ accessToken });\n  } catch {\n    res.clearCookie("refreshToken");\n    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid refresh token" });\n  }\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Keep access tokens short-lived (15 minutes)\n- Store refresh tokens in HTTP-only cookies\n- Check token blacklist for logout scenarios\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between authentication and authorization?\n2. Why are access tokens short-lived?\n3. How do you handle token refresh?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild complete auth: register, login (returns access + refresh tokens), protected route, refresh endpoint, logout (clear cookie). Rate limit login. Test with Jest.', 35, 1),

('l80801', 'm808', 'Error Handling in Express', E'# Error Handling in Express\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nCentralized error handling ensures consistent error responses and prevents information leakage in production.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement centralized error handling\n- Write async error wrappers\n- Handle common error types\n- Return consistent error responses\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Custom Error Classes\n```typescript\nclass AppError extends Error {\n  public readonly statusCode: number;\n  public readonly code:       string;\n  public readonly isOperational: boolean;\n\n  constructor(message: string, statusCode = 500, code = "INTERNAL_ERROR") {\n    super(message);\n    this.name          = this.constructor.name;\n    this.statusCode    = statusCode;\n    this.code          = code;\n    this.isOperational = true;\n    Error.captureStackTrace(this, this.constructor);\n  }\n}\n\nclass NotFoundError    extends AppError {\n  constructor(resource = "Resource") { super(`${resource} not found`, 404, "NOT_FOUND"); }\n}\n\nclass ValidationError  extends AppError {\n  public readonly fields: Record<string, string[]>;\n  constructor(fields: Record<string, string[]>) {\n    super("Validation failed", 400, "VALIDATION_ERROR");\n    this.fields = fields;\n  }\n}\n\nclass UnauthorizedError extends AppError {\n  constructor(msg = "Unauthorized") { super(msg, 401, "UNAUTHORIZED"); }\n}\n\nclass ForbiddenError    extends AppError {\n  constructor(msg = "Forbidden") { super(msg, 403, "FORBIDDEN"); }\n}\n```\n\n### Async Handler Wrapper\n```typescript\n// Avoids try/catch in every route\nconst asyncHandler = (fn: Function) =>\n  (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) =>\n    Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next);\n\n// Usage\nrouter.get("/:id", asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {\n  const course = await courseService.getById(req.params.id);\n  res.json({ data: course }); // No try/catch needed\n}));\n```\n\n### Global Error Handler\n```typescript\nconst errorHandler = (err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  // Log all errors\n  logger.error({ err, url: req.url, requestId: req.id }, err.message);\n\n  // Handle known error types\n  if (err instanceof ValidationError) {\n    return res.status(400).json({ error: err.message, code: err.code, fields: err.fields });\n  }\n\n  if (err instanceof AppError) {\n    return res.status(err.statusCode).json({ error: err.message, code: err.code });\n  }\n\n  // Database errors\n  if (err.message.includes("duplicate key")) {\n    return res.status(409).json({ error: "Resource already exists", code: "CONFLICT" });\n  }\n\n  // Unexpected errors (bugs)\n  const isProd = process.env.NODE_ENV === "production";\n  return res.status(500).json({\n    error: isProd ? "Internal server error" : err.message,\n    code:  "INTERNAL_ERROR",\n  });\n};\n\n// Register LAST (after all routes)\napp.use(errorHandler);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always use asyncHandler wrapper for async routes\n- Never expose stack traces in production\n- Map database errors to application errors\n- Log with request context (requestId, userId)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Why does Express error handler have 4 parameters?\n2. What is the asyncHandler pattern?\n3. How do you handle database errors in Express?\n\n## Assignment\nRefactor an Express app to use centralized error handling: custom error classes, asyncHandler wrapper, global error middleware, consistent JSON error format, no stack trace in production.', 25, 1),

('l80901', 'm809', 'API Architecture & Best Practices', E'# API Architecture & Best Practices\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nWell-designed APIs are easier to consume, maintain, and evolve. These patterns are used by the best engineering teams.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Design consistent API response formats\n- Implement pagination and filtering\n- Add API versioning\n- Document with Swagger/OpenAPI\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Consistent Response Format\n```typescript\n// Success response\n{\n  "data":    { ... },         // Single resource or array\n  "meta":    { "page": 1, "limit": 10, "total": 100 }, // Pagination\n  "message": "Course created successfully"\n}\n\n// Error response\n{\n  "error":     "Validation failed",\n  "code":      "VALIDATION_ERROR",\n  "requestId": "abc-123",\n  "details":   { "email": ["Invalid email format"] }\n}\n\n// Response helper\nconst ok      = (res: Response, data: unknown, meta?: object) =>\n  res.json({ data, ...(meta && { meta }) });\nconst created = (res: Response, data: unknown) =>\n  res.status(201).json({ data });\nconst noContent = (res: Response) =>\n  res.status(204).end();\n```\n\n### Pagination\n```typescript\nfunction buildPagination(page: number, limit: number, total: number) {\n  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);\n  return {\n    page, limit, total, totalPages,\n    hasNext:     page < totalPages,\n    hasPrevious: page > 1,\n  };\n}\n\napp.get("/api/courses", asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {\n  const { page = 1, limit = 10, sort = "createdAt", order = "desc" } = req.query;\n  const offset = (+page - 1) * +limit;\n\n  const [courses, total] = await Promise.all([\n    db.courses.findMany({ skip: offset, take: +limit, orderBy: { [sort]: order } }),\n    db.courses.count(),\n  ]);\n\n  ok(res, courses, buildPagination(+page, +limit, total));\n}));\n```\n\n### API Versioning\n```typescript\n// URI versioning (most common)\napp.use("/api/v1", v1Router);\napp.use("/api/v2", v2Router);\n\n// Header versioning\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  const version = req.headers["api-version"] ?? "1";\n  req.apiVersion = version;\n  next();\n});\n```\n\n### Swagger/OpenAPI Documentation\n```bash\nnpm install swagger-jsdoc swagger-ui-express\n```\n\n```typescript\nconst swaggerSpec = swaggerJsdoc({\n  definition: {\n    openapi: "3.0.0",\n    info: { title: "R-Learn API", version: "1.0.0" },\n    components: {\n      securitySchemes: {\n        BearerAuth: { type: "http", scheme: "bearer", bearerFormat: "JWT" }\n      }\n    }\n  },\n  apis: ["./src/routes/*.ts"],\n});\n\napp.use("/api/docs", swaggerUi.serve, swaggerUi.setup(swaggerSpec));\n\n/**\n * @openapi\n * /api/courses:\n *   get:\n *     summary: List all courses\n *     tags: [Courses]\n *     security: [{ BearerAuth: [] }]\n *     parameters:\n *       - in: query\n *         name: page\n *         schema: { type: integer, default: 1 }\n */\nrouter.get("/", listCourses);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use consistent response envelope ({data, meta, error})\n- Version your API from day one\n- Document before or while coding (not after)\n- Return pagination metadata with list endpoints\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between REST and GraphQL?\n2. How do you version an API without breaking existing clients?\n3. What is cursor-based pagination and when is it better than page-based?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a complete API with: consistent response format, cursor+page pagination, v1 versioning, full Swagger documentation, filtering and sorting on list endpoints.', 30, 1)

