('l100101', 'm1001', 'Security Fundamentals', E'# Web Security Fundamentals\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nSecurity is not a feature to add later -- it is a discipline woven into every decision. Understanding the threat landscape makes you a more responsible developer.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand the CIA triad\n- Know common attack categories\n- Apply defense-in-depth\n- Understand secure development lifecycle\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### The CIA Triad\n```\nConfidentiality  -- Only authorized parties can read data\nIntegrity        -- Data is not tampered with in transit or storage\nAvailability     -- Systems are accessible when needed\n\nAll security controls protect one or more of these three.\n```\n\n### Common Attack Categories\n```\nInjection Attacks:  SQL injection, command injection, LDAP injection\nAuthentication:     Brute force, credential stuffing, weak passwords\nAuthorization:      Privilege escalation, IDOR, BOLA\nData Exposure:      Sensitive data in logs, error messages, APIs\nConfiguration:      Default credentials, open S3 buckets, debug mode\nSupply Chain:       Malicious npm packages, dependency confusion\n```\n\n### Defense in Depth\n```\nLayer 1:  Network     -- Firewall, WAF, DDoS protection\nLayer 2:  Application -- Input validation, output encoding\nLayer 3:  Data        -- Encryption at rest and in transit\nLayer 4:  Identity    -- Strong auth, MFA, RBAC\nLayer 5:  Monitoring  -- Logging, alerting, SIEM\n\nNo single layer is enough -- attackers will bypass any one layer.\n```\n\n### HTTPS Everywhere\n```\nHTTPS = HTTP + TLS\n\nTLS provides:\n  1. Encryption      -- Data in transit is unreadable by intermediaries\n  2. Authentication  -- Server proves its identity via certificate\n  3. Integrity       -- Data cannot be tampered with undetected\n\nHSTS header enforces HTTPS:\nStrict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains\n```\n\n### Principle of Least Privilege\n```\nGrant only the minimum permissions needed for a task.\n\nExamples:\n  Database user for API: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE (no DROP, no CREATE)\n  API service account:   Read-only S3 access\n  Employee role:         View own profile only\n  Mentor role:           Manage own courses only\n  Admin role:            Full access\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- HTTPS everywhere, always\n- Principle of least privilege for all access\n- Fail securely (deny by default)\n- Keep dependencies updated (automated security scans)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the CIA triad?\n2. What is defense in depth?\n3. What is the principle of least privilege?\n\n## Assignment\nConduct a threat modeling exercise for R-Learn: identify assets, threats, vulnerabilities, and controls. Produce a STRIDE analysis for the authentication system.', 25, 1),

('l100201', 'm1002', 'Authentication Concepts', E'# Authentication Concepts\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAuthentication is the first line of defense. Understanding the full range of authentication mechanisms helps you choose the right one.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand authentication vs authorization\n- Know username/password, MFA, and SSO\n- Understand token-based authentication\n- Implement secure password handling\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Authentication vs Authorization\n```\nAuthentication:  Who are you? (Verify identity)\nAuthorization:   What can you do? (Verify permissions)\n\nAuthentication must come before authorization.\n\n401 Unauthorized = Not authenticated\n403 Forbidden    = Authenticated but not authorized\n```\n\n### Authentication Factors\n```\nFactor 1 (Something you KNOW):  Password, PIN, security question\nFactor 2 (Something you HAVE):  Phone (TOTP app), hardware key, SMS\nFactor 3 (Something you ARE):   Fingerprint, face ID, voice\n\nMFA = 2+ factors from different categories\n2FA = Factor 1 + Factor 2 (most common)\n```\n\n### Password Hashing\n```javascript\nimport bcrypt from "bcryptjs";\n\nconst SALT_ROUNDS = 12; // Higher = slower = more secure\n\n// Hash on registration\nasync function hashPassword(plaintext: string): Promise<string> {\n  return bcrypt.hash(plaintext, SALT_ROUNDS);\n}\n\n// Compare on login\nasync function verifyPassword(plaintext: string, hash: string): Promise<boolean> {\n  return bcrypt.compare(plaintext, hash);\n}\n\n// Registration\nconst user = await db.users.create({\n  data: {\n    email,\n    passwordHash: await hashPassword(password),\n  }\n});\n\n// Login\nconst user = await db.users.findUnique({ where: { email } });\nif (!user || !await verifyPassword(password, user.passwordHash)) {\n  throw new UnauthorizedError("Invalid email or password");\n  // Note: same message for both -- prevents email enumeration\n}\n```\n\n### TOTP (Time-Based One-Time Password) - MFA\n```javascript\nimport { authenticator } from "otplib";\nimport QRCode from "qrcode";\n\n// Generate secret on setup\nconst secret = authenticator.generateSecret();\nconst otpauth = authenticator.keyuri(user.email, "R-Learn", secret);\nconst qrCode  = await QRCode.toDataURL(otpauth);\n// Store secret encrypted in database\n\n// Verify on login\nconst isValid = authenticator.verify({ token: userEnteredCode, secret });\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Never store plaintext passwords\n- Use bcrypt with cost factor >= 12\n- Use same error message for invalid email/password (prevent enumeration)\n- Implement account lockout after N failed attempts\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between hashing and encryption?\n2. What is bcrypt and why use it over MD5?\n3. What is multi-factor authentication?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a complete registration and login flow: hash passwords with bcrypt, rate limit login attempts, implement email verification, and add TOTP-based 2FA.', 25, 1),

('l100301', 'm1003', 'Sessions & Cookies', E'# Sessions & Cookies\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nSessions and cookies are the traditional way to maintain state in HTTP. Understanding them is essential even when using JWTs.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand HTTP sessions\n- Implement secure cookies\n- Know session fixation and CSRF attacks\n- Compare sessions vs JWT\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### HTTP Cookies\n```http\n// Server sets cookie\nSet-Cookie: sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict; Path=/; Max-Age=3600\n\n// Browser sends cookie on subsequent requests\nCookie: sessionId=abc123\n```\n\n### Cookie Flags\n```\nHttpOnly     -- Not accessible via JavaScript (XSS protection)\nSecure       -- Only sent over HTTPS\nSameSite     -- Controls cross-site sending:\n               Strict: Never cross-site\n               Lax:    GET requests from links allowed\n               None:   All cross-site (requires Secure)\nMax-Age      -- Seconds until expiry\nExpires      -- Absolute expiry date\nDomain       -- Which domain receives cookie\nPath         -- URL path scope\n```\n\n### Sessions in Express\n```bash\nnpm install express-session connect-pg-simple\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport session from "express-session";\nimport pgSession from "connect-pg-simple";\n\nconst PgStore = pgSession(session);\n\napp.use(session({\n  store: new PgStore({ pool: db }),\n  secret:            process.env.SESSION_SECRET!,\n  resave:            false,\n  saveUninitialized: false,\n  cookie: {\n    httpOnly: true,\n    secure:   process.env.NODE_ENV === "production",\n    sameSite: "strict",\n    maxAge:   7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000, // 7 days\n  },\n}));\n\n// Login\napp.post("/login", async (req, res) => {\n  const user = await authenticate(req.body);\n  // Regenerate session ID on login (prevents fixation)\n  req.session.regenerate((err) => {\n    if (err) return next(err);\n    req.session.userId = user.id;\n    req.session.role   = user.role;\n    res.json({ user });\n  });\n});\n\n// Logout\napp.post("/logout", (req, res) => {\n  req.session.destroy((err) => {\n    res.clearCookie("connect.sid");\n    res.json({ ok: true });\n  });\n});\n```\n\n### CSRF Protection\n```typescript\nimport csrf from "csrf";\nimport Tokens from "csrf";\n\nconst tokens = new Tokens();\n\n// Generate token per session\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  if (!req.session.csrfSecret) {\n    req.session.csrfSecret = tokens.secretSync();\n  }\n  res.locals.csrfToken = tokens.create(req.session.csrfSecret);\n  next();\n});\n\n// Verify on state-changing requests\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  if (["GET", "HEAD", "OPTIONS"].includes(req.method)) return next();\n  const token = req.headers["x-csrf-token"] as string;\n  if (!tokens.verify(req.session.csrfSecret, token)) {\n    return res.status(403).json({ error: "Invalid CSRF token" });\n  }\n  next();\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always regenerate session ID on login\n- Use HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Strict on session cookies\n- Store sessions server-side (Redis or Postgres), not client-side\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a session cookie and a persistent cookie?\n2. What is session fixation and how do you prevent it?\n3. What is CSRF and how does SameSite protect against it?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement session-based authentication: login, logout, session storage in Postgres, CSRF protection, session regeneration on login, secure cookie configuration.', 30, 1),

('l100401', 'm1004', 'JSON Web Tokens (JWT)', E'# JSON Web Tokens (JWT)\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nJWT is the dominant mechanism for stateless authentication in REST APIs and SPAs. Understanding its structure and security properties is required for any API work.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand JWT structure\n- Sign and verify JWTs\n- Implement access + refresh token pattern\n- Know JWT security pitfalls\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### JWT Structure\n```\neyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9    <- Header (base64)\n.\neyJ1c2VySWQiOiIxMjMiLCJyb2xlIjoiYWRtaW4iLCJpYXQiOjE3MDAsImV4cCI6MTcwMH0  <- Payload (base64)\n.\nSflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c  <- Signature\n\nHeader:  { "alg": "HS256", "typ": "JWT" }\nPayload: { "userId": "123", "role": "admin", "iat": 1700000000, "exp": 1700000900 }\nSignature: HMACSHA256(base64(header) + "." + base64(payload), secret)\n```\n\n### Creating & Verifying\n```typescript\nimport jwt from "jsonwebtoken";\n\nconst ACCESS_SECRET  = process.env.JWT_SECRET!;\nconst REFRESH_SECRET = process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET!;\n\ninterface JwtPayload {\n  userId: string;\n  role:   string;\n}\n\nfunction signAccessToken(payload: JwtPayload): string {\n  return jwt.sign(payload, ACCESS_SECRET, {\n    expiresIn: "15m",\n    issuer:    "rlearn.com",\n    audience:  "rlearn-api",\n  });\n}\n\nfunction signRefreshToken(payload: JwtPayload): string {\n  return jwt.sign(payload, REFRESH_SECRET, {\n    expiresIn: "7d",\n  });\n}\n\nfunction verifyAccessToken(token: string): JwtPayload {\n  return jwt.verify(token, ACCESS_SECRET, {\n    issuer:   "rlearn.com",\n    audience: "rlearn-api",\n  }) as JwtPayload;\n}\n```\n\n### Access + Refresh Token Pattern\n```\nAccess Token:   Short-lived (15min), in-memory or Authorization header\nRefresh Token:  Long-lived (7d), HTTP-only cookie\n\nFlow:\n1. Login: server returns access token + refresh token (cookie)\n2. API calls: send access token in Authorization header\n3. Access token expires: call /auth/refresh with cookie\n4. Server: verifies refresh token, returns new access token\n5. Logout: delete refresh token from database + clear cookie\n```\n\n### Security Pitfalls\n```\n1. Storing JWT in localStorage\n   RISK: XSS attack can steal token\n   FIX:  Store access token in memory (JS variable)\n\n2. No expiry\n   RISK: Stolen token valid forever\n   FIX:  Set expiresIn on every token\n\n3. Weak secret\n   RISK: Secret guessable or brute-forced\n   FIX:  Use 256+ bit random secret (openssl rand -base64 32)\n\n4. "alg: none" attack\n   RISK: Malicious token with no signature accepted\n   FIX:  Always specify algorithm: { algorithms: ["HS256"] }\n\n5. No token revocation\n   RISK: Logged-out tokens still work\n   FIX:  Token blacklist for refresh tokens (store in Redis)\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use RS256 (asymmetric) in production for better key management\n- Add issuer and audience claims\n- Keep payload small (it is base64, not encrypted)\n- Never put sensitive data in JWT payload\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. Is JWT encrypted? What information is visible in a JWT?\n2. How do you revoke a JWT before it expires?\n3. What is the "alg:none" attack?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement full JWT auth: login returns access + refresh tokens, authentication middleware, token refresh endpoint, logout that invalidates refresh token, blacklist with Redis.', 30, 1),

('l100501', 'm1005', 'OAuth 2.0 & OpenID Connect', E'# OAuth 2.0 & OpenID Connect\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\n"Sign in with Google/GitHub" is on every modern app. Understanding OAuth enables you to implement third-party login and delegate access to external APIs.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand OAuth 2.0 flows\n- Implement Google/GitHub OAuth\n- Understand OpenID Connect\n- Handle OAuth tokens securely\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### OAuth 2.0 Roles\n```\nResource Owner:     The user (owns the data)\nClient:             Your application (wants access)\nAuthorization Server: Google, GitHub, etc. (issues tokens)\nResource Server:    Google APIs, GitHub API (where data lives)\n```\n\n### Authorization Code Flow (Web Apps)\n```\n1. User clicks "Sign in with Google"\n2. Redirect to Google: https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth\n   ?client_id=YOUR_ID\n   &redirect_uri=https://rlearn.com/auth/callback\n   &scope=openid email profile\n   &response_type=code\n   &state=RANDOM_STRING   (CSRF protection)\n\n3. User authenticates with Google, grants permissions\n\n4. Google redirects back:\n   https://rlearn.com/auth/callback?code=AUTHORIZATION_CODE&state=...\n\n5. Your server exchanges code for tokens:\n   POST https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token\n   { client_id, client_secret, code, redirect_uri, grant_type: "authorization_code" }\n   -> { access_token, id_token, refresh_token }\n\n6. Verify id_token (JWT), extract user info\n7. Create/update user in your database\n8. Issue your own session/JWT\n```\n\n### Implementation with Passport.js\n```bash\nnpm install passport passport-google-oauth20 passport-github2\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport passport from "passport";\nimport { Strategy as GoogleStrategy } from "passport-google-oauth20";\n\npassport.use(new GoogleStrategy({\n  clientID:     process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID!,\n  clientSecret: process.env.GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET!,\n  callbackURL:  "https://rlearn.com/auth/google/callback",\n}, async (accessToken, refreshToken, profile, done) => {\n  try {\n    let user = await db.users.findFirst({\n      where: { oauthProvider: "google", oauthId: profile.id },\n    });\n\n    if (!user) {\n      user = await db.users.create({\n        data: {\n          name:          profile.displayName,\n          email:         profile.emails![0].value,\n          oauthProvider: "google",\n          oauthId:       profile.id,\n          avatar:        profile.photos![0].value,\n        },\n      });\n    }\n    done(null, user);\n  } catch (err) { done(err); }\n}));\n\napp.get("/auth/google", passport.authenticate("google", { scope: ["openid", "email", "profile"] }));\napp.get("/auth/google/callback",\n  passport.authenticate("google", { session: false }),\n  (req, res) => {\n    const token = signAccessToken({ userId: req.user.id, role: req.user.role });\n    res.redirect(`/auth/success?token=${token}`);\n  }\n);\n```\n\n### OpenID Connect\n```\nOAuth 2.0 = Authorization (can app access data?)\nOIDC = Authentication (who is this user?) built on OAuth 2.0\n\nOIDC adds:\n  id_token -- JWT with user identity claims (sub, email, name)\n  /userinfo endpoint -- Fetch additional user info\n  Discovery -- /.well-known/openid-configuration\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always verify state parameter (CSRF protection)\n- Use PKCE for SPAs (no client_secret)\n- Store OAuth provider IDs, not their access tokens\n- Issue your own tokens after OAuth (do not use Google''s tokens as auth)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between OAuth and OpenID Connect?\n2. What is PKCE and why is it needed for SPAs?\n3. Why do you issue your own JWT after OAuth login?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement Google and GitHub OAuth login: create/find user in database, issue app JWT, handle account merging (same email, different providers).', 30, 1),

('l100601', 'm1006', 'Role-Based Access Control', E'# Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAuthorization determines what authenticated users can do. RBAC is the most common authorization model in enterprise applications.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Design a role and permission system\n- Implement role-based middleware\n- Handle attribute-based access control\n- Test authorization logic\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### RBAC Model\n```\nUser -- has --> Roles\nRole -- has --> Permissions\nPermission -- grants --> Action on Resource\n\nExample:\nUser: Alice\nRoles: [mentor]\nPermissions: [courses:read, courses:create, courses:update:own, lessons:write]\n```\n\n### Simple RBAC Middleware\n```typescript\nconst PERMISSIONS: Record<string, string[]> = {\n  admin: [\n    "users:read",   "users:write",   "users:delete",\n    "courses:read", "courses:write", "courses:delete",\n    "admin:access",\n  ],\n  mentor: [\n    "courses:read", "courses:write",\n    "lessons:read", "lessons:write",\n  ],\n  employee: [\n    "courses:read",\n    "lessons:read",\n    "progress:write",\n  ],\n};\n\nfunction hasPermission(role: string, permission: string): boolean {\n  return PERMISSIONS[role]?.includes(permission) ?? false;\n}\n\n// Middleware factory\nfunction authorize(permission: string) {\n  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    if (!req.user) return res.status(401).json({ error: "Unauthorized" });\n    if (!hasPermission(req.user.role, permission)) {\n      return res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden", required: permission });\n    }\n    next();\n  };\n}\n\n// Usage\nrouter.get  ("/",    authenticate, authorize("courses:read"),   listCourses);\nrouter.post ("/",    authenticate, authorize("courses:write"),  createCourse);\nrouter.delete("/:id", authenticate, authorize("courses:delete"), deleteCourse);\n```\n\n### Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)\n```typescript\n// ABAC: authorization based on attributes of user, resource, environment\nfunction canUpdateCourse(user: User, course: Course): boolean {\n  if (user.role === "admin")  return true;\n  if (user.role === "mentor" && course.authorId === user.id) return true;\n  return false;\n}\n\nrouter.put("/:id", authenticate, async (req, res, next) => {\n  const course = await courseService.getById(req.params.id);\n  if (!canUpdateCourse(req.user!, course)) {\n    return res.status(403).json({ error: "You do not own this course" });\n  }\n  // ... proceed with update\n});\n```\n\n### Field-Level Permissions\n```typescript\n// Admin sees all fields; employee sees limited fields\nfunction sanitizeUser(user: User, viewerRole: string): Partial<User> {\n  const base = { id: user.id, name: user.name, role: user.role };\n  if (viewerRole === "admin") {\n    return { ...base, email: user.email, xp: user.xp, createdAt: user.createdAt };\n  }\n  return base;\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Define permissions as strings: "resource:action" or "resource:action:scope"\n- Add scope for own-resource operations: "courses:update:own"\n- Test authorization separately from authentication\n- Log all 403 responses for security monitoring\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between RBAC and ABAC?\n2. How do you handle "users can only edit their own resources"?\n3. What is privilege escalation?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign and implement a full RBAC system for R-Learn: admin/mentor/employee roles, permissions for courses/lessons/users, resource ownership checks, and a permissions audit trail.', 30, 1),

('l100701', 'm1007', 'Password Security', E'# Password Security\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nPassword breaches are the most common entry point for attackers. Proper password handling is one of the most important security controls you can implement.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Hash passwords correctly with bcrypt\n- Implement password policies\n- Build secure password reset flows\n- Detect compromised passwords\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Why bcrypt?\n```\nMD5:     8 billion hashes/second (GPU) -- NEVER USE\nSHA-256: 2 billion hashes/second -- NEVER USE for passwords\nbcrypt:  100 hashes/second (cost 12) -- USE THIS\nArgon2:  Even slower/more secure -- Recommended in 2024\n\nbcrypt is slow by design. Slow hashing = slow brute force.\n```\n\n### bcrypt Implementation\n```typescript\nimport bcrypt from "bcryptjs";\n\n// REGISTRATION\nasync function registerUser(email: string, password: string) {\n  // Validate password policy before hashing\n  validatePasswordStrength(password);\n\n  const SALT_ROUNDS = 12; // ~300ms -- good balance\n  const hash = await bcrypt.hash(password, SALT_ROUNDS);\n\n  return db.users.create({ data: { email, passwordHash: hash } });\n}\n\n// LOGIN\nasync function loginUser(email: string, password: string) {\n  // IMPORTANT: Use timing-safe comparison\n  const user = await db.users.findUnique({ where: { email } });\n\n  // Always run bcrypt.compare to prevent timing attacks\n  const dummyHash = "$2b$12$dummyHashToPreventTimingAttacks....";\n  const isValid = user\n    ? await bcrypt.compare(password, user.passwordHash)\n    : await bcrypt.compare(password, dummyHash); // Same time even if no user\n\n  if (!user || !isValid) {\n    throw new UnauthorizedError("Invalid email or password");\n    // Same message -- prevents email enumeration\n  }\n\n  return user;\n}\n```\n\n### Password Policy\n```typescript\nimport { z } from "zod";\n\nconst PasswordSchema = z.string()\n  .min(8,  "Must be at least 8 characters")\n  .max(128, "Must be at most 128 characters")\n  .regex(/[A-Z]/, "Must contain uppercase letter")\n  .regex(/[a-z]/, "Must contain lowercase letter")\n  .regex(/[0-9]/, "Must contain number")\n  .regex(/[^A-Za-z0-9]/, "Must contain special character");\n\n// Check HaveIBeenPwned API for known compromised passwords\nasync function isCompromised(password: string): Promise<boolean> {\n  const hash = crypto.createHash("sha1").update(password).digest("hex").toUpperCase();\n  const prefix = hash.slice(0, 5);\n  const suffix = hash.slice(5);\n\n  const res  = await fetch(`https://api.pwnedpasswords.com/range/${prefix}`);\n  const text = await res.text();\n  return text.includes(suffix);\n}\n```\n\n### Secure Password Reset\n```typescript\n// 1. Generate cryptographically secure token\nimport crypto from "crypto";\n\nasync function requestPasswordReset(email: string) {\n  const user = await db.users.findUnique({ where: { email } });\n  if (!user) return; // Silent success -- prevent email enumeration\n\n  const token = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString("hex");\n  const hashedToken = crypto.createHash("sha256").update(token).digest("hex");\n\n  await db.passwordResets.create({\n    data: {\n      userId:    user.id,\n      tokenHash: hashedToken,\n      expiresAt: new Date(Date.now() + 60 * 60 * 1000), // 1 hour\n    },\n  });\n\n  await sendResetEmail(email, token); // Send raw token in email\n}\n\n// 2. Verify token\nasync function resetPassword(token: string, newPassword: string) {\n  const hashedToken = crypto.createHash("sha256").update(token).digest("hex");\n\n  const reset = await db.passwordResets.findFirst({\n    where: { tokenHash: hashedToken, expiresAt: { gt: new Date() } },\n  });\n\n  if (!reset) throw new AppError("Invalid or expired reset token", 400);\n\n  await db.users.update({\n    where: { id: reset.userId },\n    data:  { passwordHash: await bcrypt.hash(newPassword, 12) },\n  });\n\n  await db.passwordResets.delete({ where: { id: reset.id } });\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use bcrypt with cost 12+ (or argon2)\n- Always run hash comparison even when user not found (timing attack prevention)\n- Hash reset tokens before storing (token stored in email is like a password)\n- Invalidate all reset tokens after successful reset\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a timing attack?\n2. Why is MD5 not suitable for passwords?\n3. How do you securely implement password reset?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild complete password management: registration with strength validation, login with timing-safe comparison, rate-limited reset flow, compromised password check via HaveIBeenPwned API.', 30, 1),

('l100801', 'm1008', 'OWASP Top 10', E'# OWASP Top 10\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nOWASP Top 10 is the most referenced security framework. Knowing and preventing these vulnerabilities is expected of every professional developer.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Know all OWASP Top 10 categories\n- Understand each vulnerability with an example\n- Apply specific controls for each\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### OWASP Top 10 (2021)\n\n#### A01: Broken Access Control\n```\nProblem:  Users access resources they should not\nExample:  Change /api/orders/123 to /api/orders/124 -- see other user''s order\nFix:      Always check ownership before returning data (BOLA)\n```\n\n#### A02: Cryptographic Failures\n```\nProblem:  Sensitive data exposed due to weak/missing encryption\nExample:  Passwords in plaintext, PII in HTTP, weak cipher\nFix:      HTTPS everywhere, bcrypt, AES-256 for sensitive fields\n```\n\n#### A03: Injection\n```javascript\n// SQL Injection\nconst query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ''${email}''`;\n// email = "admin''--" -> logs in as admin!\n\n// FIXED: Parameterized queries\nconst user = await db.users.findFirst({ where: { email } }); // Prisma is safe\n// Or: db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1", [email]);\n```\n\n#### A04: Insecure Design\n```\nProblem:  Missing security controls in the design phase\nExample:  No rate limiting on login, no account lockout\nFix:      Threat modeling, security requirements in design phase\n```\n\n#### A05: Security Misconfiguration\n```\nProblem:  Default credentials, debug mode in prod, open cloud storage\nExample:  DEBUG=true in production, S3 bucket public by default\nFix:      Security hardening checklists, automated config scanning\n```\n\n#### A06: Vulnerable Components\n```bash\n# Check dependencies for known CVEs\nnpm audit\n\n# Automated dependency updates\n# GitHub Dependabot, Renovate Bot\n```\n\n#### A07: Authentication & Identification Failures\n```\nProblem:  Weak auth, no MFA, session not invalidated on logout\nFix:      Strong password policy, MFA, session revocation\n```\n\n#### A08: Software & Data Integrity Failures\n```\nProblem:  Unsigned packages, unsafe deserialization\nExample:  npm package replaced with malicious version\nFix:      Package integrity checks, supply chain security\n```\n\n#### A09: Security Logging & Monitoring\n```typescript\n// Log security events\nlogger.warn({ userId, ip, path }, "Failed login attempt");\nlogger.error({ userId, action: "delete-all-data" }, "Suspicious action");\n\n// Alert on anomalies\n// 100 failed logins from same IP -> block + alert\n```\n\n#### A10: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)\n```\nProblem:  Server makes requests to internal resources on user''s behalf\nExample:  POST /api/fetch-url with url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\nFix:      Allowlist valid URLs, block RFC1918 ranges, disable redirects\n```\n\n## Assignment\nConduct an OWASP Top 10 security review of the R-Learn API. Document each finding (category, CVSS score, example, fix). Fix at least A01, A03, A07.', 30, 1),

('l100901', 'm1009', 'XSS, CSRF & SQL Injection', E'# XSS, CSRF & SQL Injection\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nThese three attacks are responsible for the majority of web application breaches. Every developer must understand how to prevent them.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand and prevent XSS\n- Prevent CSRF attacks\n- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection\n- Test for these vulnerabilities\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)\n```\nAttacker injects malicious JavaScript into a page\nVictim''s browser executes attacker''s code\n\nTypes:\n  Stored XSS:    Payload stored in DB, affects all viewers\n  Reflected XSS: Payload in URL, immediate execution\n  DOM-based XSS: Payload in URL fragment, client-side execution\n```\n\n```javascript\n// VULNERABLE: Reflects user input unescaped\napp.get("/search", (req, res) => {\n  res.send(`<h1>Results for: ${req.query.q}</h1>`);\n  // URL: /search?q=<script>document.cookie</script>\n});\n\n// FIXED: Encode output\nimport { escapeHtml } from "./utils";\napp.get("/search", (req, res) => {\n  res.send(`<h1>Results for: ${escapeHtml(req.query.q)}</h1>`);\n});\n\n// BETTER: Use Content Security Policy\nres.setHeader("Content-Security-Policy",\n  "default-src ''self''; script-src ''self''; style-src ''self'' ''unsafe-inline''");\n\n// BEST: Use React/Vue (auto-escapes) and avoid dangerouslySetInnerHTML\n// In React: {userContent} is safe. dangerouslySetInnerHTML is not.\n```\n\n### CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery)\n```\nAttacker tricks a logged-in victim into making a request to your site\nVictim''s browser sends their cookies automatically\n\nExample:\n  Attacker''s site: <img src="https://bank.com/transfer?to=attacker&amount=1000">\n  Victim visits attacker''s page -> browser GETs bank URL with victim''s cookies\n```\n\n```typescript\n// Prevention 1: SameSite cookie\nres.cookie("session", token, { sameSite: "strict" });\n// SameSite=Strict: cookie NOT sent in cross-site requests\n\n// Prevention 2: CSRF Token\napp.use(csurf({ cookie: true }));\n\n// Frontend includes token in forms/headers\nfetch("/api/transfer", {\n  method: "POST",\n  headers: { "X-CSRF-Token": getCsrfToken() },\n});\n```\n\n### SQL Injection\n```sql\n-- VULNERABLE: String concatenation\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ''${email}'' AND password = ''${password}''\n-- email = '' OR 1=1 --\n-- Result: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '' OR 1=1 --'' ...\n-- Returns ALL users!\n\n-- FIXED: Parameterized queries\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1 AND password_hash = $2\n-- Parameters are never interpreted as SQL\n```\n\n```typescript\n// Using pg (parameterized)\nawait db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1", [email]);\n\n// Using Prisma (always parameterized -- no injection possible)\nawait db.users.findFirst({ where: { email } });\n\n// Second-order injection: stored data used in later query\n// Always parameterize even "trusted" data from your own DB\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- XSS: Encode output, use CSP, use modern frameworks (auto-escape)\n- CSRF: SameSite=Strict cookies, CSRF tokens for legacy forms\n- SQLi: Parameterized queries ALWAYS -- never string concatenation\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between stored and reflected XSS?\n2. How does SameSite protect against CSRF?\n3. Why do parameterized queries prevent SQL injection?\n\n## Assignment\nFind and fix 3 XSS, 2 CSRF, and 2 SQL injection vulnerabilities in a deliberately vulnerable Express app. Document each: how it works, impact, fix, and how to test.', 30, 1),

('l101001', 'm1010', 'HTTPS & API Security', E'# HTTPS & API Security\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nHTTPS is the foundation of web security. API-specific controls like rate limiting, input validation, and security headers form the next layer.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand TLS and certificate management\n- Configure security headers\n- Implement API-level security controls\n- Use WAF and DDoS protection\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### TLS Handshake\n```\n1. Client Hello:    Supported TLS versions, cipher suites\n2. Server Hello:    Chosen version, cipher, certificate\n3. Certificate:     Server proves identity (signed by CA)\n4. Key Exchange:    Derive session key (Diffie-Hellman)\n5. Finished:        Both sides confirm handshake\n6. Encrypted Data:  All subsequent traffic encrypted\n```\n\n### Certificate Types\n```\nDV (Domain Validated):  Verify domain ownership only. Free (Let''s Encrypt)\nOV (Organization):      Verify org identity. $100-500/year\nEV (Extended):          Highest verification. Browser shows green org name.\nWildcard: *.rlearn.com  One cert for all subdomains\nSAN:                    Multiple domains in one cert\n```\n\n### Security Headers\n```typescript\n// Use helmet for automatic security headers\nimport helmet from "helmet";\n\napp.use(helmet({\n  contentSecurityPolicy: {\n    directives: {\n      defaultSrc: ["''self''"],\n      scriptSrc:  ["''self''"],\n      styleSrc:   ["''self''", "''unsafe-inline''"],\n      imgSrc:     ["''self''", "data:", "https://cdn.rlearn.com"],\n      connectSrc: ["''self''", "https://api.rlearn.com"],\n      fontSrc:    ["''self''", "https://fonts.gstatic.com"],\n    },\n  },\n  hsts: { maxAge: 31536000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true },\n}));\n\n// What helmet sets:\n// Strict-Transport-Security   -- HTTPS only\n// X-Frame-Options: DENY       -- Clickjacking\n// X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff -- MIME sniffing\n// Content-Security-Policy     -- XSS prevention\n// X-XSS-Protection: 0         -- Let CSP handle it\n// Referrer-Policy             -- Limit referrer info\n```\n\n### API Rate Limiting & Throttling\n```typescript\nimport rateLimit  from "express-rate-limit";\nimport slowDown   from "express-slow-down";\nimport RedisStore from "rate-limit-redis";\n\n// Redis-backed rate limiter (works across multiple servers)\nconst limiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,\n  max:      100,\n  store:    new RedisStore({ client: redis }),\n  handler:  (req, res) => res.status(429).json({\n    error:       "Too many requests",\n    retryAfter:  Math.ceil(limiter.resetTime / 1000),\n  }),\n});\n\n// Slow down approaching limit (better UX than hard block)\nconst speedLimiter = slowDown({\n  windowMs:          15 * 60 * 1000,\n  delayAfter:        50,   // Start slowing after 50 requests\n  delayMs:           500,  // Add 500ms per request above limit\n  maxDelayMs:        5000, // Max 5s delay\n});\n\napp.use("/api/", speedLimiter, limiter);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use Let''s Encrypt for free, auto-renewing TLS certificates\n- Enable HSTS preload after confirming your site is HTTPS-only\n- Use a WAF (Cloudflare, AWS WAF) in front of your API\n- Rotate API keys and secrets regularly\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What does TLS protect against that HTTPS without TLS does not?\n2. What is HSTS preloading?\n3. What is a Web Application Firewall?\n\n## Assignment\nSecurity-harden a production API: configure TLS with Let''s Encrypt, set all helmet headers, Redis-backed rate limiting, add WAF rules, run SSL Labs test, achieve A+ rating.', 25, 1)

