('l120101', 'm1201', 'Git Fundamentals', E'# Git Fundamentals\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nGit is the universal version control system. Every professional developer uses it daily. Understanding how it works prevents data loss and enables confident collaboration.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand what version control is and why it matters\n- Initialize a repository and configure Git\n- Understand the working tree, staging area, and repository\n- Run the core Git workflow\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### What is Git?\n```\nGit is a distributed version control system:\n  - Tracks every change to every file over time\n  - Enables multiple developers to work simultaneously\n  - Allows reverting to any previous state\n  - Every clone is a full backup\n```\n\n### Setup\n```bash\ngit --version\ngit config --global user.name "Alice"\ngit config --global user.email "alice@example.com"\ngit config --global core.editor "code --wait"\ngit config --global init.defaultBranch main\n```\n\n### The Three Areas\n```\nWorking Tree  -- Files you are editing right now\nStaging Area  -- Files snapshotted for the next commit (git add)\nRepository    -- Committed history stored in .git folder\n\nWorking Tree  --git add-->  Staging  --git commit-->  Repository\n```\n\n### Core Workflow\n```bash\ngit init                     # Initialize repo\ngit status                   # See what has changed\ngit add file.js              # Stage a file\ngit add .                    # Stage all changes\ngit add -p                   # Stage interactively (hunk by hunk)\ngit commit -m "feat: add user login"\ngit log                      # View history\ngit log --oneline --graph    # Compact visual history\n```\n\n### Ignoring Files\n```bash\n# .gitignore\nnode_modules/\ndist/\n.env\n*.log\n.DS_Store\ncoverage/\n.vscode/\n\ngit check-ignore -v filename  # Debug why file is ignored\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Commit often with meaningful messages\n- Use .gitignore from the start (before first commit)\n- Configure user.name and user.email globally\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between git add and git commit?\n2. What are the three areas in Git?\n3. What does git status show?\n\n## Assignment\nInitialize a Git repo for a new project. Make 5 commits following conventional commit format. View the log with --oneline --graph. Create a .gitignore for a Node.js project.', 20, 1),

('l120201', 'm1202', 'Commits & History', E'# Commits & Git History\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nA clean, readable commit history is a gift to your future self and teammates. It serves as documentation, a debugging tool, and a code review aid.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write meaningful commit messages\n- Navigate and search history\n- Undo changes at different stages\n- Use git diff effectively\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Conventional Commits\n```\nformat: <type>(<scope>): <description>\n\nTypes:\n  feat:     New feature\n  fix:      Bug fix\n  docs:     Documentation only\n  style:    Formatting, no logic change\n  refactor: Code restructure, no feature/bug change\n  test:     Adding or fixing tests\n  chore:    Build, deps, config changes\n  perf:     Performance improvement\n\nExamples:\n  feat(auth): add JWT refresh token endpoint\n  fix(courses): resolve null pointer when author is deleted\n  docs(api): add OpenAPI spec for enrollment endpoints\n  chore(deps): upgrade express to 4.18.3\n```\n\n### Navigating History\n```bash\ngit log                          # Full log\ngit log --oneline                # One line per commit\ngit log --oneline --graph --all  # Visual branch tree\ngit log -n 10                    # Last 10 commits\ngit log --since="2024-01-01"     # Since date\ngit log --author="Alice"         # By author\ngit log -- src/auth.ts           # History of one file\ngit log --grep="fix"             # Search commit messages\n\ngit show abc1234                 # Show a specific commit\ngit show HEAD~2                  # Show 2 commits ago\n```\n\n### Diffing\n```bash\ngit diff                         # Unstaged changes\ngit diff --staged                # Staged changes (about to commit)\ngit diff main..feature           # Between branches\ngit diff abc123 def456           # Between commits\ngit diff HEAD~1 -- src/api.ts    # File changes since last commit\n```\n\n### Undoing Changes\n```bash\n# Working tree (before git add)\ngit restore file.js              # Discard changes to file\ngit restore .                    # Discard ALL working tree changes\n\n# Staged (after git add, before commit)\ngit restore --staged file.js     # Unstage a file (keep changes)\ngit restore --staged .           # Unstage everything\n\n# Committed (creates a new commit undoing changes -- SAFE)\ngit revert abc1234               # Undo a commit\ngit revert HEAD                  # Undo last commit\n\n# Committed (rewrites history -- DANGEROUS on shared branches)\ngit reset --soft HEAD~1          # Undo commit, keep staged\ngit reset --mixed HEAD~1         # Undo commit, keep in working tree\ngit reset --hard HEAD~1          # Undo commit, DISCARD changes\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Write commit messages in imperative mood: "Add login" not "Added login"\n- Keep commits atomic: one logical change per commit\n- Use git revert (not reset) on shared branches\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between git reset and git revert?\n2. What is the difference between git diff and git diff --staged?\n3. What are conventional commits?\n\n## Assignment\nCreate a feature branch, make 8 commits following conventional commits format, use git log --oneline --graph, practice git restore and git revert.', 20, 1),

('l120301', 'm1203', 'Branching & Merging', E'# Branching & Merging\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nBranches enable parallel development. Every feature, bug fix, and experiment should live on its own branch before merging.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create and switch branches\n- Merge branches with and without conflicts\n- Resolve merge conflicts\n- Use rebase for a linear history\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Branch Operations\n```bash\ngit branch                         # List local branches\ngit branch -a                      # List all (including remote)\ngit branch feature/user-auth       # Create branch\ngit checkout feature/user-auth     # Switch to branch\ngit checkout -b feature/user-auth  # Create AND switch\ngit switch -c feature/user-auth    # Modern syntax\n\ngit branch -d feature/done         # Delete merged branch\ngit branch -D feature/abandoned    # Force delete unmerged\ngit branch -m old-name new-name    # Rename\n```\n\n### Merging\n```bash\n# Merge feature into main\ngit checkout main\ngit merge feature/user-auth\n\n# Fast-forward merge (no divergent history)\n# Before: main -- A -- B\n#         feature:    C -- D\n# After:  main -- A -- B -- C -- D\n\n# Three-way merge (divergent histories -- creates merge commit)\n# --no-ff forces merge commit even if fast-forward possible\ngit merge --no-ff feature/user-auth\n```\n\n### Resolving Conflicts\n```bash\n# After a conflict:\ngit status  # Shows conflicted files\n\n# Conflict markers in file:\n<<<<<<< HEAD\nconst user = await getUser(id);\n=======\nconst user = await findUser(id);\n>>>>>>> feature/user-auth\n\n# Edit file to resolve, then:\ngit add conflicted-file.js\ngit commit  # Complete the merge\n\n# Or abort:\ngit merge --abort\n```\n\n### Rebase (Linear History)\n```bash\n# Instead of merging, replay your commits on top of main\ngit checkout feature/user-auth\ngit rebase main\n\n# Before:\n# main:    A -- B -- C\n# feature: A -- B -- D -- E\n\n# After rebase:\n# main:    A -- B -- C\n# feature: A -- B -- C -- D'' -- E''   (replayed on top of C)\n\n# Then merge (will be fast-forward -- no merge commit)\ngit checkout main\ngit merge feature/user-auth\n```\n\n### Golden Rebase Rule\n```\nNEVER rebase commits that are on a shared branch.\nRebase rewrites history. If others have pulled your commits,\nthey will have conflicts when you push the rebased history.\n\nSafe to rebase: your local feature branch\nNever rebase: main, develop, or any shared branch\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Branch for every feature, bug fix, and experiment\n- Keep branches short-lived (merge within days, not weeks)\n- Use --no-ff on main for explicit merge history\n- Rebase local branches before merging to reduce noise\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between merge and rebase?\n2. What is a fast-forward merge?\n3. How do you resolve a merge conflict?\n\n## Assignment\nSimulate a team workflow: create two feature branches from main, make changes to the same file, merge both back to main, and resolve the resulting conflict.', 25, 1),

('l120401', 'm1204', 'Remote Repositories', E'# Remote Repositories\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nRemote repos (GitHub, GitLab) are how teams share code. Understanding push, pull, and fetch is essential for any collaborative development.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Add and manage remotes\n- Push and pull changes\n- Handle diverged histories\n- Use SSH keys for authentication\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Working with Remotes\n```bash\n# Add remote\ngit remote add origin git@github.com:user/repo.git\ngit remote -v                       # List remotes\ngit remote rename origin upstream    # Rename\ngit remote remove old-remote        # Remove\n\n# Push\ngit push origin main                # Push to remote\ngit push -u origin main             # Push + track (first time)\ngit push                            # Push to tracked remote\ngit push --force-with-lease         # Safer force push (abort if remote changed)\n\n# Fetch (download but do not merge)\ngit fetch origin                    # Fetch all branches\ngit fetch origin main               # Fetch specific branch\n\n# Pull (fetch + merge)\ngit pull                            # Pull tracked branch\ngit pull origin main                # Pull specific branch\ngit pull --rebase                   # Pull + rebase instead of merge\n```\n\n### Clone\n```bash\ngit clone git@github.com:org/repo.git         # Clone main branch\ngit clone -b develop git@github.com:org/repo  # Clone specific branch\ngit clone --depth=1 git@github.com:org/repo   # Shallow clone (faster)\n```\n\n### SSH Keys Setup\n```bash\nssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "alice@example.com"\ncat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub           # Copy public key\n# Paste in GitHub Settings -> SSH Keys\n\nssh -T git@github.com               # Test connection\n# Hi alice! You have successfully authenticated...\n```\n\n### Handling Diverged Histories\n```bash\n# You and teammate both pushed to main\ngit pull --rebase    # Replay your commits on top of theirs\n# vs\ngit pull            # Creates merge commit\n\n# Configure pull behavior\ngit config --global pull.rebase true    # Always rebase\ngit config --global pull.ff only        # Only fast-forward pulls\n```\n\n### Tracking Branches\n```bash\ngit branch -u origin/main            # Track remote branch\ngit branch -vv                       # Show tracking info\ngit status                           # Shows ahead/behind count\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use SSH keys not HTTPS (no password prompts)\n- Use --force-with-lease not --force (safer)\n- Fetch before starting work to see what teammates pushed\n- Use pull --rebase to keep history linear\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between git fetch and git pull?\n2. What does git push -u origin main do?\n3. What is a tracking branch?\n\n## Assignment\nSet up SSH keys, fork a repo on GitHub, clone it, create a branch, push it, and open a pull request. Practice fetching upstream changes and rebasing your branch.', 20, 1),

('l120501', 'm1205', 'Pull Requests & Code Review', E'# Pull Requests & Code Review\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nPull requests are the primary mechanism for code review, knowledge sharing, and quality control in professional teams.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Create effective pull requests\n- Review code constructively\n- Use GitHub review tools\n- Handle review feedback\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Creating a Good PR\n```markdown\n## Summary\n- Added JWT refresh token endpoint\n- Refresh token stored in HTTP-only cookie\n- Access token validity reduced to 15 minutes\n\n## Why\nLong-lived access tokens are a security risk. This pattern\nreduces the window of exposure if a token is compromised.\n\n## Testing\n- [ ] Unit tests for token generation\n- [ ] Integration test for refresh endpoint\n- [ ] Manual test: login, wait 15min, verify auto-refresh works\n- [ ] Tested on Safari (cookie behavior differs)\n\n## Screenshots\n[Screenshot of Network tab showing refresh request]\n\n## Breaking Changes\nFrontend must handle 401 response by calling /refresh endpoint.\n```\n\n### PR Best Practices\n```\nSize:         Small PRs (<400 lines) get better reviews\nFocus:        One logical change per PR\nDescription:  Why, not just what\nTests:        Include tests with the PR (not after)\nSelf-review:  Review your own diff before requesting review\n```\n\n### Code Review Guidelines\n```\nAs AUTHOR:\n  - Respond to every comment\n  - Do not take feedback personally\n  - Explain your reasoning when you disagree\n  - Mark resolved comments as resolved\n  - Re-request review after addressing feedback\n\nAs REVIEWER:\n  - Review within 24 hours\n  - Be specific: "Consider using Map here because..." not "This is wrong"\n  - Ask questions: "What does this handle when...?"\n  - Approve when code is good enough, not perfect\n  - Distinguish: nit (style), suggestion (improvement), required (must fix)\n```\n\n### GitHub Review Commands\n```bash\ngh pr create --title "feat: add refresh token" --body "$(cat pr-body.md)"\ngh pr list\ngh pr checkout 42          # Checkout PR locally to test\ngh pr review 42 --approve\ngh pr review 42 --request-changes --body "Please add tests"\ngh pr merge 42 --squash    # Merge with squash\ngh pr merge 42 --rebase    # Merge with rebase\n```\n\n### Protected Branch Rules (GitHub)\n```\nFor main branch:\n  Require pull request before merging\n  Require 1+ approvals\n  Require status checks (tests, lint) to pass\n  Restrict who can push directly\n  Require linear history (no merge commits)\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Self-review your diff before requesting review\n- Keep PRs small -- break large features into smaller PRs\n- Automate what you can (lint, tests) so reviewers focus on logic\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What makes a good pull request description?\n2. How do you handle disagreement during code review?\n3. What is a protected branch?\n\n## Assignment\nOpen a PR with a complete description (summary, why, testing checklist, screenshots). Review a teammate''s PR with at least 3 constructive comments. Respond to review feedback on your own PR.', 20, 1),

('l120601', 'm1206', 'Git Workflows', E'# Git Workflows\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDifferent teams use different Git workflows. Knowing the main workflows helps you adapt to any team and contribute to workflow decisions.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand Gitflow, GitHub Flow, and trunk-based development\n- Choose the right workflow for team size\n- Manage releases with tags\n- Handle hotfixes correctly\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### GitHub Flow (Simple -- recommended for most teams)\n```\nmain is always deployable\n\n1. Create branch from main:  git checkout -b feature/user-auth\n2. Make commits\n3. Open Pull Request\n4. Review and discuss\n5. Deploy from branch to staging (optional)\n6. Merge to main\n7. Deploy main to production\n8. Delete branch\n```\n\n### Gitflow (Complex releases)\n```\nBranches:\n  main     -- Production-ready code (tagged releases)\n  develop  -- Integration branch for features\n  feature/* -- Feature branches (from develop)\n  release/* -- Release prep (from develop, merge to main + develop)\n  hotfix/*  -- Emergency fixes (from main, merge to main + develop)\n\nWhen to use:\n  - Multiple versions in production\n  - Scheduled releases (not continuous deployment)\n  - Large teams with strict release control\n```\n\n### Trunk-Based Development (Modern, fastest)\n```\nEveryone commits to main (or short-lived branches < 1 day)\nFeature flags hide incomplete features\nCI runs on every commit\nDeploy multiple times per day\n\nWhen to use:\n  - High-performing, experienced teams\n  - Continuous deployment\n  - Solid test coverage\n```\n\n### Tags & Releases\n```bash\n# Lightweight tag\ngit tag v1.0.0\n\n# Annotated tag (preferred -- stored as full object)\ngit tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Version 1.0.0 -- Initial production release"\n\ngit tag                          # List tags\ngit show v1.0.0                  # Show tag details\ngit push origin v1.0.0           # Push specific tag\ngit push origin --tags           # Push all tags\n\n# Semantic versioning\nMAJOR.MINOR.PATCH\n  MAJOR: Breaking changes\n  MINOR: New features (backward compatible)\n  PATCH: Bug fixes (backward compatible)\n```\n\n### Hotfix Workflow\n```bash\n# Bug found in production (v1.2.3)\ngit checkout -b hotfix/login-crash v1.2.3  # Branch from tag\n# Fix the bug\ngit add .\ngit commit -m "fix: prevent null pointer in login flow"\ngit tag -a v1.2.4 -m "Hotfix: login crash"\ngit checkout main\ngit merge hotfix/login-crash\ngit push && git push --tags\ngit checkout develop\ngit merge hotfix/login-crash  # Also merge to develop\ngit branch -d hotfix/login-crash\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Start with GitHub Flow -- adopt more complexity only when needed\n- Tag every release, use semantic versioning\n- Protect main -- no direct pushes\n- Delete branches after merge (keeps repo clean)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between GitHub Flow and Gitflow?\n2. What is trunk-based development?\n3. What is semantic versioning?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement GitHub Flow for a small project: create 3 feature branches, open PRs, merge them, tag a v1.0.0 release, then simulate a hotfix as v1.0.1.', 20, 1),

('l120701', 'm1207', 'Advanced Git', E'# Advanced Git Techniques\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAdvanced Git commands solve real problems: recovering lost work, splitting commits, finding bugs, and managing complex histories.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Use git stash for temporary work storage\n- Cherry-pick specific commits\n- Use git bisect to find bugs\n- Manage the reflog\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### git stash\n```bash\n# Save work in progress without committing\ngit stash                          # Stash working tree + staged\ngit stash push -m "WIP: login form validation"\ngit stash list                     # List stashes\ngit stash pop                      # Apply most recent + remove\ngit stash apply stash@{1}         # Apply specific stash (keeps it)\ngit stash drop stash@{0}          # Delete a stash\ngit stash clear                    # Delete all stashes\ngit stash show -p                  # Show stash diff\n\n# Use case: urgent fix needed while in middle of feature\ngit stash                          # Save current work\ngit checkout -b hotfix/urgent      # Switch to hotfix\n# ... fix ...\ngit checkout feature/my-feature\ngit stash pop                      # Restore work\n```\n\n### Cherry-pick\n```bash\n# Apply a specific commit from one branch to another\ngit log --oneline feature-branch   # Find commit hash\ngit checkout main\ngit cherry-pick abc1234             # Apply that commit to main\ngit cherry-pick abc1234 def5678    # Multiple commits\ngit cherry-pick abc1234^..def5678  # Range\n\n# Use case: backport a bug fix to an older release branch\n```\n\n### git bisect (Find regression)\n```bash\ngit bisect start\ngit bisect bad HEAD              # Current commit is broken\ngit bisect good v1.2.3           # This version was good\n# Git checks out middle commit\n# Test the app...\ngit bisect good                  # This commit is fine\n# Git narrows range, checks out another middle commit\ngit bisect bad                   # This commit is broken\n# Repeat until bisect finds the exact commit that introduced the bug\ngit bisect reset                 # End bisect session\n```\n\n### git reflog (Safety net)\n```bash\n# reflog records every HEAD movement (even resets!)\ngit reflog\n# abc1234 HEAD@{0}: commit: feat: add search\n# def5678 HEAD@{1}: reset: moving to HEAD~2  <- The reset you regret\n# ghi9012 HEAD@{2}: commit: fix: user profile\n\n# Recover from accidental reset\ngit reset --hard ghi9012          # Go back to before the reset\n# Or create a branch at that point\ngit branch recovered-work ghi9012\n```\n\n### Interactive Rebase (Clean up commits)\n```bash\ngit rebase -i HEAD~5              # Edit last 5 commits\n\n# Editor opens:\n# pick abc1 feat: add user model\n# pick def2 WIP\n# pick ghi3 fix typo\n# pick jkl4 more wip\n# pick mno5 fix: complete user model\n\n# Change to:\n# pick abc1 feat: add user model\n# squash def2 WIP              <- merge into previous\n# squash ghi3 fix typo         <- merge into previous\n# squash jkl4 more wip         <- merge into previous\n# squash mno5 fix: complete user model <- merge into previous\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use git stash for quick context switching\n- Use reflog as a safety net -- almost nothing is truly lost in Git\n- Use interactive rebase to clean up before opening a PR\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What does git stash do?\n2. What is git bisect used for?\n3. How do you recover from an accidental git reset --hard?\n\n## Assignment\nPractice: stash work to apply a hotfix and restore, cherry-pick a commit from one branch to another, use git bisect to find which commit broke a test, recover from a reset using reflog.', 25, 1),

('l120801', 'm1208', 'GitHub Actions & CI/CD', E'# GitHub Actions & CI/CD\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nContinuous Integration/Deployment automates testing and shipping. It catches bugs before they reach production and enables fast, confident releases.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Write GitHub Actions workflows\n- Run tests and linting on every PR\n- Build and deploy automatically on merge\n- Use secrets and environment variables\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Workflow Syntax\n```yaml\n# .github/workflows/ci.yml\nname: CI\n\non:\n  push:\n    branches: [main, develop]\n  pull_request:\n    branches: [main]\n\nenv:\n  NODE_VERSION: "20"\n\njobs:\n  test:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    \n    services:\n      postgres:\n        image: postgres:16\n        env:\n          POSTGRES_PASSWORD: postgres\n          POSTGRES_DB: rlearn_test\n        options: >-\n          --health-cmd pg_isready\n          --health-interval 10s\n          --health-timeout 5s\n          --health-retries 5\n        ports:\n          - 5432:5432\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n\n      - uses: actions/setup-node@v4\n        with:\n          node-version: ${{ env.NODE_VERSION }}\n          cache: npm\n\n      - name: Install dependencies\n        run: npm ci\n\n      - name: Run linter\n        run: npm run lint\n\n      - name: Run type check\n        run: npm run typecheck\n\n      - name: Run tests\n        run: npm test\n        env:\n          DATABASE_URL: postgresql://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/rlearn_test\n          JWT_SECRET: test-secret-min-32-characters-long\n\n      - name: Upload coverage\n        uses: codecov/codecov-action@v4\n```\n\n### Deploy Workflow\n```yaml\n# .github/workflows/deploy.yml\nname: Deploy\n\non:\n  push:\n    branches: [main]\n\njobs:\n  deploy:\n    needs: [test]  # Only deploy if tests pass\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: production\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-node@v4\n        with: { node-version: "20", cache: npm }\n\n      - run: npm ci\n      - run: npm run build\n\n      - name: Deploy to Vercel\n        run: npx vercel deploy --prod --token ${{ secrets.VERCEL_TOKEN }}\n        env:\n          VERCEL_ORG_ID:     ${{ secrets.VERCEL_ORG_ID }}\n          VERCEL_PROJECT_ID: ${{ secrets.VERCEL_PROJECT_ID }}\n```\n\n### Secrets\n```bash\n# Add in GitHub: Settings -> Secrets -> Actions\n# Access in workflow:\n${{ secrets.DATABASE_URL }}\n${{ secrets.JWT_SECRET }}\n${{ secrets.VERCEL_TOKEN }}\n\n# Environment variables (non-secret)\n${{ vars.NODE_ENV }}\n${{ vars.API_URL }}\n```\n\n### Branch Protection with Status Checks\n```\nGitHub Settings -> Branch Rules -> Add rule for "main":\n  Require status checks before merging:\n    - CI / test\n    - CI / lint\n  Require branches to be up to date before merging\n  Require pull request reviews: 1\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Run tests on every PR (not just main)\n- Cache node_modules in CI (npm cache)\n- Deploy only after tests pass (use needs:)\n- Use environments for staging/production approvals\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between CI and CD?\n2. What is a GitHub Actions workflow trigger?\n3. How do you use secrets in GitHub Actions?\n\n## Assignment\nCreate a complete CI/CD pipeline: lint + typecheck + test on every PR, deploy to Vercel on merge to main, require CI to pass before merge, post coverage report as PR comment.', 25, 1)

