('l130101', 'm1301', 'Layered Architecture', E'# Layered Architecture\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nLayered architecture is the most common backend pattern. It separates concerns so that each layer can be changed, tested, and scaled independently.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand the 3-tier layered architecture\n- Implement Controller-Service-Repository\n- Know the dependency direction rule\n- Test each layer independently\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### The Layers\n```\nPresentation Layer (Controller)\n  Receives HTTP requests, validates input, sends responses\n  Does NOT contain business logic\n\nBusiness Logic Layer (Service)\n  Implements business rules and workflows\n  Does NOT know about HTTP or databases\n\nData Access Layer (Repository)\n  Database queries only\n  Does NOT contain business logic\n\nDependency direction: Controllers -> Services -> Repositories\nServices do NOT import controllers\nRepositories do NOT import services\n```\n\n### Implementation\n```typescript\n// Repository: database only\nclass CourseRepository {\n  async findById(id: string): Promise<Course | null> {\n    return this.db.courses.findUnique({ where: { id } });\n  }\n\n  async findMany(filter: CourseFilter): Promise<Course[]> {\n    return this.db.courses.findMany({ where: this.buildWhere(filter) });\n  }\n\n  async create(data: CreateCourseData): Promise<Course> {\n    return this.db.courses.create({ data });\n  }\n}\n\n// Service: business logic only\nclass CourseService {\n  constructor(private repo: CourseRepository) {}\n\n  async publish(courseId: string, userId: string): Promise<Course> {\n    const course = await this.repo.findById(courseId);\n    if (!course) throw new NotFoundError("Course");\n    if (course.authorId !== userId) throw new ForbiddenError();\n    if (course.moduleCount === 0) throw new ValidationError({ base: ["Cannot publish empty course"] });\n    return this.repo.update(courseId, { publishedAt: new Date() });\n  }\n}\n\n// Controller: HTTP only\nclass CourseController {\n  constructor(private service: CourseService) {}\n\n  publish = asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {\n    const course = await this.service.publish(req.params.id, req.user!.id);\n    res.json({ data: course });\n  });\n}\n```\n\n### Testing Each Layer\n```typescript\n// Repository test: uses real database (integration test)\ntest("findById returns null for unknown id", async () => {\n  const result = await repo.findById("unknown-id");\n  expect(result).toBeNull();\n});\n\n// Service test: mocks repository\ntest("publish throws if course not owned by user", async () => {\n  mockRepo.findById.mockResolvedValue({ authorId: "other-user" });\n  await expect(service.publish("id", "my-user")).rejects.toThrow(ForbiddenError);\n});\n\n// Controller test: mocks service\ntest("POST /publish returns 200", async () => {\n  mockService.publish.mockResolvedValue(fakeCourse);\n  const res = await request(app).post("/courses/1/publish").set("Authorization", ...);\n  expect(res.status).toBe(200);\n});\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Each layer only depends on layers below it\n- Inject dependencies (do not import directly) for testability\n- Keep each class focused on one responsibility\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is layered architecture?\n2. What is the dependency direction rule?\n3. How do you test each layer independently?\n\n## Assignment\nRefactor a monolithic Express route file into Controller + Service + Repository. Add unit tests for the service layer using mock repositories.', 30, 1),

('l130201', 'm1302', 'Monolithic vs Microservices', E'# Monolithic vs Microservices Architecture\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nChoosing the wrong architecture for your scale is expensive. Understanding the real trade-offs helps you make the right call.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Define monolith and microservices\n- Understand the real trade-offs\n- Know when to use each\n- Understand the strangler fig migration pattern\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Monolith\n```\nAll components in one deployable unit:\n  - Single codebase\n  - Single database\n  - Deployed all at once\n  - Scaled horizontally (multiple instances of the whole thing)\n\nPros:\n  Simple to develop and test locally\n  Easy to refactor across the whole codebase\n  No network latency between components\n  Simple deployment (one thing to deploy)\n  Strong consistency (single database, single transaction)\n\nCons:\n  Everything restarts on every deploy\n  One bug can take down the whole system\n  Scaling requires scaling everything\n  Large codebase becomes harder to understand\n  Technology lock-in\n```\n\n### Microservices\n```\nSmall, independently deployable services:\n  - Each service owns its data\n  - Services communicate via APIs or messages\n  - Each deployed independently\n  - Each can be scaled independently\n\nPros:\n  Independent deployments (deploy one service without touching others)\n  Independent scaling (scale only high-traffic services)\n  Technology diversity (each service can use different stack)\n  Fault isolation (one service failing does not take down all)\n\nCons:\n  Distributed systems complexity (network failures, latency)\n  Data consistency across services is hard\n  Operational complexity (many services to monitor/deploy)\n  More infrastructure needed\n  Debugging across services is harder\n```\n\n### When to Use Which\n```\nStart with a monolith if:\n  - Team < 20 engineers\n  - Product has not found product-market fit yet\n  - Simple domain\n  - You do not know the right service boundaries yet\n\nConsider microservices when:\n  - Different parts scale very differently\n  - Different teams own different parts and deploy independently\n  - You need different technology stacks per component\n  - You have operational maturity to handle distributed systems\n\nReal world: Most successful startups start as monoliths\n(Twitter, Shopify, GitHub, Stack Overflow all started as monoliths)\n```\n\n### Strangler Fig Migration\n```\nGradually replace monolith functionality:\n1. Route requests through a facade/gateway\n2. Implement new service for one feature\n3. Route that feature''s traffic to new service\n4. Delete old code from monolith\n5. Repeat for next feature\n\nNever try to rewrite the whole thing at once.\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Build a modular monolith first (good module boundaries)\n- Extract services only when you have a clear reason\n- Define service boundaries along domain lines (DDD bounded contexts)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the main advantage of microservices over monoliths?\n2. What is the strangler fig pattern?\n3. When would you NOT use microservices?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign R-Learn as both a monolith and microservices. For microservices, define service boundaries, APIs between services, and which database each service owns.', 25, 1),

('l130301', 'm1303', 'API Gateway & Service Mesh', E'# API Gateway & Service Mesh\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nIn microservices architectures, gateways handle cross-cutting concerns (auth, rate limiting, routing) and service meshes handle service-to-service communication.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand API gateway responsibilities\n- Implement a simple gateway\n- Understand service mesh concepts\n- Use Kong or AWS API Gateway\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### API Gateway Responsibilities\n```\nSingle entry point for all clients:\n  Authentication/Authorization  -- Verify tokens before routing\n  Rate Limiting                 -- Per-client or per-endpoint limits\n  Request Routing               -- Route to correct service\n  Protocol Translation          -- HTTP to gRPC, REST to WebSocket\n  Request/Response Transform    -- Add headers, rename fields\n  Load Balancing                -- Distribute across service instances\n  SSL Termination               -- TLS handled at gateway\n  Caching                       -- Cache responses\n  Logging/Monitoring            -- Centralized access logs\n  Circuit Breaking              -- Stop cascading failures\n```\n\n### Simple Express Gateway\n```typescript\nimport { createProxyMiddleware } from "http-proxy-middleware";\n\nconst app = express();\n\n// Auth middleware applies to all routes\napp.use(authenticate);\napp.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60000, max: 100 }));\n\n// Route to services\napp.use("/api/courses",   createProxyMiddleware({ target: "http://course-service:3001",   changeOrigin: true }));\napp.use("/api/users",     createProxyMiddleware({ target: "http://user-service:3002",     changeOrigin: true }));\napp.use("/api/payments",  createProxyMiddleware({ target: "http://payment-service:3003",  changeOrigin: true }));\napp.use("/api/analytics", createProxyMiddleware({ target: "http://analytics-service:3004", changeOrigin: true }));\n```\n\n### Service Mesh (Istio/Linkerd)\n```\nService mesh: infrastructure layer for service-to-service communication\n\nWhat it handles (automatically, without code changes):\n  Mutual TLS          -- Encrypted, authenticated service calls\n  Load balancing      -- Smart traffic distribution\n  Circuit breaking    -- Auto-detect and isolate failing services\n  Retries             -- Automatic retry with backoff\n  Tracing             -- Distributed request tracing\n  Traffic management  -- Canary deployments, A/B testing\n\nSidecar pattern:\n  Each service instance runs with a sidecar proxy (Envoy)\n  All traffic in/out goes through the sidecar\n  Sidecar handles all mesh features\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Put all cross-cutting concerns in the gateway (not each service)\n- Use a managed gateway (AWS API Gateway, Kong) rather than building your own\n- Service mesh is for mature microservices environments -- overkill for small setups\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is an API gateway and what does it do?\n2. What is the sidecar pattern?\n3. What is the difference between an API gateway and a load balancer?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a simple API gateway in Express: JWT validation, rate limiting, route to 3 mock services, centralized error handling, request logging with request ID propagation.', 25, 1),

('l130401', 'm1304', 'Event-Driven Architecture', E'# Event-Driven Architecture\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nEvent-driven systems decouple services and enable real-time features. They are foundational to modern scalable backend design.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand events, producers, and consumers\n- Implement event-driven patterns\n- Know event sourcing and CQRS\n- Design for eventual consistency\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Events vs Commands vs Queries\n```\nCommand:  "Create user Alice"        -- Intent, expect result\nQuery:    "Get user Alice"           -- Read, no side effects\nEvent:    "UserCreated(Alice, 2024)" -- Fact, already happened\n\nCommands can fail; Events are facts (already occurred)\n```\n\n### Simple Event Bus\n```typescript\ntype EventHandler<T> = (event: T) => Promise<void>;\n\nclass EventBus {\n  private handlers = new Map<string, EventHandler<unknown>[]>();\n\n  subscribe<T>(eventType: string, handler: EventHandler<T>) {\n    const existing = this.handlers.get(eventType) ?? [];\n    this.handlers.set(eventType, [...existing, handler as EventHandler<unknown>]);\n  }\n\n  async publish<T>(eventType: string, event: T) {\n    const handlers = this.handlers.get(eventType) ?? [];\n    await Promise.all(handlers.map(h => h(event).catch(err =>\n      logger.error({ err, eventType }, "Event handler failed")\n    )));\n  }\n}\n\n// Publishers\nclass UserService {\n  async createUser(data: CreateUserDto) {\n    const user = await this.repo.create(data);\n    await this.eventBus.publish("UserCreated", { userId: user.id, email: user.email, role: user.role });\n    return user;\n  }\n}\n\n// Subscribers\nemailService.subscribe("UserCreated", async ({ email }) => {\n  await sendWelcomeEmail(email);\n});\n\nnotificationService.subscribe("UserCreated", async ({ userId }) => {\n  await createDefaultNotifications(userId);\n});\n\nanalytics.subscribe("UserCreated", async (event) => {\n  await trackEvent("user_registered", event);\n});\n```\n\n### Saga Pattern (Distributed Transactions)\n```\nChoreography saga: each service publishes events, others react\n\n1. OrderService: OrderPlaced event\n2. PaymentService: listens -> processes payment -> PaymentProcessed event\n3. InventoryService: listens -> reserves stock -> StockReserved event\n4. ShippingService: listens -> schedules delivery -> OrderShipped event\n\nOn failure:\n3b. InventoryService: StockUnavailable event\n2b. PaymentService: listens -> refunds payment -> PaymentRefunded event\n1b. OrderService: listens -> marks order failed -> OrderCancelled event\n```\n\n### CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)\n```\nSeparate read and write models:\n\nWrite side (Commands):\n  Optimized for consistency\n  Complex domain model\n  Normalized database\n\nRead side (Queries):\n  Optimized for read performance\n  Denormalized views / projections\n  Read replicas, search indexes, caches\n\nExample:\n  Write: POST /api/courses (creates in PostgreSQL)\n  Event: CourseCreated\n  Projection: Update Elasticsearch index for search\n  Read: GET /api/courses?search=react (queries Elasticsearch)\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Events should be immutable facts (past tense)\n- Include enough context in event payload (not just IDs)\n- Handle event handler failures gracefully (idempotent handlers + retry)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between an event and a command?\n2. What is eventual consistency?\n3. What is CQRS?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign a course enrollment flow using events: CourseEnrolled -> send welcome email, update leaderboard, grant initial XP, create progress record. Implement with an in-memory event bus.', 25, 1),

('l130501', 'm1305', 'Message Queues & Pub/Sub', E'# Message Queues & Pub/Sub\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nMessage queues decouple services, buffer load spikes, and guarantee delivery. They power background jobs, email sending, and async processing at scale.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand queues vs pub/sub\n- Use BullMQ for job queues\n- Design for reliability\n- Handle failures with dead letter queues\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Queue vs Pub/Sub\n```\nQueue (Point-to-Point):\n  One producer -> One consumer\n  Each message processed by exactly one consumer\n  Use: task distribution, background jobs\n\nPub/Sub (Broadcast):\n  One producer -> Many consumers\n  Each subscriber receives every message\n  Use: notifications, event broadcasting\n\nTechnology choices:\n  Redis/BullMQ:    Simple queues, job scheduling\n  RabbitMQ:        Advanced routing, complex topologies\n  Apache Kafka:    High-throughput, event streaming, replay\n  AWS SQS/SNS:     Managed, serverless\n  Google Pub/Sub:  Managed, global\n```\n\n### BullMQ (Redis-backed)\n```bash\nnpm install bullmq ioredis\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport { Queue, Worker, Job } from "bullmq";\nimport Redis from "ioredis";\n\nconst connection = new Redis({ host: "localhost", port: 6379 });\n\n// Define queues\nconst emailQueue   = new Queue("emails",   { connection });\nconst exportQueue  = new Queue("exports",  { connection });\nconst xpQueue      = new Queue("xp-awards", { connection });\n\n// Add jobs\nawait emailQueue.add("welcome-email", {\n  to:   "alice@example.com",\n  name: "Alice",\n  type: "welcome"\n}, {\n  attempts:   3,          // Retry 3 times on failure\n  backoff: { type: "exponential", delay: 5000 },\n  removeOnComplete: 1000, // Keep last 1000 completed\n});\n\n// Delayed job (send 24h after signup)\nawait emailQueue.add("onboarding-email", { userId }, { delay: 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000 });\n\n// Recurring job (cron)\nawait emailQueue.add("weekly-digest", {}, { repeat: { cron: "0 9 * * 1" } }); // Every Monday 9am\n\n// Worker (processes jobs)\nconst emailWorker = new Worker("emails", async (job: Job) => {\n  const { to, name, type } = job.data;\n  await sendEmail({ to, subject: getSubject(type), body: getBody(name, type) });\n  await job.updateProgress(100);\n}, {\n  connection,\n  concurrency: 10,    // Process 10 emails at once\n});\n\nemailWorker.on("completed", (job) => console.log(`Email ${job.id} sent`));\nemailWorker.on("failed",    (job, err) => logger.error({ job: job?.id, err }, "Email failed"));\n```\n\n### Dead Letter Queue\n```typescript\n// Jobs that fail all retries go to a DLQ for inspection\nconst failedWorker = new Worker("emails:failed", async (job) => {\n  // Alert team, log for manual investigation\n  await alertSlack(`Email job ${job.id} failed: ${job.data.to}`);\n  await logToDatabase(job);\n}, { connection });\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Make job handlers idempotent (safe to retry)\n- Set reasonable concurrency limits per worker\n- Use dead letter queues for persistent failures\n- Monitor queue depth (alert if growing unbounded)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a queue and pub/sub?\n2. What is an idempotent job handler?\n3. What is a dead letter queue?\n\n## Assignment\nBuild a background job system with BullMQ: email queue (welcome, enrollment, digest), export queue (CSV course data, rate-limited), XP award queue (batch updates). Include DLQ and monitoring dashboard.', 25, 1),

('l130601', 'm1306', 'Caching Strategies', E'# Caching Strategies\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nCaching reduces latency and database load by serving pre-computed results. The right caching strategy can reduce response times from seconds to milliseconds.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement Redis caching\n- Apply cache invalidation strategies\n- Use cache headers for HTTP caching\n- Design cache warming\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Caching Layers\n```\nBrowser cache    -- HTTP cache headers\nCDN              -- Static assets, API responses\nApplication      -- In-memory (node-cache) or Redis\nDatabase         -- Query result cache, buffer pool\n```\n\n### Redis Caching\n```typescript\nimport { createClient } from "redis";\n\nconst redis = createClient({ url: process.env.REDIS_URL });\nawait redis.connect();\n\n// Cache-aside pattern (most common)\nasync function getCourse(id: string): Promise<Course> {\n  const cacheKey = `course:${id}`;\n\n  // 1. Check cache\n  const cached = await redis.get(cacheKey);\n  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached);\n\n  // 2. Cache miss -- query database\n  const course = await db.courses.findUnique({ where: { id } });\n  if (!course) throw new NotFoundError("Course");\n\n  // 3. Store in cache with TTL\n  await redis.setEx(cacheKey, 3600, JSON.stringify(course)); // 1 hour\n\n  return course;\n}\n\n// Invalidate on update\nasync function updateCourse(id: string, data: UpdateCourseData) {\n  const course = await db.courses.update({ where: { id }, data });\n  await redis.del(`course:${id}`);          // Invalidate specific\n  await redis.del(`courses:list:*`);        // Pattern delete (if supported)\n  return course;\n}\n```\n\n### Cache Patterns\n```\nCache-Aside (Lazy loading):\n  Read: check cache -> miss -> read DB -> write cache\n  Write: update DB -> delete cache\n  Pros: Only cache what is needed. Cons: First request is slow.\n\nWrite-Through:\n  Write: update DB AND cache simultaneously\n  Pros: Cache always fresh. Cons: Every write hits cache.\n\nWrite-Behind (Async):\n  Write: update cache immediately, update DB asynchronously\n  Pros: Very fast writes. Cons: Risk of data loss.\n\nRead-Through:\n  Cache sits in front of DB, handles miss automatically\n```\n\n### HTTP Cache Headers\n```typescript\n// Public static assets -- cache forever (content-hashed)\nres.setHeader("Cache-Control", "public, max-age=31536000, immutable");\n\n// API responses -- cache briefly\nres.setHeader("Cache-Control", "public, max-age=60, stale-while-revalidate=300");\n\n// Authenticated data -- no shared cache\nres.setHeader("Cache-Control", "private, max-age=0, must-revalidate");\n\n// ETag for conditional requests\nconst etag = generateETag(course);\nif (req.headers["if-none-match"] === etag) {\n  return res.status(304).end(); // Not Modified\n}\nres.setHeader("ETag", etag);\nres.json(course);\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Cache at the highest level possible (CDN > App > DB)\n- Set appropriate TTLs (shorter for frequently changing data)\n- Use cache stampede protection (lock during miss)\n- Monitor hit rate (< 80% hit rate means cache not effective)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the cache-aside pattern?\n2. What is cache invalidation and why is it hard?\n3. What is the difference between max-age and s-maxage?\n\n## Assignment\nImplement Redis caching for the R-Learn API: cache course list (5min TTL), individual courses (1hr), leaderboard (10min). Add cache invalidation on updates. Measure hit rate.', 25, 1),

('l130701', 'm1307', 'Scalability Patterns', E'# Scalability Patterns\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAs applications grow, they must handle more users and data. Understanding scalability patterns lets you build systems that grow gracefully.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand vertical vs horizontal scaling\n- Apply database read replicas\n- Implement connection pooling\n- Design for stateless services\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling\n```\nVertical (Scale Up):   Bigger server (more CPU/RAM)\n  Pros:   Simple, no code changes\n  Cons:   Limited (hardware ceiling), single point of failure\n\nHorizontal (Scale Out): More servers\n  Pros:   Unlimited (add more machines), high availability\n  Cons:   Requires stateless design, distributed system complexity\n\nFor stateful services (databases):\n  Read replicas for read-heavy workloads\n  Sharding for write-heavy workloads\n```\n\n### Stateless Services\n```typescript\n// STATEFUL (cannot scale horizontally)\nconst sessions = new Map(); // In-memory -- lost on restart!\n\napp.post("/login", (req, res) => {\n  sessions.set(req.body.email, { loggedIn: true });\n});\n\n// STATELESS (can scale horizontally)\n// State lives in Redis or database, not in the process\napp.post("/login", async (req, res) => {\n  const user  = await authenticate(req.body);\n  const token = generateJWT(user); // Self-contained\n  await redis.setEx(`session:${token}`, 3600, JSON.stringify(user));\n  res.json({ token });\n});\n\n// Any server can handle any request -- JWT carries context\n```\n\n### Database Read Replicas\n```typescript\n// Primary for writes, replica for reads\nconst primaryDb = createPgPool({ host: "primary.db.internal" });\nconst replicaDb = createPgPool({ host: "replica.db.internal" });\n\n// Write to primary\nasync function createCourse(data: CreateCourseData) {\n  return primaryDb.query("INSERT INTO courses ...", data);\n}\n\n// Read from replica (may be slightly behind)\nasync function listCourses(filter: CourseFilter) {\n  return replicaDb.query("SELECT * FROM courses WHERE ...", filter);\n}\n\n// With Prisma\nconst prisma = new PrismaClient();\nprisma.$extends({\n  query: {\n    $allOperations({ operation, query, args }) {\n      if (["findMany", "findFirst", "count"].includes(operation)) {\n        return prisma.$primary().then(p => (p as any)[operation](args));\n        // Read from replica\n      }\n      return query(args); // Write to primary\n    }\n  }\n});\n```\n\n### Connection Pooling\n```typescript\nimport { Pool } from "pg";\n\n// Pool reuses connections instead of creating new ones per request\nconst pool = new Pool({\n  host:              process.env.DB_HOST,\n  database:          process.env.DB_NAME,\n  max:               20,   // Max 20 connections\n  min:               5,    // Maintain 5 connections always\n  idleTimeoutMillis: 30000,\n  connectionTimeoutMillis: 2000,\n});\n\n// PgBouncer for external pooling (between app and Postgres)\n// DATABASE_URL points to PgBouncer, not Postgres directly\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Design stateless services from day one\n- Use connection pooling (PgBouncer for Postgres)\n- Read from replicas, write to primary\n- Use a CDN for static assets (free horizontal scaling for content)\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between vertical and horizontal scaling?\n2. Why must services be stateless to scale horizontally?\n3. What is a connection pool?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign the scaling architecture for R-Learn at 10x current traffic: load balancer config, read replicas, Redis caching, CDN, connection pooling. Identify the bottlenecks.', 25, 1),

('l130801', 'm1308', 'Observability & Monitoring', E'# Observability & Monitoring\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nYou cannot fix what you cannot see. Observability -- logs, metrics, and traces -- is what transforms a black box into a system you can understand and debug.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement structured logging\n- Collect and alert on metrics\n- Add distributed tracing\n- Build a health check endpoint\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### The Three Pillars\n```\nLogs:    What happened? (events, errors, actions)\nMetrics: How is it performing? (latency, throughput, error rate)\nTraces:  Where did time go? (request path across services)\n```\n\n### Structured Logging\n```typescript\nimport pino from "pino";\n\nconst logger = pino({\n  level: process.env.LOG_LEVEL ?? "info",\n  base:  { service: "course-api", env: process.env.NODE_ENV },\n});\n\n// Request logging middleware\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  const start = Date.now();\n  const requestId = crypto.randomUUID();\n  req.log = logger.child({ requestId });\n\n  res.on("finish", () => {\n    req.log.info({\n      method:     req.method,\n      path:       req.path,\n      statusCode: res.statusCode,\n      duration:   Date.now() - start,\n      userId:     req.user?.id,\n    }, "Request completed");\n  });\n  next();\n});\n```\n\n### Metrics with Prometheus\n```bash\nnpm install prom-client\n```\n\n```typescript\nimport { Registry, Counter, Histogram, Gauge } from "prom-client";\n\nconst registry = new Registry();\n\nconst httpRequests = new Counter({\n  name:       "http_requests_total",\n  help:       "Total HTTP requests",\n  labelNames: ["method", "path", "status"],\n  registers:  [registry],\n});\n\nconst httpDuration = new Histogram({\n  name:       "http_request_duration_seconds",\n  help:       "HTTP request duration",\n  labelNames: ["method", "path"],\n  buckets:    [0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 1, 2.5, 5],\n  registers:  [registry],\n});\n\nconst activeConnections = new Gauge({\n  name:      "active_connections",\n  help:      "Current active connections",\n  registers: [registry],\n});\n\n// Middleware\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  const timer = httpDuration.startTimer({ method: req.method, path: req.route?.path });\n  res.on("finish", () => {\n    timer();\n    httpRequests.inc({ method: req.method, path: req.route?.path, status: res.statusCode });\n  });\n  next();\n});\n\n// Metrics endpoint (scraped by Prometheus)\napp.get("/metrics", async (req, res) => {\n  res.set("Content-Type", registry.contentType);\n  res.end(await registry.metrics());\n});\n```\n\n### Health Check Endpoint\n```typescript\napp.get("/health", async (req, res) => {\n  const checks = {\n    database: await checkDatabase(),\n    redis:    await checkRedis(),\n    disk:     checkDisk(),\n  };\n\n  const healthy = Object.values(checks).every(c => c.status === "ok");\n\n  res.status(healthy ? 200 : 503).json({\n    status: healthy ? "healthy" : "unhealthy",\n    checks,\n    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n    version:   process.env.APP_VERSION,\n  });\n});\n\nasync function checkDatabase() {\n  try {\n    await db.$queryRaw`SELECT 1`;\n    return { status: "ok" };\n  } catch (err) {\n    return { status: "error", message: err.message };\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Log in JSON in production (machine-parseable)\n- Alert on SLOs not raw metrics (99th percentile latency > 2s, error rate > 1%)\n- Add distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry) for microservices\n- Health check should check all critical dependencies\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What are the three pillars of observability?\n2. What is the difference between metrics and logs?\n3. What should a health check endpoint verify?\n\n## Assignment\nAdd full observability to an Express API: pino structured logging, Prometheus metrics (request count, latency, error rate), health check endpoint, Grafana dashboard.', 25, 1),

('l130901', 'm1309', 'Resilience Patterns', E'# Resilience Patterns\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDistributed systems fail. Resilience patterns prevent a single failure from cascading into a system-wide outage.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Implement circuit breaker pattern\n- Apply retry with exponential backoff\n- Use timeouts and bulkheads\n- Design for graceful degradation\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Circuit Breaker\n```typescript\n// States: Closed (normal) -> Open (failing) -> Half-Open (testing)\n\nclass CircuitBreaker {\n  private failures    = 0;\n  private lastFailure = 0;\n  private state:      "closed" | "open" | "half-open" = "closed";\n\n  constructor(\n    private threshold:  number = 5,      // Failures before opening\n    private timeout:    number = 60000,  // ms before trying again\n  ) {}\n\n  async call<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> {\n    if (this.state === "open") {\n      if (Date.now() - this.lastFailure > this.timeout) {\n        this.state = "half-open";\n      } else {\n        throw new Error("Circuit open -- service unavailable");\n      }\n    }\n\n    try {\n      const result = await fn();\n      this.onSuccess();\n      return result;\n    } catch (err) {\n      this.onFailure();\n      throw err;\n    }\n  }\n\n  private onSuccess() {\n    this.failures = 0;\n    this.state    = "closed";\n  }\n\n  private onFailure() {\n    this.failures++;\n    this.lastFailure = Date.now();\n    if (this.failures >= this.threshold) this.state = "open";\n  }\n}\n\nconst emailBreaker = new CircuitBreaker(5, 30000);\nawait emailBreaker.call(() => emailService.send(data));\n```\n\n### Retry with Exponential Backoff\n```typescript\nasync function withRetry<T>(\n  fn:       () => Promise<T>,\n  options:  { attempts: number; baseDelay: number; maxDelay: number } =\n            { attempts: 3, baseDelay: 1000, maxDelay: 30000 }\n): Promise<T> {\n  let lastError: Error;\n\n  for (let attempt = 1; attempt <= options.attempts; attempt++) {\n    try {\n      return await fn();\n    } catch (err) {\n      lastError = err as Error;\n\n      if (attempt === options.attempts) break;\n\n      // Exponential backoff with jitter\n      const delay = Math.min(\n        options.baseDelay * 2 ** (attempt - 1) + Math.random() * 1000,\n        options.maxDelay\n      );\n\n      logger.warn({ attempt, delay, err: lastError.message }, "Retrying after error");\n      await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, delay));\n    }\n  }\n\n  throw lastError!;\n}\n\n// Usage\nawait withRetry(() => fetch("/api/external"), { attempts: 3, baseDelay: 1000, maxDelay: 10000 });\n```\n\n### Timeout\n```typescript\nfunction withTimeout<T>(promise: Promise<T>, ms: number): Promise<T> {\n  return Promise.race([\n    promise,\n    new Promise<never>((_, reject) =>\n      setTimeout(() => reject(new Error(`Timeout after ${ms}ms`)), ms)\n    )\n  ]);\n}\n\nawait withTimeout(callExternalApi(), 5000); // Fail after 5s\n```\n\n### Graceful Degradation\n```typescript\n// Return cached/default data when live data unavailable\nasync function getCourseRecommendations(userId: string) {\n  try {\n    return await withTimeout(mlRecommendationService.get(userId), 500);\n  } catch {\n    logger.warn("ML recommendations unavailable, using fallback");\n    return getPopularCourses(); // Always works\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Apply circuit breakers to all external service calls\n- Add jitter to retry delays to prevent thundering herd\n- Set conservative timeouts (fail fast, do not hang)\n- Design fallbacks for every critical dependency\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a circuit breaker pattern?\n2. What is exponential backoff and why add jitter?\n3. What is graceful degradation?\n\n## Assignment\nAdd resilience to an external API integration: circuit breaker (5 failures -> open), retry with backoff (3 attempts), 2-second timeout, and a fallback response when all else fails.', 25, 1),

('l131001', 'm1310', 'Cloud Deployment', E'# Cloud Deployment\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nModern backends live in the cloud. Understanding deployment options, containers, and infrastructure as code is required for production engineering.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Containerize a Node.js app with Docker\n- Deploy to a cloud provider\n- Use environment-specific configuration\n- Set up basic infrastructure as code\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Dockerfile for Node.js\n```dockerfile\n# Multi-stage build\nFROM node:20-alpine AS deps\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY package*.json ./\nRUN npm ci --only=production\n\nFROM node:20-alpine AS builder\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY package*.json ./\nRUN npm ci\nCOPY . .\nRUN npm run build\n\nFROM node:20-alpine AS runner\nWORKDIR /app\n\n# Security: non-root user\nRUN addgroup -S nodejs && adduser -S nodejs -G nodejs\nUSER nodejs\n\nCOPY --from=deps    /app/node_modules ./node_modules\nCOPY --from=builder /app/dist         ./dist\nCOPY package.json .\n\nEXPOSE 3000\nHEALTHCHECK CMD wget -qO- http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1\n\nCMD ["node", "dist/index.js"]\n```\n\n### Docker Compose (Local Development)\n```yaml\n# docker-compose.yml\nservices:\n  api:\n    build: .\n    ports: [\"3000:3000\"]\n    environment:\n      DATABASE_URL: postgresql://postgres:postgres@db:5432/rlearn\n      REDIS_URL:    redis://redis:6379\n    depends_on:\n      db:    { condition: service_healthy }\n      redis: { condition: service_started }\n    volumes:\n      - ./src:/app/src  # Hot reload in dev\n\n  db:\n    image: postgres:16-alpine\n    environment:\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: postgres\n      POSTGRES_DB: rlearn\n    volumes:\n      - postgres_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"pg_isready\", \"-U\", \"postgres\"]\n      interval: 10s\n\n  redis:\n    image: redis:7-alpine\n    volumes: [redis_data:/data]\n\nvolumes:\n  postgres_data:\n  redis_data:\n```\n\n### Deployment Options\n```\nSimple (small projects):\n  Railway:  git push to deploy, managed Postgres/Redis\n  Render:   Web services, databases, workers\n  Fly.io:   Docker-based, global regions, free tier\n\nMid-scale:\n  AWS ECS:  Managed Docker containers\n  AWS EB:   Elastic Beanstalk -- managed Node hosting\n  GCP Cloud Run: Serverless containers\n\nEnterprise:\n  Kubernetes: Container orchestration at scale\n  AWS EKS / GKE / AKS: Managed Kubernetes\n```\n\n### Environment Config\n```yaml\n# .env.production (set via deployment platform)\nNODE_ENV=production\nPORT=3000\nDATABASE_URL=postgresql://user:pass@db.internal:5432/rlearn\nREDIS_URL=redis://redis.internal:6379\nJWT_SECRET=<32+ char random secret from secrets manager>\nLOG_LEVEL=info\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Use multi-stage Docker builds (smaller production images)\n- Run as non-root user in containers\n- Add HEALTHCHECK to Dockerfile\n- Use a secrets manager (AWS Secrets Manager, not environment variables) for production secrets\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a multi-stage Docker build and why use it?\n2. What is the difference between CMD and ENTRYPOINT in Dockerfile?\n3. How do you manage secrets in a cloud deployment?\n\n## Assignment\nDockerize the R-Learn API: multi-stage Dockerfile, docker-compose for local dev (API + Postgres + Redis), health check, non-root user, deploy to Railway or Fly.io.', 25, 1)

