('l140101', 'm1401', 'System Design Fundamentals', E'# System Design Fundamentals\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nSystem design is tested in senior engineering interviews and is the skill that separates engineers who can build features from engineers who can build systems.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Apply a structured approach to system design\n- Estimate capacity requirements\n- Identify bottlenecks\n- Make and justify trade-off decisions\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### System Design Interview Framework\n```\n1. Clarify Requirements (5 min)\n   Functional: What does it do?\n   Non-functional: Scale, latency, consistency, availability\n   Constraints: Budget, timeline, team size\n\n2. Estimate Scale (5 min)\n   Users: DAU, MAU\n   Requests: reads/writes per second\n   Storage: data size, growth rate\n   Bandwidth: data transferred per second\n\n3. High-Level Design (10 min)\n   Draw major components\n   Identify APIs\n   Data flow through system\n\n4. Deep Dive (20 min)\n   Pick 2-3 key components\n   Database schema\n   API design\n   Algorithms\n\n5. Address Bottlenecks (5 min)\n   Scaling\n   Caching\n   Trade-offs\n```\n\n### Capacity Estimation\n```\nUseful numbers to memorize:\n  1 million req/day  = ~12 req/second\n  1 billion req/day  = ~12,000 req/second\n\n  1 KB  = 1,000 bytes\n  1 MB  = 1,000,000 bytes\n  1 GB  = 1,000,000,000 bytes\n\n  10ms:  In-memory cache read\n  1ms:   SSD read\n  10ms:  HDD seek\n  150ms: Cross-continent network roundtrip\n  1ms:   Same region network\n\n  Postgres:  ~10,000 QPS (simple queries, indexed)\n  Redis:     ~100,000 ops/second\n  HTTP API:  ~1,000-10,000 RPS per server instance\n```\n\n### Design Trade-offs\n```\nCAP theorem: choose at most 2:\n  Consistency  -- All nodes see the same data\n  Availability -- Always respond to requests\n  Partition tolerance -- Work despite network splits\n\nUsually choose:\n  CP: Banks, payment systems (consistency critical)\n  AP: Social media, recommendations (availability critical)\n\nSQL vs NoSQL:\n  SQL:    ACID, joins, schema, proven. Use for most things.\n  NoSQL:  Flexible schema, horizontal scale, eventual consistency.\n          Use when SQL bottlenecks or truly flexible schema needed.\n```\n\n### Key Design Decisions\n```\nFor every component, articulate:\n  Why this technology?\n  What is the failure mode?\n  How does it scale?\n  What is the consistency model?\n  What are the operational costs?\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Start broad (high level) before going deep\n- State assumptions explicitly\n- Drive the conversation -- do not wait to be asked\n- Quantify decisions: "This needs 10 servers because..."\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. How would you approach designing a URL shortener?\n2. What is the difference between latency and throughput?\n3. What is the CAP theorem?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign R-Learn from scratch: estimate scale (10k DAU), define APIs, draw component diagram, choose databases, design for 99.9% uptime. Present and defend your choices.', 30, 1),

('l140201', 'm1402', 'Scalability & Load Balancing', E'# Scalability & Load Balancing\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nLoad balancers are the gateway to horizontal scalability. They are in every production system handling more than trivial traffic.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand load balancing algorithms\n- Configure health checks\n- Implement session affinity\n- Design for zero-downtime deployments\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Load Balancing Algorithms\n```\nRound Robin:          Distribute requests in order (A, B, C, A, B, C...)\n                      Simple. Ignores server load.\n\nWeighted Round Robin: Servers get requests proportional to weight\n                      (A:2 gets 2x requests of B:1)\n\nLeast Connections:    Route to server with fewest active connections\n                      Better for long-lived connections.\n\nIP Hash:              Same client always goes to same server\n                      Session affinity. Problem: uneven distribution.\n\nRandom:               Pick server randomly. Simple and effective.\n\nHealth-based:         Only route to healthy servers.\n```\n\n### Nginx Load Balancer Config\n```nginx\nupstream rlearn_api {\n    least_conn;                          # Algorithm\n    server api-1.internal:3000 weight=3; # 3x traffic\n    server api-2.internal:3000 weight=1;\n    server api-3.internal:3000 backup;   # Only used if others fail\n\n    keepalive 32;                        # Reuse connections\n}\n\nserver {\n    listen 443 ssl;\n    server_name api.rlearn.com;\n\n    ssl_certificate     /etc/ssl/cert.pem;\n    ssl_certificate_key /etc/ssl/key.pem;\n    ssl_protocols       TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;\n\n    location / {\n        proxy_pass         http://rlearn_api;\n        proxy_set_header   Host $host;\n        proxy_set_header   X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\n        proxy_set_header   X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\n        proxy_read_timeout 60s;\n        proxy_connect_timeout 5s;\n    }\n\n    location /health {\n        access_log off;          # Do not log health checks\n        proxy_pass http://rlearn_api;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Auto-Scaling\n```\nHorizontal Pod Autoscaler (Kubernetes):\n  Scale up:   When CPU > 70% for 3 minutes\n  Scale down: When CPU < 30% for 5 minutes\n  Min: 2 pods, Max: 20 pods\n\nAWS Auto Scaling Group:\n  Trigger: Average CPU > 60%\n  Cool down: 5 minutes (prevent thrashing)\n  Scale in protection: Do not terminate instances handling requests\n```\n\n### Zero-Downtime Deployment\n```\nBlue-Green Deployment:\n  Blue: Current production (100% traffic)\n  Green: New version (0% traffic)\n  Test green -> Switch all traffic -> Blue becomes standby\n  Rollback: Switch traffic back to blue instantly\n\nRolling Deployment:\n  Replace instances one at a time\n  Always have minimum healthy instances\n  Slower but no idle fleet cost\n\nCanary Release:\n  5% of traffic to new version\n  Monitor error rate\n  Gradually increase to 100%\n  Automated rollback if errors spike\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always configure health checks (load balancer removes unhealthy servers)\n- Use least_conn for long-lived connections (WebSockets, streaming)\n- Prefer rolling or canary over big-bang deployments\n- Test failover: actually kill servers to verify routing works\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between a load balancer and a reverse proxy?\n2. What is session affinity and when do you need it?\n3. What is a canary deployment?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign the load balancing and deployment strategy for R-Learn: Nginx config, health checks, auto-scaling rules, blue-green deployment runbook, rollback procedure.', 25, 1),

('l140301', 'm1403', 'Database Design at Scale', E'# Database Design at Scale\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDatabases are typically the first bottleneck. Knowing how to scale them -- read replicas, sharding, and choosing the right database -- is critical knowledge.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Scale PostgreSQL with read replicas\n- Understand database sharding\n- Choose between SQL and NoSQL\n- Design for high write throughput\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Read Replicas\n```\nPrimary (Master): Handles all writes + some reads\nReplica(s):       Handle reads only (eventually consistent)\n\nReplication lag: Usually < 100ms for same-region replicas\n\nRoute reads to replicas for:\n  Analytics queries\n  Reports\n  Search\n  API list endpoints\n\nKeep on primary:\n  Reads immediately after writes (read-your-writes consistency)\n  Financial transactions\n  Auth token lookups after login\n```\n\n### Database Sharding\n```\nShard by user_id:\n  Shard 1: users 1-1M\n  Shard 2: users 1M-2M\n  Shard 3: users 2M-3M\n\nBenefits: Each shard is smaller, faster, and can be on different hardware\n\nChallenges:\n  Cross-shard queries are complex (cannot JOIN across shards)\n  Resharding is painful (moving data when shards fill up)\n  Hot shards (some users much more active than others)\n\nPreferred approach: Use a managed solution\n  PlanetScale (MySQL, horizontal sharding)\n  CockroachDB (distributed SQL, auto-sharding)\n  Vitess (MySQL sharding at YouTube scale)\n```\n\n### SQL vs NoSQL Decision Matrix\n```\nUse PostgreSQL when:\n  You need ACID transactions\n  Data has clear relationships\n  You need ad-hoc queries and reporting\n  You are not sure (SQL is the safe default)\n\nUse Redis when:\n  Caching\n  Session storage\n  Rate limiting counters\n  Real-time leaderboards (sorted sets)\n  Pub/sub messaging\n\nUse Elasticsearch when:\n  Full-text search across large text fields\n  Complex relevance ranking\n  Log aggregation and analysis\n\nUse MongoDB when:\n  Truly flexible schema (document structure varies per record)\n  Hierarchical data with no need for cross-collection joins\n  Rapid prototyping\n\nUse Cassandra/DynamoDB when:\n  Very high write throughput (millions/second)\n  Time-series data (append-only)\n  Global distribution\n```\n\n### Write Optimization\n```sql\n-- Batch inserts (10x faster than individual inserts)\nINSERT INTO activity_logs (user_id, action, created_at)\nVALUES ($1, $2, $3), ($4, $5, $6), ... -- 1000 rows at once\n\n-- Bulk upsert\nINSERT INTO user_progress SELECT * FROM temp_progress\nON CONFLICT (user_id, lesson_id) DO UPDATE SET completed_at = EXCLUDED.completed_at;\n\n-- Partitioning for large tables\nCREATE TABLE activity_logs (LIKE activity_logs_template)\nPARTITION BY RANGE (created_at);\n\nCREATE TABLE activity_logs_2024_01 PARTITION OF activity_logs\nFOR VALUES FROM (''2024-01-01'') TO (''2024-02-01'');\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Add read replicas before vertical scaling\n- Partition large time-series tables by date\n- Index before you need to -- adding indexes on large tables is slow\n- Use connection pooling (PgBouncer) -- PostgreSQL has high connection overhead\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is a read replica and what problem does it solve?\n2. What is database sharding?\n3. When would you choose MongoDB over PostgreSQL?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign the database architecture for R-Learn at 1M users: primary + 2 replicas, partitioned activity_logs, Redis for sessions/caching, Elasticsearch for course search. Draw the data flow diagram.', 25, 1),

('l140401', 'm1404', 'Caching & CDN at Scale', E'# Caching & CDN at Scale\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nCaching is the most impactful performance optimization you can make. CDNs distribute static content globally, reducing latency for users worldwide.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Design a multi-tier caching strategy\n- Configure CDN for APIs and static assets\n- Handle cache invalidation at scale\n- Prevent cache stampede\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Multi-Tier Cache\n```\nTier 1: CDN Edge Cache\n  Location: 200+ locations worldwide\n  Latency: < 10ms (nearest edge)\n  Content: Static assets, cacheable API responses\n  TTL: 60s-1 year\n\nTier 2: Application Cache (Redis)\n  Location: Same datacenter as API servers\n  Latency: 1-5ms\n  Content: DB query results, session data, computed values\n  TTL: Seconds to hours\n\nTier 3: Database Cache\n  Location: In-memory within Postgres (shared_buffers)\n  Latency: 0.1ms\n  Content: Recently accessed pages\n  TTL: Managed by Postgres\n```\n\n### Cache Stampede Prevention\n```typescript\n// Problem: Many requests simultaneously miss cache, all hit DB\n// Solution 1: Locking (only one request rebuilds the cache)\nasync function getWithLock(key: string, buildFn: () => Promise<unknown>, ttl: number) {\n  const cached = await redis.get(key);\n  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached);\n\n  const lockKey = `lock:${key}`;\n  const locked  = await redis.set(lockKey, "1", { NX: true, EX: 10 });\n\n  if (locked) {\n    // We got the lock -- build the cache\n    const value = await buildFn();\n    await redis.setEx(key, ttl, JSON.stringify(value));\n    await redis.del(lockKey);\n    return value;\n  } else {\n    // Wait for the lock holder to finish\n    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 100));\n    return getWithLock(key, buildFn, ttl); // Retry\n  }\n}\n\n// Solution 2: Probabilistic early expiration\nasync function getWithEarlyRefresh(key: string, ttl: number, buildFn: () => Promise<unknown>) {\n  const data = await redis.get(key);\n  if (!data) return rebuild();\n\n  const { value, expiresAt } = JSON.parse(data);\n  const remaining = expiresAt - Date.now();\n\n  // Probabilistically refresh before expiry (avoid stampede)\n  if (remaining < ttl * 0.1 * 1000 && Math.random() < 0.1) {\n    rebuild(); // Async -- do not await\n  }\n\n  return value;\n\n  async function rebuild() {\n    const fresh = await buildFn();\n    await redis.set(key, JSON.stringify({ value: fresh, expiresAt: Date.now() + ttl * 1000 }), { EX: ttl });\n    return fresh;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### CDN Configuration\n```\nCloudflare Page Rules:\n  /*.js, /*.css, /*.png  -> Cache Everything, max-age=1year\n  /api/*                 -> Bypass Cache\n  /api/courses*          -> Cache for 60 seconds (public endpoints)\n  /api/me*               -> Bypass Cache (private)\n\nCache-Control headers your API should return:\n  Public API (courses list):\n    Cache-Control: public, max-age=60, stale-while-revalidate=300\n\n  Private API (user profile):\n    Cache-Control: private, no-store\n\n  Static assets:\n    Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Cache at the CDN level first (free, global, zero server load)\n- Use stale-while-revalidate for API responses\n- Prevent stampede with locks or early refresh\n- Monitor hit rate -- < 70% means cache not working\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is cache stampede and how do you prevent it?\n2. What is stale-while-revalidate?\n3. What is the difference between public and private Cache-Control?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign caching for R-Learn: CDN for static assets, Redis for course data (with invalidation), cache stampede prevention, and a cache monitoring dashboard showing hit rates.', 25, 1),

('l140501', 'm1405', 'Message Queues & Async Processing', E'# Message Queues & Async Processing at Scale\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nAsynchronous processing decouples slow operations from the request path, enabling fast API responses while heavy work happens in the background.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Design async processing systems\n- Handle at-least-once delivery\n- Implement idempotent consumers\n- Use Kafka for high-throughput streaming\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### When to Use Async Processing\n```\nSynchronous (in request):\n  < 200ms operations\n  User needs the result immediately\n  Example: Validate and save a form\n\nAsynchronous (queued):\n  Slow operations (email, PDF generation, ML inference)\n  Operations that can fail and retry\n  Fan-out (one action triggers many)\n  Example: After enrollment, send email + update leaderboard + award XP\n```\n\n### Delivery Guarantees\n```\nAt-most-once:   Message might be lost, never delivered twice\n                Use: Metrics, logs (losing some is ok)\n\nAt-least-once:  Message always delivered, might be duplicate\n                Use: Emails, payments (must succeed, handle duplicates)\n\nExactly-once:   Never lost, never duplicate\n                Very hard to achieve in distributed systems\n                Use Kafka transactions or idempotency keys\n```\n\n### Idempotent Consumer\n```typescript\n// Idempotent: processing the same message twice has no additional effect\nasync function handleEnrollment(job: Job<EnrollmentEvent>) {\n  const { userId, courseId, eventId } = job.data;\n\n  // Check if already processed (idempotency check)\n  const processed = await redis.get(`processed:${eventId}`);\n  if (processed) {\n    logger.info({ eventId }, "Event already processed, skipping");\n    return;\n  }\n\n  // Process\n  await db.$transaction(async tx => {\n    // Upsert -- safe to run twice\n    await tx.enrollments.upsert({\n      where: { userId_courseId: { userId, courseId } },\n      create: { userId, courseId, enrolledAt: new Date() },\n      update: {}, // No-op if already exists\n    });\n\n    await tx.users.update({\n      where: { id: userId },\n      data:  { xp: { increment: 50 } },\n    });\n  });\n\n  // Mark as processed (TTL: 7 days to handle delayed retries)\n  await redis.setEx(`processed:${eventId}`, 7 * 24 * 3600, "1");\n}\n```\n\n### Kafka for High-Throughput Streaming\n```\nKafka concepts:\n  Topic:     Named stream of events (courses, enrollments, xp)\n  Partition: Ordered, immutable log within a topic\n  Consumer Group: Set of consumers sharing partition consumption\n  Offset:    Position in partition (allows replay)\n\nWhen to use Kafka vs BullMQ:\n  BullMQ: Simple job queues, < 10k msgs/sec, need retry/scheduling\n  Kafka:  Event streams, > 10k msgs/sec, need replay, audit log\n\nKey features:\n  Messages retained for configurable period (replay history)\n  Multiple consumer groups (same message consumed by many services)\n  Partitioning for parallel processing\n  Compaction for latest-value-per-key semantics\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Design consumers to be idempotent from the start\n- Use at-least-once delivery + idempotency (simpler than exactly-once)\n- Monitor queue depth -- growing queue means consumers are too slow\n- Set dead letter queues for poison messages\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between at-least-once and exactly-once delivery?\n2. What is an idempotent consumer?\n3. When would you use Kafka instead of Redis queues?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign the async processing system for R-Learn: enrollment flow (5 downstream effects), notification system (push/email/SMS), leaderboard updates, certificate generation. Use BullMQ with idempotent handlers.', 25, 1),

('l140601', 'm1406', 'Availability & Reliability', E'# Availability & Reliability\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nDowntime has real cost -- lost revenue, damaged reputation, breached SLAs. Building for high availability requires deliberate design.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Define SLA, SLO, and SLI\n- Calculate availability from nines\n- Design for high availability\n- Implement graceful degradation\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Availability Nines\n```\n99%      = 3.65 days downtime/year\n99.9%    = 8.76 hours downtime/year\n99.99%   = 52.6 minutes downtime/year\n99.999%  = 5.26 minutes downtime/year (five nines)\n\nFor R-Learn API target: 99.9% (8.76 hours/year budget)\n```\n\n### SLA / SLO / SLI\n```\nSLI (Service Level Indicator):\n  Actual measurement: "Our API responded in < 200ms for 99.2% of requests"\n\nSLO (Service Level Objective):\n  Internal target: "99.9% of requests respond in < 200ms"\n\nSLA (Service Level Agreement):\n  External commitment: "We guarantee 99.9% uptime or refund 10% of monthly fee"\n\nError Budget:\n  SLO - Actual = Budget\n  99.9% SLO, actual 99.95% = 0.05% error budget remaining\n  Use budget for risky deployments; freeze if budget exhausted\n```\n\n### Eliminating Single Points of Failure\n```\nIdentify SPoFs:\n  Single DB server     -> Primary + replica with failover\n  Single region        -> Multi-region with DNS failover\n  Single load balancer -> Active-passive LB pair\n  Shared state         -> Distributed (Redis Cluster, not single Redis)\n  External dependency  -> Circuit breaker + fallback\n\nRedundancy patterns:\n  Active-Active:  Both handle traffic simultaneously\n  Active-Passive: Standby takes over on failure\n```\n\n### Multi-Region Architecture\n```\nRegion A (Primary):  ap-south-1 (Mumbai)\n  Primary DB\n  Cache\n  API servers\n  Load balancer\n\nRegion B (Secondary): ap-southeast-1 (Singapore)\n  DB replica\n  Cache (warm)\n  API servers (warm standby)\n  Load balancer\n\nFailover:\n  DNS health check detects Region A down\n  DNS switches to Region B\n  Region B DB replica promoted to primary\n  RTO: 5 minutes, RPO: < 1 minute (replication lag)\n```\n\n### Recovery Objectives\n```\nRTO (Recovery Time Objective): How long can we be down?\n  Critical system: RTO = 5 minutes\n  Internal tools:  RTO = 4 hours\n\nRPO (Recovery Point Objective): How much data can we lose?\n  Financial data:  RPO = 0 (no data loss allowed)\n  User activity:   RPO = 1 minute\n  Analytics:       RPO = 1 hour\n\nBackup strategy:\n  Continuous: WAL streaming replication (< 1 min RPO)\n  Daily:      Full database backup (1 day RPO, slow recovery)\n  Point-in-time: PITR (any point in time, < 1 min RPO)\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Define SLOs before incidents happen\n- Use error budgets to balance reliability and velocity\n- Run chaos engineering (Chaos Monkey) to validate resilience\n- Test failover quarterly -- do not find out it is broken during an incident\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What is the difference between SLA, SLO, and SLI?\n2. What is an error budget?\n3. What is RTO and RPO?\n\n## Assignment\nDefine SLOs for R-Learn (availability, latency, error rate). Calculate error budget. Design a multi-region failover architecture. Write a runbook for database failover.', 25, 1),

('l140701', 'm1407', 'CAP Theorem & Consistency', E'# CAP Theorem & Consistency Models\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nCAP theorem explains the fundamental trade-offs in distributed systems. Understanding it helps you make informed database and architecture choices.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Understand the CAP theorem\n- Know consistency models\n- Choose between CP and AP systems\n- Understand eventual consistency in practice\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### CAP Theorem\n```\nIn a distributed system, you can guarantee at most 2 of 3:\n\nConsistency (C):         All nodes see the same data at the same time\nAvailability (A):        Every request gets a response (not an error)\nPartition tolerance (P): System continues despite network splits\n\nIn practice: Partition tolerance is non-negotiable\n(Networks DO partition -- we must handle it)\n\nSo the real choice is:\n  CP: Consistent but may become unavailable during partition\n  AP: Available but may serve stale data during partition\n```\n\n### Real Examples\n```\nCP Systems (consistent, may be unavailable):\n  PostgreSQL (single node, no partitions)\n  HBase\n  ZooKeeper (leader election, consensus)\n  Use: Banks, financial systems, inventory\n\nAP Systems (available, eventually consistent):\n  Cassandra, DynamoDB\n  CouchDB\n  DNS\n  Shopping carts (Amazon)\n  Use: Social feeds, product catalogs, recommendations\n\nThe nuance:\n  Most modern databases offer tunable consistency\n  PostgreSQL with synchronous replicas = CP\n  PostgreSQL with async replicas = AP (replica may be stale)\n```\n\n### Consistency Models (Strong to Weak)\n```\nLinearizability (Strongest):\n  Reads always reflect the most recent write\n  Feels like a single machine\n  Cost: High latency, low availability\n\nSequential Consistency:\n  Operations from each process appear in program order\n  Global order exists but not real-time\n\nCausal Consistency:\n  Causally related operations in correct order\n  Concurrent operations may be in different order\n  Use: Distributed messaging (messages in conversation in order)\n\nEventual Consistency (Weakest):\n  If no new updates, all replicas converge eventually\n  Reads may return stale data\n  Use: DNS, social media likes, shopping cart\n```\n\n### Practical Eventual Consistency\n```\nEventual consistency strategies:\n\n1. Read your own writes:\n   After user writes, route that user''s reads to primary\n   or cache the write locally until replica catches up\n\n2. Monotonic reads:\n   Ensure user never sees data moving backwards\n   Sticky sessions to same replica\n\n3. Bounded staleness:\n   Guarantee: reads never see data older than T minutes\n   Set replication lag alert if lag > T\n\n4. Version vectors / CRDTs:\n   Allow concurrent writes, merge automatically\n   Use for collaborative documents, counters\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Choose CP for financial data, inventory, authentication\n- Choose AP for social feeds, recommendations, non-critical data\n- Expose consistency level as a configuration option\n- Document your consistency guarantees for API consumers\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. What does CAP theorem state?\n2. What is the difference between strong consistency and eventual consistency?\n3. Give an example of a real system that chooses AP over CP.\n\n## Assignment\nAnalyze R-Learn''s consistency requirements: which data must be strongly consistent (payments, enrollment), which can be eventually consistent (leaderboard, analytics). Justify each choice.', 25, 1),

('l140801', 'm1408', 'Designing Real Systems', E'# Designing Real Systems\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nPracticing real system designs internalizes the framework and builds intuition for trade-offs that come up in interviews and at work.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Design a URL shortener end-to-end\n- Design a notification service\n- Design a search service\n- Apply all system design concepts\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### Design: URL Shortener (like bit.ly)\n```\nRequirements:\n  Functional: Shorten URL, redirect to original, analytics\n  Non-functional: 100M URLs/day, low latency redirect (< 10ms)\n\nEstimation:\n  Shorten: 100M/day = 1,200/s\n  Redirect: 10:1 read:write = 12,000/s\n  Storage: 100M * 365 * 200 bytes = ~7 TB/year\n\nAPI:\n  POST /shorten { url } -> { shortUrl: "rl.co/abc123" }\n  GET  /{code}         -> 301 Redirect to original\n\nCore Algorithm (Short Code Generation):\n  Option 1: Base62(incrementing ID) -- predictable, sequential\n  Option 2: Hash first 6 chars of MD5(url) -- collisions possible\n  Option 3: Pre-generate codes (Redis set) -- most scalable\n\nDB Schema:\n  links: { id, code(unique), long_url, user_id, created_at, expires_at }\n\nCaching:\n  Cache code -> long_url in Redis (most reads are repeat)\n  TTL: 24 hours for popular links\n  Cache hit rate target: > 95%\n\nRedirect flow:\n  GET /abc123\n  1. Check Redis cache -- hit? -> 301 with long_url (1ms)\n  2. Miss -> Query PostgreSQL -> Cache -> 301 (10ms)\n  3. Async: increment click counter in background\n```\n\n### Design: Notification Service\n```\nRequirements:\n  Send email, push, SMS, in-app notifications\n  10M notifications/day\n  Delivery guarantees, retry on failure\n\nComponents:\n  API:        POST /notifications { userId, type, template, data }\n  Dispatcher: Route to correct channel (email/push/SMS)\n  Queues:     Separate queue per channel (email-queue, push-queue)\n  Workers:    One worker pool per channel\n  Preferences: User controls which channels to use\n\nKey decisions:\n  Priority queues: transactional (immediate), marketing (batch)\n  Rate limiting per channel: 100 emails/user/day\n  Idempotency: notification_id prevents duplicates\n  Status tracking: pending, delivered, failed, bounced\n```\n\n### Design: Search Service\n```\nRequirements:\n  Search courses by title, description, tags\n  Typo tolerance, ranking by relevance + popularity\n  100ms latency, 10k queries/second\n\nComponents:\n  API:         GET /search?q=react+hooks\n  Elasticsearch: Full-text search engine\n  Indexer:     Syncs DB changes to Elasticsearch\n\nIndex structure:\n  { id, title, description, tags, difficulty, enrolled, created_at }\n\nRanking:\n  TF-IDF relevance score (Elasticsearch default)\n  Boost by enrolled count\n  Boost by recency\n\nSync strategy:\n  Write to DB -> Publish event -> Indexer consumes -> Update ES\n  Lag acceptable: < 5 seconds\n  Full reindex daily for consistency\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Always start with requirements before design\n- Quantify every decision: "We need X servers because Y"\n- Identify the hard part early (usually consistency or scale bottleneck)\n- Draw diagrams -- system design is a visual discipline\n\n## Interview Questions\n1. How would you design a URL shortener that handles 100M requests/day?\n2. How would you ensure at-least-once delivery in a notification system?\n3. How does Elasticsearch keep its index in sync with the database?\n\n## Assignment\nDesign the full R-Learn system from scratch: API servers, databases (read replicas), Redis (sessions + cache), search (Elasticsearch), notification service, CDN, load balancer. Draw the complete architecture diagram.', 35, 1),

('l140901', 'm1409', 'System Design Interview Prep', E'# System Design Interview Preparation\n\n## Why This Topic Matters\nSystem design interviews determine senior engineering offers. Structured preparation over multiple practice sessions is what separates passing from failing.\n\n## Learning Objectives\n- Master the system design interview framework\n- Practice common system design questions\n- Know how to communicate trade-offs\n- Build confidence with timed practice\n\n## Core Concepts\n\n### The Framework (Repeat Until Automatic)\n```\n1. Clarify requirements (5 min)\n   "Before I start, let me clarify a few things..."\n   Functional requirements: What does it do?\n   Non-functional: Scale (DAU), latency, consistency, availability\n   Out of scope: What are we NOT building?\n\n2. Estimate scale (3-5 min)\n   "Let me estimate the scale to inform the design..."\n   DAU -> requests/sec\n   Storage per user -> total storage\n   Read:write ratio\n\n3. High-level API design (5 min)\n   Define 3-5 key API endpoints\n   Request and response shapes\n\n4. High-level system design (10 min)\n   Draw: client, LB, servers, cache, DB, queue\n   Explain data flow for the main use case\n\n5. Database schema (5 min)\n   Key tables and relationships\n   Indexes for main queries\n\n6. Deep dive (10 min)\n   Interviewer guides: "Tell me more about X"\n   Be ready: caching, scaling, consistency, failure modes\n\n7. Address bottlenecks (5 min)\n   "Given our scale, the bottleneck is..."\n   "We handle this by..."\n```\n\n### Common System Design Questions\n```\nBeginner:\n  URL shortener (bit.ly)\n  Pastebin\n  Rate limiter\n\nIntermediate:\n  Instagram / Photo sharing\n  Twitter timeline\n  Chat application (WhatsApp)\n  Design Dropbox / Google Drive\n  YouTube\n\nAdvanced:\n  Distributed message queue\n  Distributed cache\n  Search autocomplete\n  Ride sharing (Uber/Lyft)\n  Hotel reservation system\n```\n\n### Communication Tips\n```\nState assumptions:\n  "I will assume we have 10M DAU and need 99.9% availability"\n\nExplain trade-offs:\n  "I could use Redis here which gives us O(1) lookups but requires\n   additional infrastructure. Alternatively, we could use PostgreSQL\n   with an index which is simpler but has higher latency. Given our\n   100ms latency requirement, I will use Redis."\n\nHandle unfamiliar territory:\n  "I am not familiar with X, but I would approach it by..."\n  "That is a great point. How would you normally handle this?"\n\nDo not over-engineer:\n  "We could use Kafka here, but given the scale, BullMQ on Redis\n   is simpler and sufficient. We can migrate if we hit its limits."\n```\n\n### Practice Schedule (4 weeks)\n```\nWeek 1: Foundations\n  URL shortener, Pastebin, Rate limiter\n  Focus: Framework, estimation, API design\n\nWeek 2: Storage\n  Photo sharing, File storage, Metrics system\n  Focus: Database design, caching, storage choices\n\nWeek 3: Real-time & Scale\n  Chat app, Twitter timeline, Notification service\n  Focus: Message queues, pub/sub, fan-out\n\nWeek 4: Advanced\n  YouTube, Uber, Hotel reservations\n  Focus: Complex trade-offs, geography, consistency\n\nEach session:\n  45 minutes solo design\n  Review against published solution\n  Note gaps for next session\n```\n\n## Best Practices\n- Practice out loud (pretend you are presenting)\n- Time yourself -- 45 minutes per question\n- Study real architectures: Netflix tech blog, AWS re:Invent talks\n- Review your weak areas weekly\n\n## Interview Questions (Practice these)\n1. Design a real-time collaborative document editor (Google Docs)\n2. Design a distributed rate limiter\n3. Design the R-Learn platform from scratch for 1M users\n\n## Assignment\nConduct 3 timed system design sessions (45 min each): URL shortener, chat app, and a design of your choice. Record yourself, review against published solutions, document what you learned.', 30, 1)

